@node "Before You Begin"

Welcome to @{b}TurboText@{ub}, the most advanced text editor available for Amiga
computers. TurboText has been designed from the ground up to provide the
necessary tools to easily perform a varied range of sophisticated text
editing tasks.

Whether TurboText is used for educational, recreational, or professional
text editing, it offers Amiga users the highest level of performance and
ease of use available.

TurboText can be used out of the box and offers an impressive array of
capabilities. The more advanced users can customize the editing environment
to a high degree. Additional capabilities are available through @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"},
by using the vast collection of commands supported by TurboText's ARexx
interface.

TurboText has been thoroughly tested to insure it works correctly and
reliably. The software was run for several months on a wide range of
different hardware platforms with various peripherals, running many
different background software utilities. A strict quality assurance
process has been applied throughout the development stage to insure all
levels of the software operate properly.

	@{" System Requirements " link "System Requirements"}
	@{" Using This Manual   " link "Using This Manual"}
	@{" Acknowlegements     " link "Acknowlegements"}

@endnode


@node "System Requirements"

TurboText operates correctly on all members of the Amiga line of computers
with a minimum of 512K of memory and one disk drive.

At least Release 2.04 of the Amiga Kickstart and Workbench are required
for correct operation. Additional features are generally available when
using more recent versions. You can obtain updates to older operating
system versions by contacting your local Amiga dealer.

TurboText can be used with floppy-only systems, or more conveniently with
systems equipped with a hard disk.

@endnode


@node "Using This Manual"

This manual contains the tutorial and reference information necessary to
understand and use TurboText. Certain layout and style conventions are
used throughout the document to help convey information consistently and
with minimum confusion.

The special character @{b}[Return]@{ub} is implied at the end of every full command
line. If the line to be entered is too long to show on a single line in the
manual, the extra characters are shown on the following lines, and are
slightly indented.

A special notation is used to help describe key sequences (series of
characters entered at the keyboard). A key sequence consists of a single
character accompanied by an arbitrary number of key qualifiers. Key
qualifiers are keys like @{b}[Shift]@{ub} or @{b}[Alt]@{ub} which alter the meaning of other
keys. The possible key qualifiers are:

	@{b}[Shift]@{ub}		either Shift key

	@{b}[Left Shift]@{ub}	the left Shift key

	@{b}[Right Shift]@{ub}	the right Shift key

	@{b}[Alt]@{ub}		either Alt key

	@{b}[Left Alt]@{ub}	the left Alt key

	@{b}[Right Alt]@{ub}	the right Alt key

	@{b}[Ctrl]@{ub}		the Ctrl key

	@{b}[Amiga]@{ub}		either Amiga key

	@{b}[Left Amiga]@{ub}	the left Amiga key

	@{b}[Right Amiga]@{ub}	the right Amiga key

	@{b}[NumPad]@{ub}	for keys located on the numeric keypad

As mentioned, these qualifiers alter the meaning of other keys. For
example, pressing the "A" key by itself yields the letter "a", while
pressing the "A" key and at the same time holding down the Shift key
yields the letter "A". These would show up in this text as:

	@{b}A@{ub}

	@{b}[Shift]-A@{ub}

Keyboard sequences also need to describe keys which do not have simple
characters attached to them. For those keys, special names are used:

	@{b}[Backspace]@{ub}
	@{b}[CursorUp]@{ub}
	@{b}[CursorDown]@{ub}
	@{b}[CursorRight]@{ub}
	@{b}[CursorLeft]@{ub}
	@{b}[Del]@{ub}
	@{b}[End]@{ub}
	@{b}[Enter]@{ub}
	@{b}[Esc]@{ub}
	@{b}[F1]@{ub} through @{b}[F12]@{ub}
	@{b}[Help]@{ub}
	@{b}[Home]@{ub}
	@{b}[Insert]@{ub}
	@{b}[PageDown]@{ub}
	@{b}[PageUp]@{ub}
	@{b}[Return]@{ub}
	@{b}[SpaceBar]@{ub}
	@{b}[Tab]@{ub}

Here are some examples of keyboard sequences:

	@{b}[Ctrl]-A@{ub}		hold down the Ctrl key and press the "A" key

	@{b}[Shift]-[Del]@{ub}		hold down a Shift key and press the "DEL" key

	@{b}[Shift]-[Alt]-[F1]@{ub}	hold down a Shift and an Alt key and press
				the "F1" key

Menu commands, or menu choices, are referenced throughout this manual as
@{b}Menu/Item@{ub}, where "Menu" is the menu containing "Item". For example, "...
select @{b}Project/Save@{ub} ..." tells you to pull down the "Project" menu and
select the "Save" item from it.

