@node "Starting TurboText"

The TurboText program is started as a standard application from Workbench
or any available shell window. TTX is the name of the program to invoke
when you wish to use TurboText.

@{fg highlight}Starting TurboText from Workbench:@{fg text}

	1 - Find the TTX program icon.

	2 - Double-click on the icon.

@{fg highlight}Starting TurboText from Shell:@{fg text}

	1 - Open an AmigaDOS shell by double-clicking the Shell icon found
	    on the Workbench disk.

	2 - Type

		TTX

	    at a shell prompt.

	3 - Press @{b}[Return]@{ub}.

Once started, TurboText opens a window ready for editing.

@endnode


@node "The TurboText Document Window"

TurboText's document window is the medium through which all text entry and
editing takes place. The straightforward on-screen layout provides the
basic tools and information for all text editing applications.

The @{b}Close Gadget@{ub} found in the upper left of the document window closes the
current window. Confirmation is required if modifications have been made
since the document was last saved. Selecting this gadget is functionally
equivalent to the @{" Project/Close Window " link "The Project Menu"} menu command.

The @{b}Title Bar@{ub} displays the name of the document currently loaded. The title
bar can be selected using the left mouse button and is used to move the
window around the screen. The title bar is also where TurboText displays
error messages, and other status messages.

The @{b}Status Area@{ub} located on the right side of the title bar is used by
TurboText to present information about the current document. The
information displayed in the status area reads from left to right:

	F·i·m·o·r·w  10, 1, 1

@{fg highlight}Status flags:@{fg text}

	f/F  Free Form			  o/O  Overstrike
	i/I  Auto-Indent New Lines	  r/R  Read-Only
	m/M  Modified since last save     w/W  Word Wrap

The status flags indicate the state of various options. When a status flag
is in lower case, it means the option is currently off or false, and if the
flag is in upper case, then the option is on or true. The first two numbers
in the status area give the current cursor position within the document, in
@{b}column, line@{ub} order, while the third number indicates the total number of
lines in the current document.

A status line appearing as:

	F·I·m·o·r·W  24, 14, 110

would indicate that the cursor was at column 24 in line 14 of a 110-line
document which had not been modified since the last @{b}Save@{ub} was performed.
@{b}Free Form@{ub}, @{b}Auto-Indent New Lines@{ub} and @{b}Word Wrap@{ub} are on. @{b}Overstrike@{ub}, and
@{b}Read-Only@{ub} are turned off.

The @{b}Zoom Gadget@{ub} lets you turn the document window into a very small title
bar-sized window, which lets you easily put it out of the way. To restore
the original window, just click on the zoom gadget once again.

The @{b}Depth Gadget@{ub} lets you rearrange windows on your display.

The @{b}Scroll Gadget@{ub} lets you move easily through the current document. The
@{" scroll gadget " link "Using The Scroll Gadget"} consists of a scroll bar, and two scroll arrows.

The @{b}Sizing Gadget@{ub} lets you change the dimensions of the window.

The @{b}Display Area@{ub} is where the document being worked on is displayed.

The @{b}Cursor@{ub} indicates the current position within the loaded document. As
you type text into the editor, characters are inserted where the cursor
indicates.

@endnode


@node "Entering Text"

The most fundamental part of a text editor is its capability to let you
enter, modify, and remove text from documents; activities known
collectively as editing. TurboText has a very flexible editing
environment, providing a significant amount of functionality in a simple
and consistent framework.

Text can be inserted into a document by simply starting to type. The cursor
indicates where the text is to appear. This is identical to how you enter
text in a system text gadget. As characters are typed in, text that was
already present is moved automatically towards the right. Pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub}
breaks the current line and moves the cursor down to the next line in the
document.

After having typed in some text, you can move back over what you typed
using the cursor keys. You can also use the mouse to position the cursor
at a new location by clicking the left mouse button once while the mouse
pointer is over the location where you wish the cursor to be.

Text can be deleted using the @{b}[Del]@{ub} and @{b}[Backspace]@{ub} keys. @{b}[Del]@{ub} deletes the
character under the cursor, while @{b}[Backspace]@{ub} deletes the character to the
left of the cursor. Again, this is exactly like in text gadgets.

Besides deleting single characters, the @{b}[Del]@{ub} and @{b}[Backspace]@{ub} keys can be
combined with the @{b}[Shift]@{ub}, @{b}[Alt]@{ub} or @{b}[Ctrl]@{ub} keys to delete groups of
characters:

	@{b}[Del]@{ub}			Delete the character under the cursor

	@{b}[Backspace]@{ub}		Delete the character to the left of the cursor

	@{b}[Shift]-[Del]@{ub}		Delete to the end of the current word

	@{b}[Shift]-[Backspace]@{ub}	Delete to the start of the current word

	@{b}[Alt]-[Del]@{ub}		Delete to the end of the current line

	@{b}[Alt]-[Backspace]@{ub}	Delete to the start of the current line

	@{b}[Ctrl]-[Del]@{ub}		Delete the current line

@endnode


@node "Editing Modes"

TurboText has two basic editing modes: @{i}insert @{ui}and @{i}overstrike. @{ui}In insert
mode, all text entered with the keyboard is inserted at the cursor's
current position. Prior to inserting a character, the current text is
shifted to the right to make room for the new character. In overstrike
mode, the current text is not shifted and the new text simply overwrites
it.

To turn on overstrike mode, press @{b}[Ctrl]-O@{ub}. To come back to insert mode,
press @{b}[Ctrl]-O@{ub} again. The @{b}O@{ub} status flag located in the @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}
indicates whether overstrike mode is on: @{b}o@{ub} indicates it is off and the
editor is in insert mode, while @{b}O@{ub} indicates the editor is in overstrike
mode.

@{i}Automatic indentation @{ui}of new lines is a very useful feature for
programmers, as it avoids much useless and repetitive typing. When in
auto-indent mode, new lines created by pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub} are padded to the
left with the same number of spaces and tabs as the previous line. That is,
a new line created by pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub} is automatically aligned on the
left side with the previous line within the document.

To turn on auto-indent mode, press @{b}[Ctrl]-I@{ub}. To come back to normal mode,
press @{b}[Ctrl]-I@{ub} again. The @{b}I@{ub} status flag located in the status area
indicates whether auto-indent mode is on: @{b}i@{ub} indicates it is off and the
editor is in normal mode, while @{b}I@{ub} indicates the editor is in auto-indent
mode.

An extremely useful feature when writing any sort of text is @{i}word wrap,@{ui}
which is a feature typically found in word processors. When word wrap mode
is off, you must press the @{b}[Return]@{ub} or @{b}[Enter]@{ub} keys in order to start each
new line of text. When word wrap mode is on, TurboText automatically
creates new lines for you whenever the cursor reaches the @{" right margin " link "Preferences - Editing"}
If you are in the middle of entering a word when the cursor reaches the
right margin, the whole word is moved down to the following line so you can
finish entering it.

Although not generally used when writing programs, word wrapping can be
very useful when writing documentation or commenting program source code.

To turn on word wrap mode, press @{b}[Ctrl]-W@{ub}. To come back to normal mode,
press @{b}[Ctrl]-W@{ub} again. The @{b}W@{ub} status flag located in the status area
indicates whether word wrap mode is on: @{b}w@{ub} indicates it is off and the
editor is in normal mode, while @{b}W@{ub} indicates the editor is in word wrap
mode.

When wrapping text, TurboText always splits lines between words. There are
some groups of words however that should always appear next to each other
and should not span multiple lines. For example, someone's name such as
@{b}John Smith@{ub} should not span two lines. To avoid word wrapping moving such
words on separate lines, you must use the special keyboard sequence
@{b}[Alt]-[SpaceBar]@{ub} instead of the regular @{b}[SpaceBar]@{ub} between the two words.
The character inserted by @{b}[Alt]-[SpaceBar]@{ub} is known as a @{i}hard space.@{ui}

Hard spaces look just like regular spaces, the difference lies in how the
editor handles them. All features dealing with words consider two words
separated by a hard space as a single word. This is why two words
separated by a hard space are never split across lines, TurboText treats
the two words as a single word.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Some text processing tools, such as compilers, may not behave
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}correctly when there are hard spaces in the files they manipulate.

@{i}Free form @{ui}editing provides the ability to position the cursor anywhere on a
line, even if there is no text there, and start typing. When not in free
form mode, TurboText limits the position of the cursor to where text has
been previously typed. Free form mode lets you move the cursor beyond the
right edge of any line of text.

To turn on free form mode, press @{b}[Ctrl]-F@{ub}. To come back to normal mode,
press @{b}[Ctrl]-F@{ub} again. The @{b}F@{ub} status flag located in the status area
indicates whether free form mode is on: @{b}f@{ub} indicates it is off and the
editor is in normal mode, while @{b}F@{ub} indicates the editor is in free form
mode.

@endnode


@node "Cursor Positioning And Scrolling"

The ability to move quickly and position the cursor easily are basic
requirements of all text editors. TurboText's intuitive operation and
unparalleled rendering and scrolling speed eliminate much of the wasted
time spent while editing files.

Positioning the cursor and scrolling can be done in three ways:

	· from the @{" keyboard with the cursor keys " link "Cursor Positioning And Scrolling From The Keyboard"}

	· with the @{" mouse " link "Positioning The Cursor With The Mouse"}

	· with the @{" scroll gadget " link "Using The Scroll Gadget"}

@endnode


@node "Cursor Positioning And Scrolling From The Keyboard"

TurboText uses the Amiga keyboard's four directional (arrow or cursor) keys
to adjust the position of the cursor. Pressing one of these keys moves the
cursor one position in the direction indicated by the arrow. The @{b}[Shift]@{ub},
@{b}[Alt]@{ub}, and @{b}[Ctrl]@{ub} keys can be used in conjunction with the cursor keys to
move by different amounts and in different ways.

The following table details the cursor movement key sequences and their
functions:

	@{b}[CursorUp]@{ub}		Move the cursor up by one line

	@{b}[CursorDown]@{ub}		Move the cursor down by one line

	@{b}[CursorLeft]@{ub}		Move the cursor left by one character

	@{b}[CursorRight]@{ub}		Move the cursor right by one character

	@{b}[Shift]-[CursorUp]@{ub}	Move the cursor up by one screenful

	@{b}[Shift]-[CursorDown]@{ub}	Move the cursor down by one screenful

	@{b}[Shift]-[CursorLeft]@{ub}	Move to the start of the previous word

	@{b}[Shift]-[CursorRight]@{ub}	Move to the start of the next word

	@{b}[Alt]-[CursorUp]@{ub}	Move the cursor to the start of the document

	@{b}[Alt]-[CursorDown]@{ub}	Move the cursor to the end of the document

	@{b}[Alt]-[CursorLeft]@{ub}	Move the cursor to the start of the current
				line

	@{b}[Alt]-[CursorRight]@{ub}	Move the cursor to the end of the current
				line

	@{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorUp]@{ub}	Scroll the display up, while keeping the
				cursor on the same line in the document

	@{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorDown]@{ub}	Scroll the display down, while keeping the
				cursor on the same line in the document

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}If you ever forget the default keyboard sequences, a list of all
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}the sequences is always available by pressing @{b}[Help]@{ub}.

@endnode


@node "Positioning The Cursor With The Mouse"

You can point the mouse anywhere within the display area and click the
left button to cause the cursor to be positioned under the mouse pointer.
Holding down the left mouse button and moving the mouse around causes the
cursor to follow the mouse pointer until the mouse button is released.

You can also use the mouse for @{i}scrolling. @{ui}Scrolling is a term which
describes the up and down or left and right motion of text within the
display area. TurboText has extremely fast scrolling making for very
efficient editing. Using the mouse, you can scroll through a document at
varying speeds, from very slow, to blindingly fast.

@{fg highlight}To scroll using the mouse:@{fg text}

	1 - Press and hold the left mouse button while the mouse pointer is
	    over the text display area.

	2 - While holding down the left button, push the mouse pointer off
	    the top or bottom edges of the display area. This starts the
	    scrolling.

	3 - Release the left mouse button to stop scrolling.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Scrolling only occurs if the current document is larger than what
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}can fit within the display area.

The speed at which vertical scrolling occurs is directly related to the
horizontal position of the mouse pointer during scrolling. The fastest
scrolling speed can be attained by positioning the mouse at the extreme
left edge of the window, while progressively slower speeds are possible by
moving the mouse towards the right edge.

In addition to the variable speed control, there are also two different
scrolling @{i}gears. @{ui}When at the extreme left of the display area, switching to
the higher gear gives a bit of extra scrolling speed. The gears are
controlled by just how far the mouse is pushed off the top or bottom of the
display area.

A scroll operation using the mouse can be aborted at any time by clicking
the right mouse button. This turns off scrolling and positions the cursor
where it was before scrolling started.

@endnode


@node "Using The Scroll Gadget"

Each TurboText window has a vertical scroll bar and two scroll arrows that
can be used to move through a document.

The scroll bar consists of two parts; a vertical box representing the
document's total length, and a solid bar inside the box representing the
portion of that document being displayed in the window. A very small bar
means that few lines are being displayed in the window in comparison with
the total number of lines in the document. A bar that completely fills the
box means that the entire document is being displayed.

To scroll by one windowful, click above or below the bar within the scroll
box with the left mouse button. Clicking above the bar shifts the display
up one window, and clicking below shifts the display down an equal
distance.

By clicking the left mouse button over the solid bar, you can drag the bar
up or down, causing TurboText to shift the display to the corresponding
location in the document. That is, dragging the bar to the top of the box
brings you to the top of the document, and dragging to the bottom of the
box brings you to the bottom of the document.

Clicking the left mouse button over the arrow gadgets moves the display in
the indicated direction. Keeping the mouse button held down repeats the
operation automatically.

@endnode


@node "File Management"

TurboText provides several basic file management functions that allow
documents to be created, stored, loaded, and printed quickly and easily.

	@{" Loading An Existing File From Workbench        " link "Loading An Existing File From Workbench"}
	@{" Loading An Existing File From Shell            " link "Loading An Existing File From Shell"}
	@{" Loading An Existing File From Within TurboText " link "Loading An Existing File From Within TurboText"}
	@{" Loading An Existing File By Dropping Icons     " link "Loading An Existing File By Dropping Icons"}
	@{" Inserting A File In A Document                 " link "Inserting A File In A Document"}
	@{" Creating A New File                            " link "Creating A New File"}
	@{" Printing A File                                " link "Printing A File"}

@endnode


@node "Loading An Existing File From Workbench"

Any single file with a TurboText project icon can be loaded from Workbench
by using the mouse to double-click on the icon.

Multiple files can be selected for loading by shift-clicking their icons
in the standard manner, and double-clicking the TurboText icon. This
launches TurboText and loads each file in its own document window.

@{fg highlight}To load multiple files from Workbench:@{fg text}

	1 - Find the icons for the files to be opened.

	2 - Select the files to be loaded by shift-clicking their icons.
	    This means to hold down either @{b}[Shift]@{ub} key while you
	    click on the icons using the left mouse button.

	3 - After all files are selected, double-click the TTX icon
	    while still holding down @{b}[Shift]@{ub}.

After doing the above, each file selected will appear in its own document
window, ready to be edited.

If TurboText is already active in your system, you can also open new
document windows, and load existing files, by selecting the @{b}Tools/TurboText@{ub}
menu command in Workbench.

@{fg highlight}To load multiple files using the @{b}Tools/TurboText@{ub} menu:@{fg text}

	1 - Find the icons for the files to be opened.

	2 - Select the files to be loaded by shift-clicking their icons.
	    This means to hold down either @{b}[Shift]@{ub} key while you
	    click on the icons using the left mouse button.

	3 - After all files are selected, choose the @{b}Tools/TurboText@{ub}
	    menu command from Workbench.

If you choose the menu command without having previously selected any
icons, then an empty document window is created, ready for editing.

@endnode


@node "Loading An Existing File From Shell"

To load files from Shell, it is simply necessary to list all the files to
load immediately after the program's name. The format for the list of files
follows the standard AmigaDOS conventions. That is, all the names must be
separated with spaces, and if a given filename contains spaces, it must be
enclosed in double quotes. As well, standard AmigaDOS @{" patterns " link "AmigaDOS Pattern Matching"} can be
included in any of the filenames.

Each file specified on the command-line is loaded into its own individual
window. If TurboText is unable to load a specific file, a new empty
document window is opened with the filename as default document name. Type

	TTX @{i}<filename>@{ui}

where @{i}<filename> @{ui}is the name of the file to be loaded. Multiple filenames
may be specified by separating them with spaces. Filenames containing
spaces must be surrounded by double quotes.

A few examples will help clarify the various features available when
loading a file from Shell:

If TurboText is started from Shell by typing

	TTX test.c

the editor will try to load the file @{b}test.c@{ub} from the current directory. If
the file cannot be loaded, a new window is created with the name @{b}test.c@{ub}.

	TTX test1.c test2.c

would load the files @{b}test1.c@{ub} and @{b}test2.c@{ub} in two separate document windows.

If a filename contains spaces, the entire name must be surrounded by double
quotes. For example, to load a file called @{b}a test.c@{ub} you would need to
specify

	TTX "a test.c"

Finally, specifying @{" patterns " link "AmigaDOS Pattern Matching"} such as

	TTX #?.txt

causes all files matching the pattern to be loaded. In this case, all files
ending with @{b}.txt@{ub} would be loaded in separate document windows.

@endnode


@node "Loading An Existing File From Within TurboText"

Once a document window is opened, it is possible to replace the current
document by a file on disk. The current document is then discarded, and
the new file is displayed in its place.

@{fg highlight}To load an existing file from within TurboText:@{fg text}

	1 - Choose the @{" Project/Open... " link "The Project Menu"} menu command. If the current
	    document has been changed and these changes have not been saved,
	    a requester is opened to ask you to confirm the operation.

	2 - In the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} that appears, enter the name of the
	    drawer containing the file to load in the @{b}Drawer@{ub} gadget,
	    and enter the name of the file in the @{b}File@{ub} gadget.

	3 - Click the @{b}Open@{ub} gadget.

@endnode


@node "Loading An Existing File By Dropping Icons"

When TurboText is running on the Workbench screen, it is possible to
simply drag Workbench icons to a TurboText document window to cause the
associated files to be loaded for editing.

@{fg highlight}To load a document by dropping its icon:@{fg text}

        1 - Find the icon for the file you wish to open.

        2 - Find an opened TurboText document window.

	3 - Drag the icon of the file to the TurboText document window.

Once you drop the icon, the contents of the document window are replaced
with the contents of the file. You can also use multiple-selection to drop
multiple icons at once on a TurboText window. The first file in the group
will go in the document window, and new windows will be opened to hold the
other files.

@endnode


@node "Inserting A File In A Document"

Once a document window is opened, it is possible to insert the contents of
a file on disk within the current document. The insertion occurs at the
current cursor position.

@{fg highlight}To insert a file within a document:@{fg text}

	1 - Position the cursor at the location where you wish to insert the
	    contents of the file.

	1 - Choose the @{" Project/Insert... " link "The Project Menu"} menu command.

	2 - In the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} that appears, enter the name of the
	    drawer containing the file to insert in the @{b}Drawer@{ub} gadget,
	    and enter the name of the file in the @{b}File@{ub} gadget.

	3 - Click the @{b}Insert@{ub} gadget.

@endnode


@node "Creating A New File"

To create new files with TurboText, you type text in the editor and save
the result to a file on disk.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}The importance of regularly saving your work cannot be overstated.
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Should a system error or some other irregularity occur, all
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}modifications made to a document since it was last saved could be
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}lost.

@{fg highlight}To save a document to disk:@{fg text}

	1 - Choose the @{" Project/Save As... " link "The Project Menu"} menu command.

	2 - In the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"}, enter the name of the file in the
	    @{b}File@{ub} gadget.

	3 - Click the @{b}Save@{ub} gadget.

TurboText normally creates icons for the files it saves. These icons can
later be double-clicked from Workbench to invoke TurboText and load the
associated file automatically. Icon creation is controlled by the
@{b}Load And Save Project Icons@{ub} checkbox in the @{" Icons " link "Preferences - Icons"} section of the
preferences requester.

When TurboText saves a document to an existing file, it does not modify the
AmigaDOS protection bits for the file. The protection bits can be adjusted
through the Workbench's Information display, or by using the AmigaDOS
@{b}Protect@{ub} command from Shell. When saving a new file, TurboText clears the @{b}E@{ub}
(Execute) protection bit.

@endnode


@node "Printing A File"

The @{" Project/Print... " link "The Project Menu"} command sends the document in the active window to
the system printer. When printing is in progress, a small window is opened
that says @{b}Printing...@{ub}. Clicking that window's close gadget aborts the print
operation and resumes editing.

Documents are sent to the Amiga's printer as defined by Preferences. If
irregular or unexpected output is being produced, check to make sure that
the correct printer driver is selected for the attached hardware. Margins
and character width settings should be adjusted from within the system
Printer Preferences if printing wide files.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Some printers are not able to handle tab characters correctly
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Additional formatting problems may result from tabs if TurboText's
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}tab width setting is different than eight. The tab width can be
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}controlled using the @{b}Tab Width For Editing@{ub} numeric selector in the
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}@{" Tabs " link "Preferences - Tabs"} section of the preferences requester. Tab characters can be
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}removed and converted into spaces using the
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}@{" Extras/Convert Tabs To Spaces " link "The Extras Menu"} menu command.

The name of the printer used by TurboText can be defined using the
@{b}Print Device@{ub} text gadget in the @{" Miscellaneous " link "Preferences - Miscellaneous"} section of the preferences
requester. This gadget normally contains @{b}PRT:@{ub}, but you may wish to change
this in order to send the printout to a PostScript printer connected to
SER:, for example.

@endnode


@node "Selection Blocks"

@{i}Selecting @{ui}or @{i}highlighting @{ui}text means choosing one or more characters in a
given document. A variety of operations can be performed on selected blocks
of text such as centering and justification. Selected text can be cut or
copied from a document to the Amiga clipboard. Once inside the clipboard,
the text then becomes available to insert in other applications, other
TurboText documents, or back into the same document but at a different
location.

Selecting text is a process of @{i}marking @{ui}the start of the region to be
selected, and then moving the cursor to the end of the region, thereby
highlighting all the text between the two points. The highlighted region
follows the cursor until an operation is performed on the block, or the
block is deselected.

@{fg highlight}To select a block of text:@{fg text}

	1 - Position the cursor at the beginning of the text to be selected.

	2 - Mark its position with the mouse by moving the mouse pointer
	    over the cursor and double-clicking the left mouse button.

	    Or, as an alternative to double-clicking the mouse, choose the
	    @{" Edit/Mark " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command.

	    Once selection mode is started, the text cursor changes to a
	    stripped box, indicating the selection process.

	3 - Move the cursor to the end of the region of text to be selected.

A highlighted region of text can be deselected by clicking the right mouse
button once, or by choosing the @{" Edit/Mark " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command again.

	@{" Using The Clipboard       " link "Using The Clipboard"}
	@{" Block Operations          " link "Block Operations"}
	@{" Vertical Selection Blocks " link "Vertical Selection Blocks"}

@endnode


@node "Using The Clipboard"

Several operations can be performed on selected blocks of text. The most
important of these operations are those to copy the selected text to the
@{i}clipboard.@{ui}

The clipboard is a special region of memory shared by applications. Any
application can copy or @{i}post @{ui}information to the clipboard. Once on the
clipboard, the information can be retrieved by other applications, or by
the same application at a later time. Information on the clipboard is
referred to as a @{i}clip.@{ui}

For example, you can select a block of numbers in TurboText, copy them to
the clipboard, load a spreadsheet program and insert the contents of the
clipboard (your numbers) into the spreadsheet. The spreadsheet can then
manipulate the numbers, and post modified numbers back to the clipboard,
so they can be inserted back into TurboText.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Not all programs use the standard Amiga clipboard functions. For
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}this reason, transferring text between applications via the
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}clipboard may not always work.

@{fg highlight}To copy text to the clipboard:@{fg text}

	1 - Select a block of text.

	2 - Choose the @{" Edit/Copy " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command.

@{fg highlight}To insert the contents of the clipboard in the current document:@{fg text}

	1 - Position the cursor at the location where you wish to insert the
	    contents of the clipboard.

	2 - Choose the @{" Edit/Paste " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command.

Copying and pasting is not only useful for exchanging data between
different applications, but is also very useful for moving text around
within the same document. For example, you can select a paragraph of text,
copy it to the clipboard, and paste it back into the document at a
different location.

Once text is on the clipboard, it can be pasted any number of times. You
can continue to paste the same clip over and over, until some other data
is posted to the clipboard in its place. This is useful for creating
templates of repetitive information which can then be edited. Posting new
data to the clipboard erases what was previously there.

In addition to copying and pasting text, TurboText uses the clipboard for
a few other features.

When a block is selected, it is possible to @{i}cut @{ui}it to the clipboard. This
involves first copying the selected data to the clipboard and then removing
the original from the document. So @{b}cut@{ub} works exactly like @{b}copy@{ub} except that
as the data is copied to the clipboard, it is removed from the document.
Cutting is done by choosing the @{" Edit/Cut " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command instead of the
@{" Edit/Copy " link "The Edit Menu"} command.

It is possible to load a file directly into the clipboard. You can load a
file into the clipboard, and paste it into the current document at any
position, by choosing the @{" Edit/Open Clip... " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command, and selecting
the filename from the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"}.

Along the same lines, it is possible to save the current contents of the
clipboard to a file on disk. To save the current contents of the clipboard,
choose the @{" Edit/Save Clip As... " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command. The current contents of
the clipboard can also be sent to the system printer by choosing the
@{" Edit/Print Clip... " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command.

@endnode


@node "Block Operations"

Besides @{" clipboard-oriented " link "Using The Clipboard"} operations, selection blocks can be used to

	· erase text

	· center text

	· justify text

	· shift text sideways

	· convert selected characters to a different letter case

Erasing a block of text is done by choosing the @{" Edit/Erase " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}There is no way to recover erased text - be careful when using this
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}command.

Centering a block of text is performed by choosing the @{" Extras/Center " link "The Extras Menu"}
menu command. The text is centered between the left edge of the document
window and the current right margin. The right margin can be controlled
using the @{b}Right Margin@{ub} number gadget in the @{" Editing " link "Preferences - Editing"} section of the
preferences requester.

Justification is a process which inserts spaces between words so that both
ends of the line touch the margins. Paragraphs are then nice and square
instead of having a ragged right edge. Newspapers typically use
justification to obtain nice columns. Justification is performed by
choosing the @{" Extras/Justify " link "The Extras Menu"} menu command. Note that many people do not
like justified ASCII text, finding it distracting.

A selected block of text can also be shifted left or right for indentation
or formatting purposes, which is extremely useful for programmers.

@{fg highlight}To shift text:@{fg text}

	1 - Select the text to be shifted.

	2 - Press @{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorLeft]@{ub} to move the block to the
	    left, or @{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorRight]@{ub} to move it to the right.

All characters from a selected block can be converted to either upper or
lower case by choosing the @{" Extras/Convert To Upper Case " link "The Extras Menu"} or
@{" Extras/Convert To Lower Case " link "The Extras Menu"} menu commands.

All tab characters in a selected block can be converted to spaces by
choosing the @{" Extras/Convert Tabs To Spaces " link "The Extras Menu"} menu command.

@endnode


@node "Vertical Selection Blocks"

TurboText supports special vertical selection blocks that let you perform
the same operations as regular blocks, but on vertical columns of text
instead of on the entire document width.

@{fg highlight}To select a vertical block:@{fg text}

	1 - Position the cursor at the beginning of the text to be selected.

	2 - Mark its position by choosing the @{" Edit/Mark Vertical " link "The Edit Menu"} menu
	    command.

	3 - Move the cursor to the end of the text to be selected.

Vertical blocks can be copied, cut, shifted, and converted to upper or
lower case, just like normal blocks.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Attempting to center or justify a vertical block actually centers or
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}justifies the entire lines which the block spans, and not just the
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}block itself.

It is also possible to paste the current contents of the clipboard
vertically, so that the text on the clipboard is inserted as a column of
text instead of as a stream of continuous characters. To paste vertically,
choose the @{" Edit/Paste Vertical " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command instead of @{" Edit/Paste " link "The Edit Menu"}.

@endnode


@node "Finding And Changing Text"

When dealing with large documents, it is often desirable to search the
document for a specific text string, to move the cursor to a specific
line, or to move the cursor to the location where changes were last made.

To find a specific string of text within the current document, choose the
@{" Search/Find... " link "The Find Requester"} menu command, which causes the @{" Find " link "The Find Requester"} requester to be
opened. Entering the string to search for in the text gadget and pressing
@{b}[Return]@{ub}, starts the editor searching for the specified string, beginning
at the current cursor position.

If the string is found, the cursor is positioned on the start of the
string. If the string is not found, a message appears in the @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}
to that effect.

By adjusting options in the @{" Find " link "The Find Requester"} requester, it is possible to search
through the document in reverse direction, to have lower case letters match
upper case ones, as well as control a few other options.

Once a string has been specified in the Find requester, it can be searched
for multiple times by choosing the @{" Search/Find Next " link "The Search Menu"} menu command. This
allows you to find the next occurrence of the search string in the current
document. The find operation starts at the current cursor position.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Find operations do not find text which is directly under the
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}cursor. The search starts with the character following the character
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}under the cursor.

To move the cursor to a specific line within the document, choose the
@{" Search/Go To Line #... " link "The Search Menu"} menu command, and enter the line number in the
@{" requester " link "The Go To Line Requester"} that appears. Pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub} in this requester closes the
requester and moves the cursor to the requested line. Clicking the
requester's close gadget cancels the operation.

To move the cursor to a specific character within the document, choose the
@{" Search/Go To Char #... " link "The Search Menu"} menu command, and enter the character number in
the @{" requester " link "The Go To Line Requester"} that appears. Pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub} in this requester closes
the requester and moves the cursor to the requested character counting from
the beginning of the document. Clicking the requester's close gadget
cancels the operation.

It is possible to move the cursor to the position within the current
document where changes were last made by choosing the
@{" Search/Go To Last Change " link "The Search Menu"} menu command.

You can automatically move the cursor to the opening or closing bracket
which is mate to the one underneath the cursor. This is a very useful
feature for programmers.

@{fg highlight}To find a bracket's mate:@{fg text}

	1 - Position the cursor on a bracket. Brackets are any of

		( [ { < « » > } ] )

	2 - Choose the @{" Search/Match Bracket " link "The Search Menu"} menu command.

This moves the cursor to the matching bracket. That is, if the cursor is
currently on a @{b}{@{ub}, match bracket tries to move the cursor to a matching @{b}}@{ub}
farther down in the document. If no match is found, the cursor is left at
its current position. Note that this feature correctly handles nested
brackets, which are mated pairs of brackets between other brackets.

In combination with the Find feature presented above, the editor can also
perform text substitution for every text string found. That is, whenever a
string is found, it can be replaced automatically by another string. To use
this feature, choose the @{" Search/Find & Change... " link "The Search Menu"} menu command. This
brings up the @{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"} requester which allows you to enter the
string to search for, and the string to replace it with.

@endnode


@node "Preferences"

TurboText has a large array of user-adjustable features. The operation and
the look of the editor can easily be changed. The @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester
is where you adjust these options. This requester is opened by choosing the
@{" Prefs/Change... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu command.

TurboText can store all your current preferences settings in files on
disk. That way, when the editor is started up it can automatically use
your favorite settings instead of requiring you to adjust them every time
you use the program.

When TurboText is first started, it initializes itself to a predefined set
of preferences settings. Once this is done, it tries to find the file
@{b}TTX_Startup.prefs@{ub}. This file is a preferences file which is loaded and
becomes the new default preferences.

You can save the current preferences options to a file by choosing the
@{" Prefs/Save Prefs As... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu command and entering the name of the file in
the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} that appears. Once saved, the file can be retrieved
at any time by choosing the @{" Prefs/Open Prefs... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu command and
selecting a new preferences file from the file requester.

Finally, you can save the current preferences options as the default
options so the next time the editor is started, it uses these options
automatically. As well, any document windows opened after saving the
preferences as default use these preferences. To save the current
preferences as the default, choose the @{" Prefs/Save As Defaults " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu
command. The preferences are then saved to a file called @{b}TTX_Startup.prefs@{ub}
and are copied to the internal default preferences for future document
windows.

All the options controlled by the preferences requester are stored in the
preferences files. In addition to these options, there are a few more
items stored in the preferences files:

	· the position and dimension of the document window

	· the position of all requesters

	· the contents of the file requester's Pattern text gadget

	· the options in the @{" Find " link "The Find Requester"}, and @{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"} requesters

Storing the position and dimension of the document window in preferences
files means you can have your document windows always open at the position
and with the size you want.

@endnode


@node "On-Line Help"

TurboText supports sophisticated on-line hypertext help, using Commodore's
AmigaGuide technology.

When a document window is active, you can press the @{b}[Help]@{ub} key to obtain a
list of available keyboard commands, and other useful information.

You can also press the @{b}[Help]@{ub} key while the @{" Find " link "The Find Requester"} requester, the
@{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"} requester, or the @{" Preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester are active.
This will bring up information about the requester.

You can obtain help about any TurboText menu by displaying the menu of
interest, and pressing the @{b}[Help]@{ub} key. An AmigaGuide window will then open
and show information about the current menu.

@endnode







