@node "Multi-View Editing"

@{i}Views @{ui}are ways of keeping track of different cursor positions in a
document. TurboText maintains two distinct views on any loaded document.
Every view of a document has a different idea of what the current cursor
position is. The @{i}active view @{ui}is the view in which editing is being
performed.

Up to this point, we have dealt exclusively with TurboText's first document
view. In fact, TurboText maintains a second @{i}hidden view. @{ui}This hidden view
has its own current cursor position which is distinct from that used by the
active view. To see where the hidden view's cursor is, you need to make the
view active. This is done by choosing the @{" Windows/Views/Toggle " link "The Windows Menu"} menu
command. Choosing this command causes the hidden and active views to be
exchanged. That is, the hidden view becomes the active view, while the
active view becomes the hidden view.

Move the cursor in one view, then switch back to the other view - you will
find that the cursor position in the hidden view was not affected by the
movement in the active view. This is extremely useful when you need to
switch repeatedly between two sections of a document. You simply position
one view on the first section, and the second view on the second section.
You can then switch instantly from one section to the other by toggling
the active view.

It is also possible to show both views on screen at once by choosing the
@{" Windows/Views/Split " link "The Windows Menu"} menu command. Choosing this command splits the
document window in half, showing one view per half. The active view is the
one which has the cursor in it. Toggling the active view can still be done
using the @{" Windows/Views/Toggle " link "The Windows Menu"} menu command, or by simply clicking the
left mouse button in the desired portion of the document window.

When in split view mode, the views can be resized by dragging the
separation bar up or down using the mouse. This is done by clicking and
holding the left mouse button on top of the separation bar. While dragging
the bar, a click of the right mouse button cancels the resizing operation.
You can also resize the active view using the @{" Windows/Views/Expand " link "The WIndows Menu"} or
@{" Windows/Views/Shrink " link "The Windows Menu"} menu commands.

You can easily swap the contents of the two views by selecting the
@{" Windows/Views/Swap " link "The Windows Menu"} menu command. This will put the contents of the
bottom view in the top view, and vice-versa.

The cursor can be vertically centered within the current view by selecting
the @{" Windows/Views/Center " link "The Windows Menu"} menu command. This command scrolls the contents
of the view in order to position the cursor as close as possible to the
middle of the view. The actual position of the cursor within the document
is not changed, only its location on the screen.

You can fine-tune the vertical position of the cursor within the current
view by using the @{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorUp]@{ub} and @{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorDown]@{ub} keyboard
sequences. Pressing @{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorUp]@{ub} moves the cursor up one line in the
current view. The actual position of the cursor within the document is not
changed, only its position on the screen. @{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorDown]@{ub} move the
cursor down one line.

@endnode


@node "Bookmarks"

TurboText supports an infinite number of @{i}bookmarks@{ui}, ten of which are
available from the keyboard. TurboText bookmarks are very much like
real-world bookmarks in that they allow you to mark specific locations
within a document so you can easily find these locations at a later time.

Ten bookmarks are normally available through the TurboText menus. All the
other bookmarks can be used within @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros or in
@{" definition files " link "Definition Files"}.

Bookmarks are set by selecting a sub-item in the @{" Search/Set Bookmark " link "The Search Menu"}
menu. The sub-items are labelled @{b}#1@{ub} through @{b}#10@{ub}. Selecting one of these
menu commands sets a bookmark at the current cursor position. You can then
easily return to that position at a later time by selecting the appropriate
bookmark number from the @{" Search/Go To Bookmark " link "The Search Menu"} menu.

For example, to set a bookmark on the tenth line of a document, move the
cursor to line number @{b}10@{ub} and select the @{" Search/Set Bookmark/#1 " link "The Search Menu"} menu
command to set the bookmark. You can then move through the document, insert
and remove text, and at any time by selecting @{" Search/Go To Bookmark/#1 " link "The Search Menu"}
the cursor instantly moves back to line 10, at the exact position where you
originally set the bookmark.

Bookmarks apply to the current document only; loading a new document in
memory erases all bookmarks. Using special @{" icon commands " link "Icon Commands"}, TurboText is
capable of saving bookmarks with your documents. That way when the document
is reloaded, the same bookmarks it had when it was last saved become
available.

	@{" The Automatic Bookmark " link "The Automatic Bookmark"}

@endnode


@node "The Automatic Bookmark"

TurboText maintains a single automatic bookmark. This bookmark is set
whenever an action susceptible to move the cursor by a significant amount
occurs. This lets you instantly jump back to where the cursor was prior to
performing the action.

For example, executing a @{b}Find@{ub} operation causes the automatic bookmark to be
set to the current cursor position before doing the search. Once the search
operation is done, you can instantly jump back to the original cursor
position by selecting the @{" Search/Go To Auto-Bookmark " link "The Search Menu"} menu command.

The menu commands that set the automatic bookmark are:

	· @{" Edit/Paste               " link "The Edit Menu"}

	· @{" Edit/Paste Vertical      " link "The Edit Menu"}

	· @{" Search/Find...           " link "The Search Menu"}

	· @{" Search/Find Next         " link "The Search Menu"}

	· @{" Search/Find & Change...  " link "The Search Menu"}

	· @{" Search/Go To Line #...   " link "The Search Menu"}

	· @{" Search/Go To Char #...   " link "The Search Menu"}

	· @{" Search/Go To Last Change " link "The Search Menu"}

The following actions also set the automatic bookmark:

	· scrolling with the mouse

	· scrolling with the scroll gadget

	· jumping to a bookmark

	· moving to the start or end of the document using the keyboard

	· moving up and down by one windowful using the keyboard

Note that choosing @{" Search/Go To Auto-Bookmark " link "The Search Menu"} affects the automatic
bookmark itself. When executing this command, the cursor is moved to the
position indicated by the automatic bookmark, and the cursor position
before the movement becomes the automatic bookmark position. Thus using
this command, you can easily toggle the cursor position between two
locations within the document by executing this command every time you wish
to switch position.

@endnode


@node "Recorded Macros"

Many text editing tasks require a repetitive sequence of operations to be
performed. It often becomes quite tedious to do the same thing over and
over again. For example, to add a character at the end of every line in a
document would require you to move to the end of the current line, type
the character you need, go down to the next line, move to the end, type
the character, move to the next line, and so on.

Instead of performing such boring operations over and over yourself, you
can record a series of operations and have TurboText play it back for you
automatically. Such a recorded series of operations is known as a
@{i}recorded macro.@{ui}

To record a macro, choose the @{" Macros/Record Macro " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command. After
choosing the command, all menu and keyboard commands are recorded by
TurboText as you execute them. While you are recording, TurboText changes
the imagery of the mouse pointer to a tape cassette, to show that it is
recording. Once you have completed the series of operations you wish to
record, choose the @{" Macros/Stop Recording " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command.

Once a macro has been recorded, it can be replayed using the
@{" Macros/Play Macro " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command. Choosing this command executes the same
series of commands as you performed when recording the macro.

@{fg highlight}To record a macro to add a character at the end of every line:@{fg text}

	1 - Move the cursor to the start of the document by entering
	    @{b}[Alt]-[CursorUp]@{ub}.

	2 - Choose the @{" Macros/Record Macro " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command.

	3 - Move the cursor to the end of the line by entering
	    @{b}[Alt]-[CursorRight]@{ub}.

	4 - Type the character to be inserted, @{b}z@{ub} for example.

	5 - Move the cursor down to the next line by entering @{b}[CursorDown]@{ub}.

	5 - Choose the @{" Macros/Stop Recording " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command.

After these steps, the macro is recorded and ready to play by simply
choosing the @{" Macros/Play Macro " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command. Every time the macro is
played, the character you specified is inserted at the end of the current
line and the cursor is moved to the next line.

It is often necessary to repeat a recorded macro many times. Instead of
choosing the @{" Macros/Play Macro " link "The Macros Menu"} command many times, it is easier to
choose the @{" Macros/Play Many... " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command. Choosing this command
causes a @{" requester " link "The Play How Many Requester"} to be opened letting you specify the number of times
to repeat the macro.

Clicking the close gadget of the requester cancels the operation. A repeat
count of zero tells TurboText to repeat the macro until an error is
detected. Errors include, for example, when the end of the document is
reached. That way you can tell TurboText to repeat the current macro until
the end of the document is reached. Entering any other number repeats the
macro that many times, or until an error is encountered.

Recorded macros can be saved to disk by using the
@{" Macros/Save Macro As... " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command. To later play this macro, it first
needs to be reloaded in the editor using the @{" Macros/Open Macro... " link "The Macros Menu"} menu
command.

Recorded macros are saved in ASCII format, in a manner suitable to be run
as @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros. That is, a saved recorded macro can be run from ARexx,
or can be loaded as a recorded macro. However, the opposite is not true - a
general ARexx macro cannot be loaded as a recorded macro.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}The fact that recorded macros are saved as ARexx macros is very
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}handy. You can record a series of operations and use the resulting
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}ARexx macro as the basis for a more complex ARexx macro.

@endnode


@node "Automatic Saving"

TurboText has the ability to automatically save a document to disk at
timed intervals. This is a very useful feature to avoid loosing data due
to a power failure or other unforeseen circumstances.

Automatic saving occurs only if the document has been changed since it was
last saved. When auto-save mode is turned on, TurboText keeps track of the
elapsed time between saves. Should this time become equal to the auto-save
delay, TurboText automatically saves the document to disk.

Auto-save mode is controlled by the @{b}Auto-Save Documents@{ub} checkbox in the
@{" Automatic Saving " link "Preferences - Automatic Saving"} section of the preferences requester. In the same
section you can also specify the time in minutes between auto-saves by
adjusting the @{b}Minutes Between Auto-Save@{ub} slider. Finally, you can have
TurboText ask for confirmation before automatically saving a file. When the
@{b}Ask Before Auto-Saving@{ub} checkbox is set, a requester is opened every time
the auto-save interval expires, asking you if you really want to auto-save
the current document. If you cancel this requester, TurboText skips the
auto-save operation, and starts counting time until the next auto-save
operation.

Note that the auto-save confirmation requester does not have full keyboard
control like all other TurboText requesters do. Since this requester can
appear at any time during an editing session, keystrokes meant for the
document could easily be directed to the requester and cause problems. The
only keyboard sequences recognized by this requester are @{b}[Esc]@{ub} or
@{b}[Left Amiga]-B@{ub} to cancel the operation, and @{b}[Left Amiga]-V@{ub} to proceed with
the operation.

@endnode


@node "File Backups"

TurboText can be made to create @{i}backups @{ui}of files during save operations. A
backup is a very important safety measure. If you accidentally overwrite an
important file with incorrect data, you can always go and get the backup of
the original file. Without backup creation, you wouldn't have the original
anymore, and its contents would be lost.

Backup creation typically involves making a copy of a file on disk before
writing a new version of it. The copy is known as the backup file and
contains the data of the original file.

Turning on TurboText's backup mode is done by selecting the @{b}Create Backups
When Saving@{ub} checkbox in the @{" Backup Creation " link "Preferences - Backup Creation"} section of the preferences
requester.

TurboText supports a sophisticated method of creating file backups. You
specify a @{i}backup template @{ui}which describes how and where a backup is made.
The template is specified in the @{b}Backup Template@{ub} text gadget in the
preferences requester.

The backup template specifies a filename under which to create the backup
file. Some special characters can be included in the template to cause
special behavior. The @{b}*@{ub} symbol causes the current document name to be used,
and the @{b}#@{ub} symbol indicates that version numbering is to be used. Some
examples:

	Original Filename   Backup Template	Resulting Backup Filename

	test		    T:*.bak		T:test.bak
	test		    T:TTX.#		T:TTX.1,2,3,4,5,...
	test		    T:*.#		T:test.1,2,3,4,5,...

So simply put, whenever a @{b}*@{ub} is encountered, the current document name is
inserted in the backup template, and when a @{b}#@{ub} is encountered, a version
number is inserted. The version number is determined by the files already
existing on disk. The editor looks at the files on disk and saves the new
backup using a version number one greater than the highest numbered backup
file already on disk. The maximum version number is specified by the
@{b}Maximum Backup Version@{ub} slider in the preferences requester. When the
maximum version number is reached, the version numbering starts back at
zero.

@endnode


@node "Read-Only Mode"

TurboText lets you treat documents as read-only. That is, any attempt to
modify the contents of the document yields an error. This is a very handy
feature when you wish to load in documentation, or reference material and
wish to avoid accidental modifications.

Read-only mode is controlled using the @{" Project/Read-Only " link "The Project Menu"} menu command.
Selecting the menu item puts a checkmark next to the menu name, and enables
read-only mode. Selecting the item again then turns off the checkmark and
disables read-only mode.

The @{b}R@{ub} status flag located in the @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"} of the document window
indicates whether read-only mode is on: @{b}r@{ub} indicates it is off and the
document can be modified, while @{b}R@{ub} indicates the editor is in read-only
mode.

When TurboText loads a file from disk, it looks at the file's protection
bits. If the @{b}W@{ub} (Write) bit is not set, which means the file cannot be
written to, the document is automatically put into read-only mode after the
file is loaded.

@endnode


@node "Quote Mode"

TurboText uses many keyboard sequences as editor commands. For example,
@{b}[Ctrl]-O@{ub} toggles Overstrike mode on and off. It is sometimes necessary to
bypass the TurboText commands in order to insert a given control character
in a document. For example, if you actually wish to insert a CTRL-O
character (ASCII code 15).

In support of this, TurboText provides @{i}quote mode@{ui}. To activate quote mode,
you enter @{b}[Ctrl]-Q@{ub}. Once in quote mode, the next character sequence you
type will not be interpreted as a TurboText command, but will be inserted
in the document directly. Once a character sequence is entered, quote mode
is automatically turned off again.

@endnode


@node "Folds"

TurboText supports a unique concept known as @{i}folds @{ui}(sometimes referred to
as @{i}outlines@{ui}). Folding is a technique that hides parts of a document to make
it easier to handle. This is like folding up most of a large road map while
looking at one section of it.

A fold is composed of one or more lines which are removed from the current
document and put in a special hidden region of memory. The first line of a
fold remains on screen and has a little symbol put in front of it to show
there is a fold starting at that line.

The contents of a fold can be shown easily. When displayed, the contents
have a line drawn on the extreme left of the document window to show they
are part of a fold. A displayed fold can be hidden again easily.

Folds are a very useful tool for programmers. Entire routines can be
collapsed so that only the first line of each routine is visible on
screen. When you need to see or modify the contents of a given routine,
you simply show the fold and type away. When done, the routine can be
hidden back. This helps make large source files much more manageable.

Folds can be created in one of two ways. The first method involves
selecting a block of text, and choosing the @{" Folds/Make Fold " link "The Folds Menu"} menu
command. This collapses all selected lines into the fold. The first line of
the fold remains displayed in its original location within the document and
is preceded with a special symbol to indicate that a fold is attached to
that line.

The second way to create folds is more convenient for programmers. When no
block is selected, choosing the @{" Folds/Make Fold " link "The Folds Menu"} menu command causes
TurboText to fold away all lines following the current line, until a line
with equal or less indentation level is encountered.

For example, positioning the cursor on the word @{b}while@{ub} in the line below:

	while (x < 2) {
	    x++;
	    if (x == 1)
	    {
	        y--;
            }
	}

and choosing the @{" Folds/Make Fold " link "The Folds Menu"} menu command causes the entire while
loop to be collapsed so only the first line is shown. This is extremely
convenient when developing software, or when writing documentation. The
on-screen result looks like:

»	while (x < 2) {
	}

The @{i}fold marker @{ui}(the @{b}»@{ub} symbol) at the start of the line indicates that
there is a fold attached to the current line.

Once a fold is created, it can be displayed using the @{" Folds/Show/Single " link "The Folds Menu"}
menu command. All that is needed is to position the cursor on the first
line of the fold and to choose the menu command. When a fold is displayed,
it can be hidden again by positioning the cursor on any line of the fold,
and choosing the @{" Folds/Hide/Single " link "The Folds Menu"} menu command. When a fold is
revealed, a @{i}fold line @{ui}appears on the left of the display, next to the text
belonging in the fold.

A fold can also be displayed by just clicking the left mouse button while
the mouse pointer is over the fold marker. As well, once a fold is
displayed, it can be hidden by clicking the left mouse button while the
mouse pointer is anywhere over the fold line to the left of the document
window.

Folds can be removed by positioning the cursor on the first line of a
hidden fold, or on any line of a displayed fold, and choosing the
@{" Folds/Unmake/Single " link "The Folds Menu"} menu command.

It is possible to have folds within folds. This is known as @{i}fold nesting.@{ui}
The @{" Folds " link "The Folds Menu"} menu contains commands to show all nested folds, to hide all
nested folds, and to unmake all nested folds. The @{" Folds " link "The Folds Menu"} menu also has
commands to let you show, hide, and unmake all the folds in the current
document.

It can sometimes be difficult to spot fold markers and fold lines within a
busy document. The @{b}Fold Spacing@{ub} radio buttons in the @{" Folds " link "Preferences - Folds"} section of
the preferences requester let you specify a certain number of characters by
which to offset all text displayed by the editor towards the right.
Offsetting text in this way leaves room on the left for fold markers and
fold lines. If you do not use folds, leave this option set to 0 in order to
maximize the number of characters visible per line. If you use folds,
setting this value to 1 or 2 can be helpful. An alternative is the @{b}Dynamic@{ub}
option, which causes TurboText to provide always enough fold spacing to
make room for the most deeply nested fold.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}The information describing where in a document to put folds is not
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}saved with the document to disk. This is not possible since
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}TurboText deals with straight ASCII text files. Instead, the fold
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}information is stored in the document's icon using special
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}@{" icon commands " link "Icon Commands"}.

@endnode


@node "Icon Commands"

TurboText normally creates icons for files it saves. Icon saving can be
controlled using the @{b}Load And Save Project Icons@{ub} checkbox in the @{" Icons " link "Preferences - Icons"}
section of the preferences requester.

Icons allow you to see the saved files from Workbench. These icons can be
double-clicked to start TurboText and automatically load the associated
files.

In addition to the above, TurboText makes special use of document icons.
When saving an icon, TurboText attaches information to it describing where
are the @{" folds " link "Folds"} within the current document, where are the @{" bookmarks " link "Bookmarks"},
where the last change was made, and the @{" tab width " link "Preferences - Tabs"} used with the
document. If icons are not saved with documents, this information cannot be
saved either.

When loading a document, TurboText reads the icon associated with the
document to obtain the extra information it attached to the icon. If the
@{b}Load And Save Project Icons@{ub} option is turned off, TurboText does not read
in the icon, and thus cannot load the document's fold and bookmark
information.

To clarify, the @{" fold " link "Folds"} information that is saved in icons is not the
contents of folds, but only a series of line numbers indicating where the
folds are located within the current document. That means that if the icon
is not loaded, all that is different is that the folds are not recreated
automatically. All the document text is still there, just not folded like
it was originally.

@endnode


@node "Editing Binary Files"

One of TurboText's unique features is its @{i}hexadecimal @{ui}editing capabilities.
Hexadecimal is a way to count using base 16 instead of the usual base 10.
Digits go from 0 to 9, and then from A to F. Hexadecimal is often used by
programmers, and is very useful to inspect binary files. If you are not a
programmer or do not know hexadecimal, we suggest you skip this section.

Choosing the @{" Windows/Open Hex View... " link "The Windows Menu"} menu command opens the Hexadecimal
editing window. This window shows the contents of the current view in an
alternate form.

The format of the information displayed is identical to what the AmigaDOS
@{b}Type@{ub} command displays when invoked with the @{b}HEX@{ub} option. That is, the first
column shows the offset in bytes within the document, the middle section
shows the hexadecimal code for every character in the document, and the
right section shows the ASCII characters themselves.

Cursor movement within the Hex editing window is done using the cursor
keys as in the main document window. When moving the cursor in the Hex
editing window, the cursor of the main document window is also moved, and
vice-versa.

Editing is restricted in the Hex window to entering hexadecimal codes. That
means keys @{b}0@{ub} through @{b}9@{ub}, and @{b}A@{ub} through @{b}F@{ub} can be used to type new hexadecimal
codes to replace the existing codes. All editing in the Hex window is done
in overstrike mode.

To close the Hex window, click the window's close gadget or press @{b}[Esc]@{ub}.

The hexadecimal editing feature is very useful when you wish to edit
binary files. TurboText loads such files without complaining, although the
resulting document is generally unreadable, except when viewed through the
Hex editing window.

If you wish to edit binary files, it is generally important to be very
careful about what is being changed. TurboText has many options which
automatically modify a document as it is being loaded or saved. When
editing binary files, these options should be set in such a way to avoid
these automatic modifications. To aid you in this process, TurboText
provides the @{b}Auto-Detect Binary Files@{ub} option in the @{" Miscellaneous " link "Preferences - Miscellaneous"}
section of the preferences requester. Turning this option on causes
TurboText to inspect files as they are being loaded to see if they are
regular text files, or binary files. If a binary file is detected, the
following actions are taken:

   @{b}Remove Trailing Spaces When Saving@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Convert CR+LF/CR To LF When Loading@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Auto-Correct Word Case@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Free Form@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Word Wrap@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Save End Of Lines As@{ub} is set to @{b}LF@{ub}
   @{b}Tab Conversion@{ub} on loading and saving is set to @{b}None@{ub}
   @{b}Tab Width For Files@{ub} is set to match the value of
     @{b}Tab Width For Editing@{ub}

@endnode


@node "Word Correction"

TurboText has two sophisticated features which aid you to avoid errors as
you type text in the editor. The @{i}word correction @{ui}feature lets you easily
correct the spelling of a word by hitting a single key. The @{i}case correction@{ui}
feature watches as you type words in and changes the letter case of certain
words to match the letter case you specified in a dictionary. This last
feature is very useful for many programming languages.

Both the word correction and case correction features require a dictionary
of words to work with. In fact, both features share the same dictionary.
This dictionary is specified in the special TurboText @{" definition files " link "Definition Files"}.

The best way to understand how the correction features work is by example.
From within the editor, choose the @{" Prefs/Open Definitions... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu
command, and select the file @{b}TTX_M2.dfn@{ub} from the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} that
appears. This file contains a dictionary providing words useful for
Modula-2 programmers.

With the dictionary loaded, move the cursor to an empty line within the
editor, and type the word @{b}moduule@{ub}. This word obviously has an error, the
extra @{b}u@{ub}. To correct the error, simply move the cursor on top of the word
and press @{b}[F1]@{ub}. The word is then corrected and converted automatically to
upper case, becoming @{b}MODULE@{ub}.

TurboText uses a best-fit algorithm to choose the correct spelling and make
its corrections. If TurboText is unsuccessful in its search for a
replacement word, an error message is displayed in the @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. The
word correction feature cannot function if the first letter of the word is
wrong, if the word is too badly misspelled, or simply if the word is not in
the current dictionary.

For the next example, you need to make sure the @{b}Auto-Correct Word Case@{ub}
option is turned on by entering @{b}[Ctrl]-C@{ub}. Once the option is turned on,
move the cursor to an empty line within the editor and type the word
@{b}procedure@{ub} followed by a space. As soon as the space character is entered,
the word is converted to @{b}PROCEDURE@{ub}.

Certain programming languages, such as Modula-2, infer meaning to the
letter case of words. That is, @{b}hello@{ub} does not mean the same thing as @{b}HELLO@{ub}.
Case correction is an extremely useful feature for those languages, as it
converts words to the correct letter case automatically as they are
typed-in.

By creating @{" definition files " link "Definition Files"}, you can build your own dictionaries for
your particular applications.

@endnode


@node "Templates"

@{i}Template completion @{ui}is a feature designed to increase productivity while
reducing the chances of making errors. Template completion lets you type
the first few characters of a template, press @{b}[F2]@{ub}, and let TurboText
expand the few characters you typed into a complete multi-line template.

In the same way @{" word and case correction " link "Word Correction"} require a dictionary, template
completion requires a template list. And as the dictionaries, the template
lists are located in @{" definition files " link "Definition Files"}.

It is simpler to demonstrate this feature by example. You first need to
load a template list in the editor using the @{" Prefs/Open Definitions... " link "The Prefs Menu"}
menu command. From the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} that appears, select the
@{b}TTX_M2.dfn@{ub} file.

To see the template completion in action, move the cursor to an empty line
in TurboText and type the letters @{b}pr@{ub} and press @{b}[F2]@{ub}. The result is
something similar to:

	PROCEDURE ();
	VAR

	BEGIN

	END ;

with the cursor positioned on the open parenthesis. The few letters you
initially typed in have thus been expanded into a multi-line, ready to
fill in template.

When you press @{b}[F2]@{ub}, TurboText automatically finishes the incomplete word
under or to the left of the cursor. TurboText first analyzes the letters of
the word and finds the appropriate match from the template list. You must
type enough letters to distinguish the intended template from any other
template with similar spelling that may also be in the list.

If no matches are found for a template. an error message explaining the
situation is displayed in the @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. If more than one template is
matched by the letters you entered, you also get an error message. It is
then just necessary to enter more characters to help distinguish between
the templates.

Although the example given above deals with a Modula-2 programming language
construct, the template completion feature has many different uses. Instead
of complete multi-line templates, you can provide single word templates for
commonly used words. That way instead of typing @{b}anticonstitutional@{ub}, you
could just type @{b}an@{ub} and press @{b}[F2]@{ub} to have the editor complete it for you.
Templates are also useful for pieces of text, such as document headings,
which are used over and over again.

By creating @{" definition files " link "Definition Files"}, you can build your own template lists for
your particular applications.

@endnode


@node "Public Screens"

When TurboText is not running on the Workbench screen and instead has its
own screen opened, this screen is a @{i}public screen. @{ui}This means that other
programs can open windows on this screen. The name of TurboText's public
screen is, surprisingly enough, "TURBOTEXT".

The CON: window handler has the ability to open its windows on public
screens, which is very handy since it allows CON: windows to open on the
editor's screen. For example, executing the following command from Shell
causes an AmigaDOS shell window to be opened on the editor's screen:

	NewShell "CON:0/0/640/200/AmigaShell/SCREEN TURBOTEXT"

TurboText also has the ability to open its document windows on other public
screen. Workbench is an example of a public screen. The PUBSCREEN option
available when starting TurboText from the shell lets you specify the name
of the public screen to open the document windows on. In addition, the
@{" Window And Screen " link "Preferences - Window And Screen"} section of the preferences requester has some controls
to let you pick from within a list of available public screens.

@endnode







@remark **********************************************************************
@remark **********************************************************************







@node "Startup Options"

TurboText has many options that can be specified when the program is
launched.

A normal editing session involves starting the editor, editing a document,
and quitting the editor. The next time you wish to edit a document, the
editor must be reloaded from disk. TurboText's special background
operation mode eliminates excessive disk access by forcing TurboText to
remain in memory even though no documents are being worked on.

When running in background mode, TurboText can be invoked by using special
@{i}hot keys. @{ui}One of TurboText's important features is its ability to be used
for spot, or impulse editing. Through @{" hot keys " link "Hot Key Sequences"} you can open document
windows, and perform various other operations, at any time, from within any
application. This is an extremely convenient feature.

Startup options exist to start TurboText in the background without opening
a default window, to force it to open its windows on specific public
screens, to load files using patterns, and more.

	@{" Startup Files     " link "Startup Files"}
	@{" Workbench Options " link "Workbench Options"}
	@{" Shell Options     " link "Shell Options"}
	@{" Startup Macros    " link "Startup Macros"}
	@{" Examples          " link "Examples"}

@endnode


@node "Startup Files"

When TurboText is first loaded in memory, it attempts to load two files
from disk to initialize itself: @{b}TTX_Startup.prefs@{ub} which contains the
default preferences, and @{b}TTX_Startup.dfn@{ub} which contains the default
definitions for menu and keyboard assignments.

After the editor has been loaded, it is possible to load in new preferences
options using the @{" Prefs/Open Prefs... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu command, and to load new menu
and keyboard definitions using the @{" Prefs/Open Definitions... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu
command.

@endnode


@node "Workbench Options"

To start TurboText from Workbench, you need only double-click the program
icon. When running from Workbench, TurboText supports what are known as
Workbench @{i}Tool Types. @{ui}Tool Types are special keywords and options included
in an icon which control the behavior of an application. TurboText
understands several Tool Types, and these are specified and adjusted
through the standard Workbench Information window.

@{fg highlight}To create a Tool Type:@{fg text}

	1 - From Workbench, select the TTX icon by clicking on it once with
	    the left mouse button.

	2 - Choose the @{b}Icons/Information...@{ub} menu command.

	3 - Select the @{b}New@{ub} gadget. This causes a cursor to appear
	    in the text gadget.

	4 - Type in the new Tool Type, and press @{b}[Return]@{ub}.

	5 - Select the @{b}Save@{ub} gadget to save the new Tool Type.

@{fg highlight}To modify a Tool Type:@{fg text}

	1 - Select the TTX icon by clicking on it once with the left
	    mouse button.

	2 - Choose the @{b}Icons/Information...@{ub} menu command.

	3 - Select the Tool Type you want to modify from the scroll area.

	4 - Edit the text in the text gadget to make the modifications you
	    want.

	5 - Select the @{b}Save@{ub} gadget to save the modified Tool Type.

@{fg highlight}To remove a Tool Type:@{fg text}

	1 - Select the TTX icon by clicking on it once with the left
	    mouse button.

	2 - Choose the @{b}Icons/Information...@{ub} menu command.

	3 - Select the Tool Type you want to remove from the scroll area.

	4 - Select the @{b}Del@{ub} gadget.

	5 - Select the @{b}Save@{ub} gadget to save the change.

Refer to your Amiga's documentation for more information on how to
manipulate Tool Types.

	@{" TurboText Tool Types " link "TurboText Tool Types"}

@endnode


@node "TurboText Tool Types"

TurboText supports the following Tool Types:

@{b}STARTUP@{ub} lets you specify an ARexx macro to execute when this icon is
selected. The format for this Tool Type is:

	STARTUP=@{i}<macro name>@{ui}

For example:

	STARTUP=CleanUp

would cause the ARexx macro @{b}CleanUp@{ub} to be executed after the document
window is first opened.

@{b}SETTINGS@{ub} lets you specify the name of a TurboText preferences file to load
in when this icon is selected. The format for this Tool Type is:

	SETTINGS=@{i}<prefs file name>@{ui}

For example:

	SETTINGS=TurboText:Support/TTX_CPrefs.prefs

would cause the @{b}TTX_CPrefs.prefs@{ub} preferences file to be loaded before the
document window is first opened.

@{b}DEFINITIONS@{ub} lets you specify the name of a TurboText @{" definition file " link "Definition Files"} to
load in when this icon is selected. The format for this Tool Type is:

	DEFINITIONS=@{i}<definition file name>@{ui}

For example:

	DEFINITIONS=TurboText:Support/TTX_Emul_MEMACS.dfn

would cause the @{b}TTX_Emul_MEMACS.dfn@{ub} definition file to be loaded before the
document window is first opened.

@{b}BACKGROUND@{ub} tells TurboText you would like it to stay loaded even if there
are no document windows opened. That means TurboText stays in the
background, waiting until you invoke it using the special hot key
sequences. You only need to specify this Tool Type by itself to enable
background mode.

@{b}UNLOAD@{ub} reverses the effect of a previous @{b}BACKGROUND@{ub} Tool Type. That is,
when TurboText is running in background mode and receives an @{b}UNLOAD@{ub} Tool
Type, it unloads itself from memory the next time all document windows are
closed. Like the @{b}BACKGROUND@{ub} Tool Type, the @{b}UNLOAD@{ub} Tool Type need only be
specified by itself to be recognized.

@{b}NOWINDOW@{ub} is useful in combination with the @{b}BACKGROUND@{ub} Tool Type. It tells
TurboText not to open a window when it is started. Used in combination with
the @{b}BACKGROUND@{ub} Tool Type, it will load the editor in the background without
opening a default window.

@{b}WINDOW@{ub} lets you specify the type and dimension of the document windows
opened when clicking on this icon. The format for this Tool Type is:

	WINDOW=<left/top/width/height/iconified left/iconified top/ICONIFIED/
		CLOSED>

where:

  @{b}left/top/width/height@{ub} indicate the initial position and size of the
  document window that will be created.

  @{b}iconified left/iconified top@{ub} indicate the initial position of the
  iconified version of the document window.

  @{b}ICONIFIED@{ub} indicates that the document window should be initially opened
  in the iconified state. The window can then be de-iconified by clicking
  the @{" zoom gadget " link "The TurboText Document Window"} of the window.

  @{b}CLOSED@{ub} indicates that the document should be loaded, but no document
  window should be opened for it. The document window can be opened at a
  later time using the @{" ControlWindow " link "ControlWindow"} command.

All of the parameters to the @{b}WINDOW@{ub} Tool Type are optional. The current
default value is used for any missing parameter. For example:

	WINDOW=//200/300

means to use the current default left and top values, and to force a size
of 200x300.

@{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} lets you specify the name of the @{" public screen " link "Public Screens"} TurboText
should open its windows on. The format for this Tool Type is:

	PUBSCREEN=@{i}<public screen name> @{ui}

For example:

	PUBSCREEN=WizPaint

would cause the editor to open a window on the WizPaint public screen, or
fall back to the Workbench screen if the WizPaint screen doesn't exist.

TurboText can easily be used in the @{b}WBStartup@{ub} drawer. The ideal setup is to
copy the TTX program into the WBStartup drawer, and set the @{b}BACKGROUND@{ub} and
@{b}NOWINDOW@{ub} Tool Types. That way, TurboText will automatically be started
every time you turn on the computer, and will be available at all times by
entering a few simple keystrokes.

@{fg highlight}To automatically start TurboText upon every reboot:@{fg text}

	1 - From Workbench, Select the icon for the TTX program by clicking on
	    it once with the left mouse button.

	2 - Choose the @{b}Icons/Copy@{ub} menu command in Workbench.

	3 - Drag the @{b}Copy_Of_TTX@{ub} icon that was created in the previous step
	    to the system's WBStartup drawer.

	4 - Open the WBStartup drawer by double-clicking its icon.

	5 - Select the @{b}Copy_Of_TTX@{ub} icon by clicking on it once using the
	    left mouse button.

	6 - Select the @{b}Icons/Rename...@{ub} menu command, and remove the
	    "Copy_Of_" part in front of the program's name.

	7 - Add the @{b}BACKGROUND@{ub} and @{b}NOWINDOW@{ub} Tool Types to the TTX icon
	    in the WBStartup drawer.

With the above steps complete, TurboText will load in the background in
your system after every reboot. You can then quickly open a document window
by using a @{" hot key " link "Hot Key Sequences"} sequence such as @{b}[Ctrl]-[Alt]-W@{ub}.

As with normal Amiga applications, it is possible to invoke TurboText by
double-clicking on its project icons. That is, double-clicking on icons
created by TurboText. When this is done, the Tool Types of the project
icons override those found in the TTX icon.

@endnode


@node "Shell Options"

To start TurboText from Shell, you need only type @{b}TTX@{ub} and press @{b}[Return]@{ub}.
Several options can be provided using the standard AmigaDOS parameter
passing conventions.

The format for the parameters that can be passed to TTX is:

	TTX {files} [STARTUP @{i}<macro name>@{ui}] [WINDOW @{i}<window description>@{ui}]
	    [PUBSCREEN @{i}<public screen name>@{ui}]
	    [SETTINGS @{i}<prefs file name>@{ui}]
	    [DEFINITIONS @{i}<definition file name>@{ui}]
	    [NOWINDOW] [BACKGROUND] [WAIT] [UNLOAD]

The template for these parameters is:

	FILES/M,STARTUP/K,WINDOW/K,PUBSCREEN/K,SETTINGS/K,DEFINITIONS/K,
	NOWINDOW/S,WAIT/S,BACKGROUND/S,UNLOAD/S

@{b}FILES/M@{ub} lets you specify files TurboText should open. A separate document
window is created for every file specified.

@{b}STARTUP/K@{ub} lets you provide the name of an ARexx macro to run for every
document created as a result of this command. That is, if you specify five
different files to open using the @{b}FILES@{ub} parameter, every one of those files
will have its own document window, and the specified macro will be run for
every such window.

@{b}WINDOW/K@{ub} lets you specify the type and dimension of the document windows
opened when clicking on this icon. The format for this keyword is:

	WINDOW=<left/top/width/height/iconified left/iconified top/ICONIFIED/
		CLOSED>

where:

  @{b}left/top/width/height@{ub} indicate the initial position and size of the
  document window that will be created.

  @{b}iconified left/iconified@{ub} top indicate the initial position of the
  iconified version of the document window.

  @{b}ICONIFIED@{ub} indicates that the document window should be initially opened
  in the iconified state. The window can then be de-iconified by clicking
  the @{" zoom gadget " link "The TurboText Document Window"} of the window.

  @{b}CLOSED@{ub} indicates that the document should be loaded, but no document
  window should be opened for it. The document window can be opened at a
  later time using the @{" ControlWindow " link "ControlWindow"} command.

All of the parameters to the @{b}WINDOW@{ub} keyword are optional. The current
default value is used for any missing parameter. For example:

	WINDOW=//200/300

means to use the current default left and top values, and to force a size
of 200x300.

@{b}PUBSCREEN/K@{ub} lets you specify the name of the @{" public screen " link "Public Screens"} TurboText
should open its windows on.

@{b}SETTINGS@{ub} lets you specify the name of a TurboText preferences file to load
in for each document window that is created.

@{b}DEFINITIONS@{ub} lets you specify the name of a TurboText @{" definition file " link "Definition Files"} to
load in for each document window that is created.

@{b}NOWINDOW/S@{ub} tells TurboText not to open its default window when it starts
up. When no @{b}FILES@{ub} parameter is given, TurboText normally opens a default
document window. The @{b}NOWINDOW@{ub} option is very useful in combination with the
@{b}BACKGROUND@{ub} option, discussed in the @{" Examples " link "Examples"} section, to start the
editor in the background in your user-startup.

@{b}WAIT/S@{ub} - after you invoke TurboText from Shell, the shell prompt normally
returns immediately, allowing you to type more shell commands. When using
the editor from within AmigaDOS scripts, as well as some other special
applications, it is imperative that TurboText does not exit until the
documents being edited are unloaded. Specifying this option causes
TurboText to wait until all document windows opened by this invocation are
closed, before returning control to the shell.

@{b}BACKGROUND/S@{ub} tells TurboText you would like it to stay loaded even if there
are no document windows opened. That means TurboText stays in the
background, waiting until you invoke it using the special @{" hot key " link "Hot Key Sequences"}
sequences.

@{b}UNLOAD/S@{ub} reverses the effect of a previous @{b}BACKGROUND@{ub} option. That is, when
TurboText is running in background mode and receives the @{b}UNLOAD@{ub} option,
that tells it to unload itself from memory the next time all document
windows are closed.

	@{" Filenames " link "Filenames"}

@endnode


@node "Filenames"

The @{b}FILES@{ub} command-line parameter lets you specify files to open in the
editor. Two special features are supported for filenames.

Filenames may contain AmigaDOS patterns. In such a case, all files
matching the pattern are opened. For example:

	TTX #?.c

looks for files ending in @{b}.c@{ub} and opens any that match. See the
@{" AmigaDOS Pattern Matching " link "AmigaDOS Pattern Matching"} section for more information on pattern
matching.

The second special feature is the ability to specify the name of a drawer
instead of a file. In such a case, TurboText simply uses the specified
drawer as its default drawer in the file requester.

Note that if you wish to specify a filename which contains a space, the
entire name must be enclosed in double quotes. For example, to load a file
called @{b}Hello World@{ub}, you must enter:

	TTX "Hello World"

When multiple files are specified, they must be separated by spaces such
as:

	TTX file1 file2

@endnode


@node "Startup Macros"

By using the @{b}STARTUP/K@{ub} command-line option or the @{b}STARTUP@{ub} Tool Type, it is
possible to specify an @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macro to execute once the document is
loaded. This requires that a macro file exist on disk, ready to execute.

It is possible to execute TurboText commands once a document is loaded,
without the need to have a separate ARexx macro file. This is done by
supplying an extra set of quotes around the arguments to the STARTUP
option. This tells ARexx that the argument is to be executed as a macro
directly, instead of being taken as the name of a macro to load and
execute.

For example, if you want TurboText to load the file @{b}test.c@{ub}, and
automatically jump to line 45 in it, you can do:

	TTX test.c STARTUP "*"move 45*""

The extra set of quotes is specified by *", which is the standard way to
pass quotes on an AmigaDOS command-line. From Tool Types, you would simply
specify:

	STARTUP="move 45"

As an another example, assume you wish to load @{b}test.c@{ub}, copy lines 10 to 25
of this file to the clipboard, and then close the document, you could do:

	TTX test.c STARTUP="*"Move 10;MarkBlk;Move 25;CopyBlk;CloseDoc*""

@endnode


@node "Examples"

This section presents a few examples to demonstrate the use of the various
startup features available. We present certain scenarios and explain how
to accomplish them.

A very convenient thing to do is to have TurboText be loaded automatically
when your system is turned on. This can be done easily by dragging the TTX
program icon in the WBStartup drawer. The next time you turn on your
system, TurboText is automatically started and opens a default window. A
complete explanation of how to install TurboText in WBStartup can be found
in the @{" Workbench Options " link "WOrkbench Options"} section.

If you are a Shell user, the approach outlined above will not work.
Instead, you need to modify your system's user-startup to load TurboText
every time your system is turned on. Simply add a line such as:

	TTX BACKGROUND NOWINDOW

to your S:User-Startup file, and the editor will be loaded in the
background without opening a window. After being loaded in the background,
TurboText can be activated using its standard hot key sequences such as
@{b}[Ctrl]-[Alt]-W@{ub} to open a window.

It is sometimes desirable to unload the editor from the system to free up
memory to run other applications. This can be done in a few ways. First is
to simply enter the hot key sequence @{b}[Ctrl]-[Alt]-U@{ub} which tells TurboText
to unload itself as soon as all document windows are closed. The next way
to unload TurboText is to invoke it, passing it the @{b}UNLOAD@{ub} option. For
example:

	TTX UNLOAD

This sends a message to a background TurboText telling it to get out of the
system as soon as possible. Clicking on a TurboText icon with the @{b}UNLOAD@{ub}
Tool Type also has the same effect.

When running TurboText from a script or from within other applications, it
is very desirable to have TurboText wait until the current set of document
windows are closed before returning. This has the effect of saying to the
script or program "TurboText has returned, that means all editing is
done". For example:

	TTX test.c WAIT

opens a new document window and loads the file @{b}test.c@{ub} in it. Since the @{b}WAIT@{ub}
option was provided, TurboText waits until editing of the @{b}test.c@{ub} file is
complete before returning control to the script or application that called
it.

@endnode







