@node "Standard Menus"

This section documents the standard menus available in TurboText. The
function of every menu choice is explained in detail.

Many menu choices cause requesters to be displayed. These choices are
denoted by a trailing ellipsis at the end of the item name. For example,
@{b}Search/Find...@{ub} causes the @{" Find " link "The Find Requester"} requester to be opened.

The majority of menu choices have standard keyboard shortcuts using the
right Amiga key. These shortcuts are indicated in the menu strip using the
standard notation and are not discussed here.

TurboText menus support multiple selection using the left mouse button.
Consult your Amiga's documentation to learn how multiple menu selections
are done.

You can obtain help about any TurboText menu by displaying the menu of
interest, and pressing the @{b}[Help]@{ub} key. An AmigaGuide window will then open
and show information about the current menu.

Using @{" definition files " link "Definition Files"}, it is possible to completely change the layout
of TurboText's menus. This discussion does not address this feature.

	@{" The Project Menu " link "The Project Menu"}
	@{" The Windows Menu " link "The Windows Menu"}
	@{" The Edit Menu    " link "The Edit Menu"}
	@{" The Search Menu  " link "The Search Menu"}
	@{" The Macros Menu  " link "The Macros Menu"}
	@{" The Folds Menu   " link "The Folds Menu"}
	@{" The Extras Menu  " link "The Extras Menu"}
	@{" The Prefs Menu   " link "The Prefs Menu"}

@endnode


@node "The Project Menu"

The @{b}Project@{ub} menu offers commands that affect documents as a whole,
including loading and saving documents, and quitting the editor.

@{b}Open...@{ub} 
Opens the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} and allows a new file to be selected. After a
file is selected, it is @{" read " link "Loading An Existing File From Within TurboText"} into the current document window. If some
changes have been made to the current document since it was last saved, a
requester appears asking for confirmation before proceeding to open the
file requester.

@{b}Open New...@{ub} 
Creates a new, empty document window and opens the file requester for
loading.

@{b}Insert...@{ub} 
Opens the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} and allows a file to be selected. After a file
is selected, its contents are @{" inserted " link "Inserting A File In A Document"} at the current cursor position
within the current document.

@{b}Save@{ub} 
Writes the current document to disk under the filename shown in the title
bar of the @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. If the document is untitled, the operation
is identical to the @{b}Project/Save As...@{ub} command below.

@{b}Save As...@{ub} 
@{" Writes " link "Creating A New File"} the current document to disk under a new filename. The
@{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} is opened allowing a new name to be selected. The new
name then becomes the default filename for all future save operations.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}The importance of regularly saving your work cannot be overstated.
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Should a system error or some other irregularity occur, all
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}modifications made to a document since it was last saved could be
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}lost.

@{b}Clear@{ub} 
Clears the current document from the active window. Confirmation is
required if changes have been made since the document was last saved.

@{b}Print...@{ub} 
@{" Prints " link "Printing A File"} the current document to the system printer. A small window is
opened during printing, clicking that window's close gadget aborts the
print operation. Note that printing may continue if the printer or computer
system is equipped with a print buffer or software spooler. Embedded
control characters or escape codes in the current document may affect the
printer's operation.

@{b}Info...@{ub} 
Causes the @{" Info " link "The Info Requester"} requester to be opened.

@{b}Read-Only@{ub} 
Enables @{" read-only " link "Read-Only Mode"} mode, which prevents the current document from being
modified. Choosing the item again disables read-only mode and allows
editing once more.

@{b}Close Window@{ub} 
Closes the active window. Confirmation is required if changes have been
made since the document was last saved. This command has the same effect as
clicking the close gadget of the @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"}.

@endnode


@node "The Windows Menu"

The @{b}Windows@{ub} menu offers control over windows and views.

@{b}New@{ub} 
Creates a new and empty document window for editing.

@{b}Activate/Next Document@{ub} 
All currently active documents are kept in a sorted list according to their
order of creation. This command brings the @{b}next@{ub} TurboText window to the
front and activates it.

@{b}Activate/Previous Document@{ub} 
All currently active documents are kept in a sorted list according to their
order of creation. This command brings the @{b}previous@{ub} TurboText window to the
front and activates it.

@{b}Resize/To Maximum@{ub} 
Resizes the current document window to its maximum size.

@{b}Resize/To Minimum@{ub} 
Resizes the current document window to its maximum size.

@{b}Resize/Iconify@{ub} 
Turns the current document window into a very small title bar-sized
window. This has the same effect as clicking the zoom gadget of the window.

@{b}Organize Windows/Stack@{ub} 
Repositions and resizes all document windows on the current screen, and
puts them in a series of horizontal panels on the screen. This command
requires that @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} be installed and running in your system.

@{b}Organize Windows/Tile@{ub} 
Repositions all document windows on the current screen, and puts them in a
tile layout on the screen. This command requires that @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} be installed
and running in your system.

@{b}Organize Windows/Cascade@{ub} 
Repositions all document windows on the current screen, and puts them in a
cascading style. This command requires that @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} be installed and
running in your system.

@{b}Organize Windows/Iconify All@{ub} 
Iconifies all document windows on the current screen, and places them in a
stack on the left side of the screen.

@{b}Views/Split@{ub} 
@{" Splits the document window " link "Multi-View Editing"} in two portions. Each portion can show
different regions of the current document. Choosing the item again restores
the display to a single view.

@{b}Views/Toggle@{ub} 
Switches to the @{b}other@{ub} view. If the display is currently split in two
portions, following a @{b}Windows/Views/Split@{ub} command, this command switches
the cursor from one view to the other. If the display is not split, then
this command exchanges the hidden view with the current view.

@{b}Views/Swap@{ub}
Swaps the contents of the top view with the contents of the bottom view,
when two views are being displayed simultaneously.

@{b}Views/Expand@{ub} 
Increases the size of the current view by one line of text. This command
is only available when two views are being displayed simultaneously.

@{b}Views/Shrink@{ub} 
Reduces the size of the current view by one line of text. This command is
only available when two views are being displayed.

@{b}Views/Center@{ub} 
Adjusts the display by placing the current line in the middle of the view.

@{b}Open Hex View...@{ub} 
Opens the @{" Hex editing window " link "Editing Binary Files"}. This window allows the current document to
be viewed and edited using hexadecimal. Cursor movement, scrolling, and
editing are reflected in both the Hex window and in the main window in
real-time.

@{b}Open Calculator...@{ub} 
Opens the TurboText @{" calculator " link "The Calculator"}.

@{b}Open TTX Shell...@{ub} 
Opens the TurboText @{" command shell " link "The Command Shell"} window. This window allows you to
issue editor commands, @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros, or AmigaDOS commands directly from
the keyboard. This command requires that ARexx be installed and running in
your system.

@{b}Open DOS Shell...@{ub} 
Opens an AmigaDOS shell window on the current screen.

@{b}Help...@{ub} 
Opens an AmigaGuide window showing the TurboText quick reference page.

@{b}User's Manual@{ub}
Opens an AmigaGuide window showing the table of contents of the TurboText
on-line manual.

@endnode


@node "The Edit Menu"

The @{b}Edit@{ub} menu offers commands to access the Amiga's @{" clipboard " link "Using The Clipboard"}, including
writing and reading information to and from it.

@{b}Mark@{ub} 
Marks the current cursor position as the starting point of the text
@{" selection block " link "Selection Blocks"}. The size of the selection block can be adjusted by
positioning the cursor. Marking a block can also be done by double-clicking
the left mouse button. If a block is already selected, this command unmarks
the selection block and turns off selection mode.

@{b}Cut@{ub} 
Copies the currently selected block of text to the clipboard and deletes
the block from the current document.

@{b}Copy@{ub} 
Copies the currently selected block of text to the clipboard, leaving the
original block intact within the document.

@{b}Paste@{ub} 
Copies the contents of the clipboard into the document at the current
cursor position.

@{b}Erase@{ub} 
Erases the currently selected block of text from the document. This command
should be used in place of @{b}Edit/Cut@{ub} when there is text in the clipboard
that must be preserved, but something else in the document must be removed.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}There is no way to recover erased text - be careful when using
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}this command.

@{b}Mark Vertical@{ub} 
This is the same as @{b}Edit/Mark@{ub}, except that it initiates a
@{" vertical selection block " link "Vertical Selection Blocks"} instead of a regular horizontal block.

@{b}Paste Vertical@{ub} 
This is the same as @{b}Edit/Paste@{ub}, except that it pastes vertically.

@{b}Open Clip...@{ub} 
Reads a file from disk into the clipboard. The new contents of the
clipboard can then be inserted into the document at any position using the
@{b}Edit/Paste@{ub} command.

@{b}Save Clip As...@{ub} 
Saves the current contents of the clipboard to a file on disk.

@{b}Print Clip...@{ub} 
Prints the current contents of the clipboard to the system printer. See the
@{" Project/Print " link "The Project Menu"} command for more information on printing.

@endnode


@node "The Search Menu"

The @{b}Search@{ub} menu offers commands to @{" search " link "Finding And Changing Text"} through the document for
specific strings, line numbers, etc...

@{b}Find...@{ub} 
Causes the @{" Find " link "The Find Requester"} requester to be opened, allowing a search string to be
specified and a search operation to take place.

@{b}Find Next@{ub} 
Performs a search operation in the document using the current search string
and search attributes. The search operation can be aborted by pressing
@{b}[Esc]@{ub}.

@{b}Find & Change...@{ub} 
Causes the @{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"} requester to be opened, allowing a search
string and a replacement string to be specified and a search & replace
operation to take place.

@{b}Go To Line #...@{ub} 
Causes the @{" Go To Line " link "The Go To Line Requester"} requester to be opened which allows a line number
to be entered. The cursor is then positioned on this line.

@{b}Go To Char #...@{ub} 
Causes the @{" Go To Char " link "The Go To Char Requester"} requester to be opened which allows a character
number from the beginning of the document to be entered. The cursor is then
positioned on this character.

@{b}Go To Last Change@{ub} 
Positions the cursor where the last modification to the document was made.

@{b}Go To Auto-Bookmark@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the position indicated by the @{" automatic bookmark " link "The Automatic Bookmark"}.
The automatic bookmark gets set for every operation that can result in a
large cursor movement. This allows you to jump back instantly to the
position prior to the operation.

@{b}Match Bracket@{ub} 
Searches for the mate opening or closing bracket to the one currently
underneath the cursor. @{" Match Bracket " link "Finding And Changing Text"} is useful for finding errors in
equations that use nested brackets. The cursor must be on either @{b}{@{ub}, @{b}[@{ub}, @{b}(@{ub},
@{b}<@{ub}, @{b}«@{ub}, @{b}}@{ub}, @{b}]@{ub}, @{b})@{ub}, @{b}>@{ub}, or @{b}»@{ub} to use this command.

@endnode


@node "The Macros Menu"

The @{b}Macros@{ub} menu offers commands to @{" record " link "Recorded Macros"} sequences of actions and
replay them automatically.

@{b}Record Macro@{ub} 
Causes the editor to enter recording mode. In this mode the editor
remembers every menu choice and keyboard sequence you enter, so the entire
series can be re-executed automatically in one fell swoop. When in
recording mode, the mouse pointer is changed to an image of a tape
cassette.

@{b}Stop Recording@{ub} 
Causes the editor to exit recording mode. This is how you tell the editor
that the current macro is finished. The macro can then be re-executed via
@{b}Macros/Play Macro@{ub}.

@{b}Play Macro@{ub} 
Executes the current recorded macro, repeating the same commands as were
executed when the macro was recorded.

@{b}Play Many...@{ub} 
Causes a @{" requester " link "The Play How Many Requester"} to be opened allowing the specification of the number
of times to repeat the current recorded macro. A repeat count of zero
causes the macro to be executed until an error condition is encountered.
For example, encountering the end of a document is considered an error.

@{b}Open Macro...@{ub} 
Reads a recorded macro from disk which then becomes the current recorded
macro and can be executed via @{b}Macros/Play Macro@{ub}.

@{b}Save Macro As...@{ub} 
Writes the current recorded macro to a file on disk, where it then becomes
available for future uses of @{b}Macros/Open Macro...@{ub}. Recorded macros are
saved in ASCII format, in a manner suitable to be run as @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros.
That is, a saved recorded macro can be run from ARexx, or can be loaded as
a recorded macro. However, the opposite is not true - a general ARexx macro
cannot be loaded as a recorded macro.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}The fact that recorded macros are saved as ARexx macros is very
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}handy. You can record a series of operations and use the resulting
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}ARexx macro as the basis for a more complex ARexx macro.

@{b}Execute ARexx...@{ub} 
Lets you select an @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macro from disk using the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"},
and executes it.

@endnode


@node "The Folds Menu"

The @{b}Folds@{ub} menu offers commands for the management of folds. @{" Folds " link "Folds"} are a
special way of hiding parts of a document so it can be managed more easily.

@{b}Make Fold@{ub} 
Creates a fold within the document. If there is currently a
@{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"}, it will be folded away. If there is currently no
selected block, the fold is created by looking at the current indentation
level and folding every line which follows the current line and has a
greater indentation level, until a line with equal or lower indentation
level is encountered.

@{b}Show@{ub} 
Displays a sub-menu containing three choices: @{b}Single, Nested, All.@{ub} Choosing
@{b}Single @{ub}displays the contents of a hidden fold currently under the cursor.
Once displayed, the fold can be remade using @{b}Folds/Hide@{ub}. Choosing @{b}Nested@{ub}
instead does the same, except it also displays any folds within the current
fold, and any folds within it. Finally, choosing @{b}All @{ub}displays all folds in
the current document.

@{b}Hide@{ub} 
Displays a sub-menu containing three choices: @{b}Single, Nested, All.@{ub} Choosing
@{b}Single @{ub}remakes a fold having been revealed with @{b}Folds/Show@{ub}. Choosing @{b}Nested@{ub}
instead does the same, except it also hides any folds within the current
fold, and any folds within it. Finally, choosing @{b}All @{ub}hides all folds in the
current document.

@{b}Unmake@{ub} 
Displays a sub-menu containing three choices: @{b}Single, Nested, All.@{ub} Choosing
@{b}Single @{ub}displays and removes the fold currently under the cursor. Choosing
@{b}Nested@{ub} instead does the same, except it also unmakes any folds within the
current fold, and any folds within it. Finally, choosing @{b}All @{ub}unmakes all
folds in the current document.

@endnode


@node "The Extras Menu"

The @{b}Extras@{ub} menu offers commands which provide various capabilities to the
editor including letter case conversions, tab conversion, and
paragraph formatting.

@{b}Undelete Line@{ub} 
Restores the last line deleted using the @{b}DeleteLine@{ub} command, which is
assigned by default to @{b}[Ctrl]-[Del]@{ub}.

@{b}Undo Line@{ub} 
Undoes all changes made to the current line. The line is restored to the
condition it was in when it initially became the current line.

@{b}Center@{ub} 
@{" Centers " link "Block Operations"} a @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} of text between the left edge of the
document window and the current @{" right margin " link "Preferences - Editing"}. If no block is selected,
only the current line is centered.

@{b}Justify@{ub} 
@{" Justifies " link "Block Operations"} a @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} of text between the left edge of the
document window and the current @{" right margin " link "Preferences - Editing"}. Justification is a process
which attempts to insert spaces between words so that both ends of the line
touch the margins. Paragraphs are then nice and square instead of having a
ragged right edge. Newspapers typically use justification to obtain nice
columns. If no block is selected, only the current line is justified.

@{b}Format Paragraph@{ub} 
Modifies lines in the current paragraph so they contain as many words as
the current @{" right margin " link "Preferences - Editing"} allows. Lines longer than the right margin are
split and lines shorter than the right margin are combined. A blank line or
a line starting with a space indicates the end of a paragraph.

To format a paragraph, TurboText inserts and removes spaces and linefeeds
between words. There are some words that should always appear next to each
other and should not span two lines. For example, someone's name such as
John Smith should not span two lines. To avoid paragraph formatting moving
such words on separate lines, you must use the special keyboard sequence
@{b}[Alt]-[SpaceBar]@{ub} instead of the regular @{b}[SpaceBar]@{ub} between the two words.
The character inserted by @{b}[Alt]-[SpaceBar]@{ub} is known as a @{i}hard space.@{ui}

Hard spaces look just like regular spaces, the difference lies in how the
editor handles them. Paragraph formatting considers two words separated by
a hard space as a single word. This is why two words separated by a hard
space are never split across lines, TurboText treats the two words as a
single word.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Some text processing tools, such as compilers, may not behave
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}correctly when there are hard spaces in the files they manipulate.

@{b}Convert To Upper Case@{ub} 
Converts all lower case characters of the currently @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} to
upper case. If no block is selected, only the word under the cursor is
converted.

@{b}Convert To Lower Case@{ub} 
Converts all upper case characters of the currently @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} to
lower case. If no block is selected, only the word under the cursor is
converted.

@{b}Convert Tabs To Spaces@{ub} 
Converts all tab characters of the currently @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} to a varying
number of spaces. The number of spaces inserted for every tab character
corresponds to what is needed to preserve the same screen formatting. If no
block is currently selected, all the tab characters of the current document
are converted.

@endnode


@node "The Prefs Menu"

The @{b}Prefs@{ub} menu offers commands to manipulate the current TurboText
preferences.

@{b}Change...@{ub} 
Opens the @{" Preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester,
from which all TurboText options can be controlled.

@{b}Open Prefs...@{ub} 
Reads a new set of @{" preferences " link "Preferences"} from disk.

@{b}Save Prefs As...@{ub} 
Saves the current set of @{" preferences " link "Preferences"} to a file on disk. The file can
later be retrieved using @{b}Prefs/Open Prefs...@{ub}.

@{b}Save As Defaults@{ub} 
Saves the current set of preferences to the @{" startup preference file " link "Preferences"}. The
next time the editor is invoked, it will use the current set of
preferences.

@{b}Open Definitions...@{ub} 
Reads a new @{" definition file " link "Definition Files"} from disk. Definition files contain
information controlling the layout of menus, assignment of keyboard
sequences and more. This is the only menu item which does not allow
multiple menu selections. When this item is chosen, further menu selections
are ignored. This is because this command can result in the menu strip
being redefined, which would confuse the multiple selection process.

@endnode







