@node "Requesters"

This section provides a complete description of TurboText's requesters,
and how to operate them.

	@{" Keyboard Shortcuts          " link "Keyboard Shortcuts"}

	@{" The Preferences Requester   " link "The Preferences Requester"}
	@{" The File Requester          " link "The File Requester"}
	@{" The Find Requester          " link "The Find Requester"}
	@{" The Find & Change Requester " link "The Find & Change Requester"}
	@{" The Go To Char Requester    " link "The Go To Char Requester"}
	@{" The Go To Line Requester    " link "The Go To Line Requester"}
	@{" The Info Requester          " link "The Info Requester"}
	@{" The Play How Many Requester " link "The Play How Many Requester"}

@endnode


@node "Keyboard Shortcuts"

The majority of gadgets in TurboText requesters can be controlled using
the keyboard instead of the mouse. Whenever a gadget's name contains an
underlined letter, it can be controlled by the keyboard. The underlined
letter indicates which key controls that gadget.

Requesters featuring a positive/negative pair of gadgets (@{b}Use@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub}
for example) can be controlled by pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub} or @{b}[Left Amiga]-V@{ub} to
indicate the positive choice, and @{b}[Esc]@{ub} or @{b}[Left Amiga]-B@{ub} to indicate the
negative one.

Pressing the key associated with a text gadget activates the gadget. When a
text gadget is active, all keyboard shortcuts are disabled in order to
allow you to enter text. Pressing @{b}[Tab]@{ub} in a text gadget activates the next
text gadget in the requester, if there is one. Entering @{b}[Shift]-[Tab]@{ub} in a
text gadget activates the previous text gadget in the requester.

Pressing the key associated with a slider gadget or a number gadget causes
the value represented by the gadget to increase. Pressing the key
associated with the gadget while also holding down either @{b}[Shift]@{ub} key
decreases the value.

Pressing the key associated with a checkbox gadget toggles the state of
the gadget.

@endnode


@node "The Preferences Requester"

The TurboText preferences requester is where all of the program's options
can be controlled. The requester is divided up into multiple sections.
Each section controls a specific set of options. You can display different
sections by selecting the radio buttons that run down the left side of the
requester.

The sections of the preferences requester are:

	@{" Automatic Saving  " link "Preferences - Automatic Saving"}
	@{" Backup Creation   " link "Preferences - Backup Creation"}
	@{" Colors            " link "Preferences - Colors"}
	@{" Editing           " link "Preferences - Editing"}
	@{" End Of Lines      " link "Preferences - End Of Lines"}
	@{" Folds             " link "Preferences - Folds"}
	@{" Fonts             " link "Preferences - Fonts"}
	@{" Icons             " link "Preferences - Icons"}
	@{" Miscellaneous     " link "Preferences - Miscellaneous"}
	@{" Special Marks     " link "Preferences - Special Marks"}
	@{" Tabs              " link "Preferences - Tabs"}
	@{" Window And Screen " link "Preferences - Window And Screen"}

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Automatic Saving"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control TurboText's
ability to automatically save modified documents after a certain amount of
time passes. This can help ensure that your work is preserved in the event
of a power failure, or system crash.

@{b}Auto-Save Documents@{ub} 
When this option is on, the editor @{" automatically saves " link "Automatic Saving"} the current
document to disk at timed intervals. The effect is the same as choosing the
@{" Project/Save " link "The Project Menu"} menu command every time the interval is over. The editor
starts counting time as soon as you make any modifications to the current
document. Saving or opening a document resets and stops the timer, which is
restarted the next time the document is modified.

@{b}Ask Before Auto-Saving@{ub} 
Causes TurboText to open a requester every time the @{" automatic save " link "Automatic Saving"}
interval is expired. The requester asks you to confirm whether to save or
not. When this option is turned off, automatic saves proceed silently
without asking for confirmation.

@{b}Minutes Between Auto-Saves@{ub} 
Specifies the time in minutes between @{" automatic saves " link "Automatic Saving"}. Note that saving
or opening a document resets and stops the timer, which is only restarted
the next time the document is modified.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Backup Creation"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control is and how
TurboText creates backups of files when it saves documents to disk.

@{b}Create Backups When Saving@{ub} 
When this option is enabled, TurboText creates @{" backup copies " link "File Backups"} of files
whenever a document is saved. That is when saving, if there already is a
file of the same name on disk, it is copied elsewhere to preserve it,
before the new file is saved in its place.

@{b}Backup Template@{ub} 
Determines where and how @{" backups " link "File Backups"} are created.

@{b}Maximum Backup Version@{ub} 
Specifies the maximum number of backups when using the special
@{" numbered backup " link "File Backups"} technique as specified in the backup template.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Colors"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control the colors
used by the TurboText screen, and the colors used to render the text and
background in the TurboText @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"}.

@{b}Screen Colors@{ub}
This section of gadgets is only displayed when TurboText is running on its
own screen. If TurboText is currently on a public screen, such as
Workbench, the colors of the screen cannot be altered. The palette on the
right lets you select which color to alter, while the @{b}Red@{ub}, @{b}Green@{ub}, and @{b}Blue@{ub}
sliders let you adjust the selected color.

@{b}Text Color@{ub}
This lets you pick which color TurboText should use to display text within
the TurboText @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"}.

@{b}Background Color@{ub}
This lets you pick which color TurboText should use for the background
within the TurboText @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"}.

It is worthwhile to note that different color combinations will yield
different levels of rendering and scrolling performance in TurboText.
Selecting adjoining colors, for example the color 0 for the background,
and color 1 for the text color, will yield the best performance possible.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Editing"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control various
options affecting how TurboText behaves during text editing.

@{b}Auto-Correct Word Case@{ub} 
When this option is on, TurboText attempts to apply its @{" case correction " link "Word Correction"}
algorithm to new words as they are typed in.

@{b}Auto-Erase Selected Blocks@{ub} 
When this option is on, any selected block is automatically erased before
any editing operation is executed. So if a block of text is selected, and
you type in a key, the block would first be erased before the new
character is inserted.

@{b}Auto-Indent New Lines@{ub} 
When this option is on, new lines created because of word wrap, or by
explicitly pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub}, have the same @{" indentation " link "Editing Modes"} level as the
line above.

@{b}Select When Dragging@{ub} 
When this option is on, dragging the mouse through a document causes the
text to be automatically selected, instead of requiring you to double-click
the mouse or select the @{" Edit/Mark " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command.

@{b}Free Form@{ub} 
When this option is on, the cursor is not bound to the end of lines. That
is, normally it is impossible for the cursor to move beyond the last
character of a line. When this option is on, you can move the cursor where
you like and just start typing.

@{b}Line Wrap@{ub}
When this option is on, moving towards the left at the beginning of a
line, or moving right when at the end of a line, the cursor automatically
wraps to the previous or next line respectively. When this option is off,
you have to explicitly move up or down in order to change lines.

@{b}Overstrike@{ub} 
When overstrike is off, @{" insertion mode " link "Editing Modes"} is on. That is, as text is typed
in, it @{i}pushes @{ui}existing text out of the way. When the Overstrike option is
on, the new text replaces or @{i}types over @{ui}existing text instead.

@{b}Word Wrap@{ub} 
When this option is on, @{" carriage returns are inserted " link "Editing Modes"} automatically
before the current word whenever the cursor reaches beyond the current
right margin. The right margin can be adjusted using the @{b}Right Margin@{ub}
number gadget discussed below.

@{b}Right Margin@{ub} 
Specifies the current right margin in characters as used by the @{b}Word Wrap@{ub}
option above. When the @{b}Track Window Size@{ub} option is on, the right margin is
always equal to the maximum number of characters that can be displayed in a
single line of the current document window. So if the window is resized,
the margin will change. When this option is off, an explicit right margin
can be specified in the @{b}Right Margin@{ub} number gadget.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - End Of Lines"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control how end of
lines are handled.

@{b}Remove Trailing Spaces When Saving@{ub} 
When this option is on, spaces and tabs at the end of lines are removed
whenever the document is saved to disk. Since spaces at the end of lines
generally aren't useful, this option can slightly reduce the size of ASCII
files saved by TurboText.

@{b}Convert CR+LF/CR To LF When Loading@{ub} 
Files created on other computer platforms have different characters to
indicate the end of lines. When this option is on, an automatic
translation converts IBM-PC and Macintosh ASCII files so that the end of
lines of these files are interpreted correctly by TurboText.

@{b}Save End Of Lines As@{ub} 
Lets you control what character TurboText uses to mark the end of lines in
the files it creates. The Amiga and the UNIX world both use the LF
character to denote the end of lines. The IBM-PC and compatible world uses
two characters, CR and LF, to mark the end of lines. Finally, the Macintosh
world uses the CR character for its end-of-line marker. You can pick one of
these three combinations, or choose the @{b}Loaded@{ub} option. This makes TurboText
use the same end of line characters as was present when the document was
loaded. This is tremendously useful to edit files in a networked
environment.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Folds"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control how much
spacing is allocated within the TurboText @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"} for fold
markers.

@{b}Fold Spacing@{ub} 
Indicates the number of characters by which to shift displayed text towards
the right, thus leaving room on the left of the display for
@{" fold markers " link "Folds"}. Setting this option to @{b}Dynamic@{ub} instructs TurboText to
automatically track folds, and allow as much room on the left as is needed
in order to display all fold markers.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Fonts"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control which fonts
TurboText uses for different tasks.

@{b}Text Font@{ub} 
Shows the font currently selected for text display in the TurboText
@{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. Clicking on the up arrow gadget to the right of the
window brings up the standard system font requester, which lets you pick a
new font and size.

@{b}Gadget Font@{ub} 
Shows the font currently selected for use in gadgets within TurboText
requesters. Clicking on the up arrow gadget to the right of the window
brings up the standard system font requester, which lets you pick a new
font and size. Note that it is possible that a font that you pick ends up
making some TurboText requesters too large to fit on the screen. In such a
case, a smaller font will automatically be chosen by TurboText in order to
ensure that all requesters can always be opened.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Icons"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control how TurboText
handles Workbench icons as it loads and saves documents.

@{b}Load And Save Project Icons@{ub} 
Controls whether icons are saved along with documents. When icons are
saved, the file can be viewed and selected from the Workbench.

TurboText makes special use of document icons. When saving an icon,
TurboText attaches @{" information " link "Icon Commands"} to it describing where the folds are
within the current document, where the bookmarks are, where the last change
to the document was made.

When loading a document, TurboText reads the icon associated with the
document to obtain the extra information it attached to the icon. If this
option is off, then TurboText does not read these icons.

@{b}Default Tool For New Icons@{ub} 
Specifies the name of the tool that should be invoked whenever a document
icon is double-clicked from the Workbench. This should be the path leading
up to the editor as installed in your system. Note that the icon tool for
existing icons can be modified by using the @{b}Information@{ub} requester from
Workbench.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Miscellaneous"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control many random
options in TurboText.

@{b}Blank Mouse When Entering Text@{ub}
When this option is on, TurboText automatically makes the mouse pointer
invisible whenever you type text into the TurboText @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"}.
This is useful to get the mouse pointer out of the way when you type.
Moving the mouse instantly makes the mouse pointer visible again, so you
can easily use the mouse.

@{b}Ask Before Loading A File Twice@{ub}
When this option is on, TurboText will ask for confirmation before loading
a file from disk, which is already loaded in memory in another TurboText
window. The confirmation requester lets you load the file a second time,
lets you activate the other document window containing the file, or lets
you abort the operation.

@{b}Ask Before Overwriting A File@{ub}
When this option is on, TurboText will ask for confirmation whenever you
try to save a file which already exists on disk.

@{b}Auto-Detect Binary Files@{ub}
When this option is on, TurboText looks at the first 4K of files that are
being loaded to determine whether the file is a binary file or a regular
text files. Examples of binary files are program files. When a binary file
is detected, TurboText adjusts many preferences options in order to
prevent any automatic modifications of the file as it is being loaded. If
a binary file is detected, the following actions are taken:

   @{b}Remove Trailing Spaces When Saving@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Convert CR+LF/CR To LF When Loading@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Auto-Correct Word Case@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Free Form@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Word Wrap@{ub} is turned off
   @{b}Save End Of Lines As@{ub} is set to @{b}LF@{ub}
   @{b}Tab Conversion@{ub} on loading and saving is set to @{b}None@{ub}
   @{b}Tab Width For Files@{ub} is set to match the value of
     @{b}Tab Width For Editing@{ub}

@{b}Chunky Pixel Mode@{ub}
Certain Amiga graphics accelerator boards may run faster when this option
is turned on. It affects how TurboText scrolls text during editing. If you
have an accelerator board, you may wish to try this option and see if
scrolling gets faster.

@{b}Print Device@{ub} 
Specifies the name of the AmigaDOS device used when printing documents.
This is normally @{b}PRT:@{ub}, but you may wish to change this in order to send the
printout to a PostScript printer connected to SER:, for example.

@{b}ARexx Console@{ub} 
Whenever an @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macro is executed, an AmigaDOS console window can
optionally be opened by TurboText to provide an input and output
environment for the macro. This text gadget specifies the name of the
console that should be opened.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Special Marks"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control whether
special marks get displayed in the TurboText @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"} to
represent certain characters or conditions.

@{b}Show Spaces As ·@{ub} 
Puts a bullet instead of spaces when displaying the current document.

@{b}Show Tabs As °@{ub} 
Puts a little ball instead of any tab characters when displaying the
current document.

@{b}Show End Of Lines As ¶@{ub} 
Places a ¶ symbol at the end of every line when displaying the document.
This lets you see exactly where each line ends, accounting for spaces and
tabs at the end of lines.

@{b}Show End Of Documents As @{ub} 
Places a checkered box right after the last character in the current
document to indicate where the document ends.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Tabs"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you control how TurboText
handles tab characters when editing, loading, and saving documents.

@{b}Insert Spaces Instead Of Tabs@{ub} 
Changes the way the @{b}[Tab]@{ub} key is handled during text entry. When this
option is off, pressing the @{b}[Tab]@{ub} key inserts a @{b}tab@{ub} character within the
document. When this option is on, spaces are inserted instead. The
necessary number of spaces are inserted in order to simulate a tab.

This option only influences characters that are typed in at the keyboard.
Tab characters read in by opening a file, or pasting text are not affected.
To convert these tabs to spaces, use the @{" Extras/Convert Tabs To Spaces " link "The Extras Menu"}
menu command.

@{b}Tab Width For Editing@{ub} 
Specifies the size of tab characters. Typically, this is set to 8,
indicating that there is a @{i}tab stop @{ui}every 8th column.

@{b}Tab Width For Files@{ub} 
Specifies the size of tab characters in external files. Typically, this is
set to the same value as @{b}Tab Width For Editing@{ub}, but can be different. For
example, you can edit a file using 4 character-wide tabs, and want your
files on disk to use 8 character tabs. In such a scenario, TurboText would
convert the tabs when saving the document to disk, so that the formatting
of the document remains the same, and would convert the tabs back when
loading the document in.

@{b}Conversion When Loading@{ub}
This option lets you control how tabs are handled when documents are loaded
from disk. Tab characters can automatically be converted to equivalent
spaces, spaces can be converted to equivalent tabs, or no conversion can
occur.

@{b}Conversion When Saving@{ub}
This option lets you control how tabs are handled when documents are saved
to disk. Tab characters can automatically be converted to equivalent
spaces, spaces can be converted to equivalent tabs, or no conversion can
occur.

@{b}Conversion When Printing@{ub}
This option lets you control how tabs are handled when documents are
printed. Tab characters can automatically be converted to equivalent
spaces, spaces can be converted to equivalent tabs, or no conversion can
occur.

@endnode


@node "Preferences - Window And Screen"

This section of the @{" preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"} requester lets you

@{b}Screen@{ub} 
Shows the current screen mode or @{" public screen " link "Public Screens"} currently selected for
this TurboText window. Clicking the up arrow gadget on the right of the
window brings up the standard system screen mode requester, which lets you
pick a new screen mode for the editor, as well as screen dimensions, and
number of colors. From this requester, you can also pick a public screen on
which to open.

@{b}Deiconify Documents When Activated@{ub}
When this option is on, activating an iconified @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"}
automatically deiconifies the window and makes it ready for use.

@{b}Bring Documents To Front When Activated@{ub}
When this option is on, activating a document window automatically brings
the window in front of other windows on the current screen.

@{b}Buffer Window Contents When Hidden@{ub}
When this option is on, TurboText uses special chip RAM buffers to
preserve the contents of document windows when other windows overlap them.
These buffers allow TurboText to restore the contents of document windows
faster than redrawing the contents from scratch, whenever a section of a
document window gets exposed. (Note for programmers: this option
determines whether TurboText uses simple or smart refresh layers.)

@{b}Scroll Screen To Keep Cursor Visible@{ub}
This option only appears on systems running release 3 or later of the
Amiga Kickstart. When this option is on, TurboText will automatically
scroll oversized screens to keep the text cursor always visible as you
type text.

@{b}Zoom Gadget@{ub}
Lets you control the function of the zoom gadget on TurboText
@{" document windows " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. The @{b}Iconifies@{ub} choice causes the zoom gadget to
transform the document window into a small title bar when it is clicked.
The @{b}Resizes@{ub} choice makes the gadget behave like a normal zoom gadget, and
toggles the window between two sizes.

@{b}Scroll Gadget@{ub} 
Lets you control where TurboText puts its scroll gadget. The scroll gadget
normally appears in the right window border. You can also choose to have
it in the left window border, or to not display it at all.

@endnode


@node "The File Requester"

Whenever a filename is required in order to load or save a file from disk,
TurboText opens a system @{b}file requester@{ub} so you can select or enter a
filename. The file requester displays a list of files from a specified
drawer and allows you to select one for loading or saving.

You can move through the list of files using the scroll arrows and scroll
bar to the right of the requester. To select an item from the list,
position the mouse pointer over the item and click the left mouse button.

The list includes both files and drawers. When a file is selected, its name
is copied to the @{b}File@{ub} text gadget. When a drawer is selected, the list is
cleared and the selected drawer becomes the current drawer. It is scanned
for the files it contains, and these new files are then displayed in the
list area.

@{b}Pattern@{ub} 
This text gadget allows you to enter an AmigaDOS pattern which is used to
filter the files displayed in the list area. Only files matching the
pattern are displayed in the list. Drawers are always displayed regardless
whether they match the pattern.

@{b}Drawer@{ub} 
Specifies the drawer from which the list is taken. Files and drawers from
within this drawer are displayed in the list area as long as they match the
pattern specified in the @{b}Pattern@{ub} gadget.

@{b}File@{ub} 
Specifies the selected file. If the filename you want does not exist, it
obviously cannot be selected using the mouse. You must then enter this name
yourself using this gadget. Pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub} while this gadget contains a
filename causes the file requester to be closed and the filename to be
accepted.

@{b}Open/Insert/Save/Exec@{ub} 
This is the action gadget located in the bottom left. Its text changes
depending on the action that is to be performed when a file is selected.
After selecting a filename, click on this gadget for the selection to be
accepted. You can also double-click on the desired filename, to obtain the
same effect as clicking on this gadget. As well entering @{b}[Return]@{ub} within
the @{b}File@{ub} text gadget does the same.

@{b}Volumes@{ub} 
This gadget causes the current list of files to be replaced by a list of
all available volumes and logical assignments in the system. Selecting
this gadget again reverts to the list of files.

@{b}Parent@{ub} 
Causes the drawer containing the current drawer to itself become the
current drawer.

@{b}Cancel@{ub} 
Closes the file requester and cancels the operation that caused the file
requester to be opened. This is equivalent to clicking the requester's
close gadget.

More general information concerning the system file requester can be found
in your Amiga's documentation.

	@{" Keyboard Control " link "Keyboard Control"}

@endnode


@node "Keyboard Control"

The system file requester used by TurboText offers a fair amount of
control from the keyboard to allow you to navigate through the various
volumes and drawers of your system without touching the mouse.

When the file requester is first opened, the @{b}File@{ub} text gadget is active.
Any volume or drawer name entered in this gadget is automatically moved to
the @{b}Drawer@{ub} gadget. For example, if the gadgets contain

	Drawer  = @{b}df0:@{ub}
	File    = @{b}texts/readme.txt@{ub}

and you press @{b}[Return]@{ub} in the @{b}File@{ub} gadget, the gadgets would be changed to
contain

	Drawer  = @{b}df0:texts@{ub}
	File    = @{b}readme.txt@{ub}

If you then replace the contents of the @{b}File@{ub} gadget by entering

	@{b}df1:data/readme2.txt@{ub}

in the @{b}File@{ub} gadget and pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub}, the result would be

	Drawer  = @{b}df1:data@{ub}
        File    = @{b}readme2.txt@{ub}

The rules are simple. Whenever the @{b}File@{ub} gadget contains a slash (/), the
text up to the slash is appended to the end of the @{b}Drawer@{ub} gadget and
removed from the @{b}File@{ub} gadget. When the @{b}File@{ub} gadget contains a colon (:),
the text up to the colon replaces the contents of the @{b}Drawer@{ub} gadget and is
also removed from the @{b}File@{ub} gadget.

Entering a single slash in the @{b}File@{ub} gadget has the same effect as clicking
on the @{b}Parent@{ub} gadget.

The same type of keyboard control is also available for patterns. Whenever
a filename with patterns is entered in the @{b}File@{ub} gadget, the pattern portion
is moved to the @{b}Pattern@{ub} text gadget.

The above features can be combined to provide very convenient keyboard
control. For example:

	Pattern = @{b}#?@{ub}
        Drawer  = @{b}df0:texts@{ub}
        File    = @{b}df1:legal/contracts#?@{ub}

Pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub} in the @{b}File@{ub} gadget results in

	Pattern = @{b}contracts#?@{ub}
        Drawer  = @{b}df1:legal@{ub}
        File    =

The best way to fully understand how to use the file requester is to
experiment. Try choosing the @{b}Project/Open...@{ub} menu command and try moving
around within the available directories and volumes.

@endnode


@node "The Find Requester"

The @{b}Find@{ub} requester lets you perform searches through a document for
specific text strings. The search starts at the current cursor position,
can ignore the letter case of words, can ignore any diacritical marks, can
search forward or backward within the document, and can be made to find
only complete words instead of parts of words.

A successful search operation places the cursor on the first character of
the matched text. A failed search returns @{b}Not Found!@{ub} in the @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}.
Pressing @{b}[Esc]@{ub} during a search aborts the operation.

@{b}Find@{ub} 
Lets you specify the text string to search for. If you press @{b}[Return]@{ub} after
entering a string, the requester closes, and the search starts, using the
current options. Using the @{b}[CursorUp]@{ub} key, you can go through a list of the
search strings you have entered previously. This is known as @{i}search
history@{ui}. You can also enter the first few letters of a string, and enter
@{b}[Shift]-[CursorUp]@{ub}. This will look through the history of strings
for other strings starting with the same letter.s

@{b}Find Next@{ub} 
If you do not press @{b}[Return]@{ub} after entering a string in the Find gadget,
you can use the @{b}Find Next@{ub} gadget to cause a search. Clicking this gadget
does not cause the requester to be closed, allowing you to perform further
search operations.

@{b}Do Patterns@{ub} 
The search string entered in the @{b}Find@{ub} text gadget can contain simple
@{i}wildcards. @{ui}The question mark (?) can be used to mean @{i}match any character.@{ui}
For example, entering @{b}h?llo@{ub} as a search string causes strings such as
@{b}hallo@{ub},@{b} h4llo@{ub} or @{b}h-llo@{ub} to be considered matches. This gadget lets you
control whether ? is treated as a wildcard, or a regular character.

@{b}Ignore Accents@{ub} 
Forces the search to ignore diacritical marks. That is, a string such as
@{b}pere@{ub} becomes equivalent to @{b}pęre@{ub}.

@{b}Ignore Case@{ub} 
Forces the search to ignore the letter case of the text. That is, a string
such as @{b}HELLO@{ub} becomes equivalent to @{b}hello@{ub}.

@{b}Only Whole Words@{ub} 
When this option is on, the search only accepts complete words, and not
parts of words. For example, ordinarily if you search for the word
@{b}contract@{ub}, words such as @{b}contractual@{ub} or @{b}contracted@{ub} are flagged as matches as
they contain the word contract in them. Setting this option on causes the
editor to ignore these and only match the word @{b}contract@{ub} all by itself.

@{b}Scan Backwards@{ub} 
Causes the search to proceed from the current cursor position towards the
start of the document. When this option is off, the search proceeds from
the current cursor position towards the end of the document.

@endnode


@node "The Find & Change Requester"

The @{b}Find & Change@{ub} requester lets you perform searches through a document
for specific text strings, replacing them by other strings. The search
starts at the current cursor position, can ignore the letter case of words,
can ignore any diacritical marks, can search forward or backward within the
document, and can be made to find only complete words instead of parts of
words. Changes can be made one at a time, or globally.

A successful search operation places the cursor on the first character of
the matched text. A failed search returns @{b}Not Found!@{ub} in the @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}.
Pressing @{b}[Esc]@{ub} during a search aborts the operation.

@{b}Find@{ub} 
Lets you specify the text string to search for. If you press @{b}[Return]@{ub} after
entering a string, the @{b}Change@{ub} text gadget is activated so you can enter the
replacement string. At the same time, the search for the first occurrence
of the string starts.  Using the @{b}[CursorUp]@{ub} key, you can go through a list
of the search strings you have entered previously. This is known as @{i}search
history@{ui}. You can also enter the first few letters of a string, and enter
@{b}[Shift]-[CursorUp]@{ub}. This will look through the history of strings for other
strings starting with the same letter.s

@{b}Change@{ub} 
Lets you specify the text string to replace the search string with when it
is found. Using the @{b}[CursorUp]@{ub} key, you can go through a list of the change
strings you have entered previously. This is known as @{i}search history@{ui}. You
can also enter the first few letters of a string, and enter
@{b}[Shift]-[CursorUp]@{ub}. This will look through the history of strings for other
strings starting with the same letter.s

@{b}Find Next@{ub} 
Causes another search operation to start.

@{b}Change@{ub} 
After having found a text string, you can cause it to be replaced by the
replacement string specified in the @{b}Change@{ub} text gadget by clicking on this
gadget. The string is replaced, and a search for the next occurrence of
the search string is immediately started.

@{b}Change All@{ub} 
Causes the @{b}Find & Change@{ub} requester to be closed and the replace operation
to affect all strings found according to the current search options. This
has the same effect as clicking the @{b}Change@{ub} gadget for all strings in the
document. Once the operation is complete and no more strings are found, the
total number of replaced strings is displayed in the document window's
@{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. Use this gadget with care, incorrect search or replacement
strings can ruin a document.

@{b}Do Patterns@{ub} 
The search string entered in the @{b}Find@{ub} text gadget can contain simple
@{i}wildcards. @{ui}The question mark (?) can be used to mean @{i}match any character.@{ui}
For example, entering @{b}h?llo@{ub} as a search string causes strings such as
@{b}hallo@{ub},@{b} h4llo@{ub} or @{b}h-llo@{ub} to be considered matches. This gadget lets you
control whether ? is treated as a wildcard, or a regular character.

The replacement string can also contain wildcard characters, as long as
the number of wildcards in the replacement string does not exceed the
number in the search string.

To demonstrate how wildcards may be used, consider the following:

	Find   = @{b}?all ?an@{ub}
	Change = @{b}?ame ?en@{ub}

If a Find & Change is carried out using the above Find and Change
strings, the following are possible matches and replacements:

	Matched Text	Replaced Text

	Tall Pan	Tame Pen
	Fall Man	Fame Men
	Tall Man	Tame Men
	Tall Dan	Tame Den
	Mall Tan	Mame Ten

@{b}Ignore Accents@{ub} 
Forces the search to ignore diacritical marks. That is, a string such as
@{b}pere@{ub} becomes equivalent to @{b}pęre@{ub}.

@{b}Ignore Case@{ub} 
Forces the search to ignore the letter case of the text. That is, a string
such as @{b}HELLO@{ub} becomes equivalent to @{b}hello.@{ub} 

@{b}Only Whole Words@{ub} 
When this option is on, the search only accepts complete words, and not
parts of words. For example, ordinarily if you search for the word
@{b}contract@{ub}, words such as @{b}contractual@{ub} or @{b}contracted@{ub} are flagged as matches as
they contain the word contract in them. Setting this option on causes the
editor to ignore these and only match the word @{b}contract@{ub} all by itself.

@{b}Scan Backwards@{ub} 
Causes the search to proceed from the current cursor position towards the
start of the document. When this option is off, the search proceeds from
the current cursor position towards the end of the document.

@endnode


@node "The Go To Char Requester"

The @{b}Go To Char@{ub} requester lets you specify a character number from the
beginning of the document where the cursor should be moved to. Enter the
desired character number in the text gadget and press @{b}[Return]@{ub}. If the text
gadget is empty, or if the window's close gadget is selected, the cursor is
not moved. If a character number beyond existing bounds is specified, the
cursor is moved as far as possible. The title bar of the window indicates
tha allowable range of character numbers.

Character numbers can be entered using hexadecimal notation. This can be
done by prefixing the number being entered with $ or 0x. For example:

	$415
	0x415

@endnode


@node "The Go To Line Requester"

The @{b}Go To Line@{ub} requester lets you specify a line number where the cursor
should be moved to. Enter the desired line number in the text gadget and
press @{b}[Return]@{ub}. If the text gadget is empty, or if the window's close
gadget is selected, the cursor is not moved. If a line number beyond
existing bounds is specified, the cursor is moved as far as possible. The
title bar of the window indicates the allowable range of line numbers.

Line numbers can be entered using hexadecimal notation. This can be done
by prefixing the number being entered with $ or 0x. For example:

	$415
	0x415

@endnode


@node "The Info Requester"

The @{b}Info@{ub} requester displays useful information about TurboText, the current
document, and the system as a whole.

@{b}Program copyright and version@{ub} 
Shows the copyright for the program as well as the exact version number.
You need to mention this version number whenever requesting technical
support or ordering updates.

@{b}ARexx port name@{ub} 
The name of the ARexx port associated with the document window. This is
the port name to use when sending ARexx commands to this document window.

@{b}Visible lines@{ub} 
The number of lines in the current document which are not in folds.

@{b}Folded lines@{ub} 
The number of lines in the current document which are in hidden folds.

@{b}Total lines@{ub} 
The sum of the number of visible lines and number of folded lines. In
other words, the total number of lines in the document.

@{b}Characters@{ub} 
The total number of characters in the current document.

@{b}Average chars/line@{ub} 
The average number of characters per line in the current document.

@{b}Available memory@{ub} 
The total amount of available memory in the system, specified in bytes.

@{b}Date@{ub} 
The current system date. This display is generally only valid if your Amiga
is equipped with a battery backed-up real-time clock.

@{b}Time@{ub} 
The current system time. This display is generally only valid if your Amiga
is equipped with a battery backed-up real-time clock.

Like most other TurboText requesters, the Info requester can remain open
even while typing text into the main document window. This allows you to
see the numbers such as the total character count be updated @{b}live@{ub} as you
type. Just click the window's close gadget to get rid of it.

@endnode


@node "The Play How Many Requester"

The @{b}Play How Many@{ub} requester lets you specify the number of times to play
the current @{" recorded macro " link "Recorded Macros"}. Enter the desired number in the text gadget
and press @{b}[Return]@{ub}. As soon as you press @{b}[Return]@{ub}, the current recorded
macro is executed the indicated number of times. If the text gadget is
empty, or the window's close gadget is selected, the macro is not executed.

Specifying a repeat count of zero causes the macro to be executed until an
error condition is encountered. For example, encountering the end of a
document is considered an error.

Repeat counts can be entered using hexadecimal notation. This can be done
by prefixing the number being entered with $ or 0x. For example:

	$415
	0x415

@endnode







