@node "Keyboard And Mouse Control"

This section documents the standard keyboard and mouse button sequences
available in TurboText. The function of every sequence is explained in
detail.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}If you ever forget the default keyboard and mouse sequences, a list
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}of all the sequences is always available by pressing @{b}[Help]@{ub}.

Using @{" definition files " link "Definition Files"}, it is possible to completely change the keyboard
and mouse sequences understood by TurboText. This discussion does not
address this feature.

	@{" Keyboard Sequences " link "Keyboard Sequences"}
	@{" Hot Key Sequences  " link "Hot Key Sequences"}
	@{" Mouse Sequences    " link "Mouse Sequences"}

@endnode


@node "Keyboard Sequences"

In the following, @{b}[CursorLeft]@{ub}, @{b}[CursorRight]@{ub}, @{b}[CursorUp]@{ub} and @{b}[CursorDown]@{ub}
refer to the keyboard cursor keys, @{b}[Alt]@{ub} refers to either of the Alt keys,
@{b}[Shift]@{ub} refers to either of the Shift keys. @{b}[Return]@{ub} refers to the key
which is labelled with the bent arrow pointing left. @{b}[Enter]@{ub} refers to the
grey key labelled @{b}Enter@{ub} located at the right of the numeric keypad.

@{b}[Return]@{ub} 
Creates a new line below the current line, and moves the end of the
current line to this new line.

@{b}[Enter]@{ub} 
Inserts a new line in the current document and moves the cursor to it. The
line is inserted after the current line. The cursor is positioned on this
new line at the same column as the first non-space character of the
current line.

@{b}[Del]@{ub} 
Deletes the character currently under the cursor.

@{b}[Backspace]@{ub} 
Deletes the character to the left of the cursor.

@{b}[CursorLeft]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor one position to the left. If the cursor is already at the
start of the current line, the cursor is moved to the end of the previous
line.

@{b}[CursorRight]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor one position to the right. If the cursor is already at the
end of the current line, the cursor is moved to the start of the next line.
If the editor is in @{" free form mode " link "Preferences - Editing"}, the cursor is not moved to the next
line and is instead allowed to continue beyond the end of the line.

@{b}[CursorUp]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor up by one line.

@{b}[CursorDown]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor down by one line.

@{b}[F1]@{ub} 
@{" Corrects the spelling " link "Word Correction"} of the word under the cursor using the currently
loaded dictionary.

@{b}[F2]@{ub} 
@{" Completes the template " link "Templates"} under the cursor using the currently loaded
template list.

@{b}[F3]@{ub} 
Toggles the letter case of the character currently under the cursor, and
moves the cursor right.

@{b}[F4]@{ub} 
Exchanges the character currently under the cursor with the previous
character on the same line.

@{b}[F5]@{ub} 
Performs the same operation as clicking on the document window's zoom
gadget.

@{b}[F6]@{ub} 
Resizes the current document window to its maximum size.

@{b}[F7]@{ub} 
Resizes the current document window to its maximum size.

@{b}[F8]@{ub} 
Repositions and resizes all document windows on the current screen, and
puts them in a series of horizontal panels on the screen. This command
requires that @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} be installed and running in your system.

@{b}[F9]@{ub} 
Repositions all document windows on the current screen, and puts them in a
tile layout on the screen. This command requires that @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} be installed
and running in your system.

@{b}[F10]@{ub} 
Iconifies all document windows on the current screen, and places them in a
stack on the left side of the screen.

@{b}[Help]@{ub} 
Opens an AmigaGuide window listing a quick reference of all built-in
TurboText keyboard and mouse sequences.

@{b}[Shift]-[CursorLeft]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the start of the previous word.

@{b}[Shift]-[CursorRight]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the start of the next word.

@{b}[Shift]-[CursorUp]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the top of the current window. If the cursor is
already on the top line, moves the cursor one windowful towards the top of
the document.

@{b}[Shift]-[CursorDown]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the bottom of the current window. If the cursor is
already on the bottom line, moves the cursor down one windowful towards
the bottom of the document.

@{b}[Shift]-[Tab]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the previous tab stop position on the current line.

@{b}[Shift]-[Del]@{ub} 
Deletes all the characters to the end of the current word. If the cursor
is currently between two words, deletes all characters until the start of
the next word.

@{b}[Shift]-[Backspace]@{ub} 
Deletes all the characters to the start of the current word. If the cursor
is currently between two words, deletes all characters until the end of
the previous word.

@{b}[Shift]-[F1]@{ub} through @{b}[Shift]-[F10]@{ub} 
Sets a @{" bookmark " link "Bookmarks"} at the current cursor position.

@{b}[Alt]-[CursorLeft]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the start of the current line.

@{b}[Alt]-[CursorRight]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the end of the current line.

@{b}[Alt]-[CursorUp]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the start of the current document.

@{b}[Alt]-[CursorDown]@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the end of the current document.

@{b}[Alt]-[Del]@{ub} 
Deletes all characters to the end of the current line.

@{b}[Alt]-[Backspace]@{ub} 
Deletes all characters to the start of the current line.

@{b}[Alt]-[F1]@{ub} through @{b}[Alt]-[F10]@{ub} 
Jumps to the position indicated by a @{" bookmark " link "Bookmarks"}.

@{b}[Ctrl]-D@{ub} 
Inserts the current date in the document at the current cursor position.
This command requires that @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} be installed and running in your
system.

@{b}[Ctrl]-F@{ub} 
Toggles @{" free form mode " link "Preferences - Editing"}. The current mode is reflected in the document
window's @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. @{b}F@{ub} indicates free form is on, @{b}f@{ub} indicates it is
off.

@{b}[Ctrl]-I@{ub} 
Toggles @{" auto-indent mode " link "Editing Modes"}. The current mode is reflected in the document
window's @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. @{b}I@{ub} indicates auto-indent is on, @{b}i@{ub} indicates it is
off.

@{b}[Ctrl]-O@{ub} 
Toggles @{" overstrike mode " link "Editing Modes"}. The current mode is reflected in the document
window's @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. @{b}O@{ub} indicates overstrike is on, @{b}o@{ub} indicates it is
off.

@{b}[Ctrl]-R@{ub} 
Toggles @{" read-only mode " link "Read-Only Mode"}. The current mode is reflected in the document
window's @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. R indicates read-only is on, @{b}r@{ub} indicates it is
off.

@{b}[Ctrl]-Q@{ub} 
Activates quote mode, which causes the next keyboard sequence entered to be
taken as is, and not be interpreted as a command. Once the next keyboard
sequence is entered, quote mode is automatically disabled again. For
example, to enter a CTRL-R character in a document, you would enter:
@{b}[Ctrl]-Q@{ub} followed by @{b}[Ctrl]-R@{ub}. If instead you just enter @{b}[Ctrl]-R@{ub}, you
would cause read-only mode to be toggled instead of inserting the desired
keyboard sequence.

@{b}[Ctrl]-T@{ub} 
Inserts the current time in the document at the current cursor position.
This command requires that @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} be installed and running in your
system.

@{b}[Ctrl]-W@{ub} 
Toggles @{" word wrap mode " link "Editing Modes"}. The current mode is reflected in the document
window's @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. @{b}W@{ub} indicates word wrap is on, @{b}w@{ub} indicates it is
off.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorLeft]@{ub} 
Moves a line or a @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} left. This is done by removing spaces
and tabs at the start of lines.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorRight]@{ub} 
Moves a line or a @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} right. This is done by inserting spaces
at the start of lines.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorUp]@{ub} 
Causes the contents of the current window to scroll towards the top of the
display, while keeping the cursor on the same line within the document.
This is very useful when you wish to see a hidden part of a document,
while keeping the cursor on the same line.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[CursorDown]@{ub} 
Causes the contents of the current window to scroll towards the bottom of
the display, while keeping the cursor on the same line within the
document. This is very useful when you wish to see a hidden part of a
document, while keeping the cursor on the same line.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[Del]@{ub} 
Deletes the current line, and moves the cursor to the next line. The
deleted line can be recovered by using the @{" Extras/Undelete Line " link "The Extras Menu"} menu
command.

@endnode


@node "Hot Key Sequences"

Whenever TurboText is running in your system, various @{i}hot key @{ui}sequences are
always available to control TurboText. A hot key is a key sequence which is
never sent to the current application, but instead is intercepted and used
only by TurboText. For example, even though you are currently in a paint
program, you can enter the hot key sequence @{b}[Ctrl]-[Alt]-W@{ub} and a new
TurboText window is opened. The paint program never gets the key sequence.

Using @{" definition files " link "Definition Files"}, it is possible to completely change the hot key
sequences understood by TurboText. This discussion does not address this
feature.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[Alt]-A@{ub} 
Activates the last document window which was used. This is useful when
working with non-TurboText windows to cause the last document you worked
with to be activated.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[Alt]-O@{ub} 
Opens a new TurboText window and automatically opens the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"}
so a file can be selected.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[Alt]-S@{ub} 
Brings the TurboText screen to the front of all screens.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[Alt]-U@{ub} 
Tells TurboText to unload itself from memory as soon as all its windows are
closed. This sequence is useful when the editor has been started using the
special BACKGROUND option covered in @{" Startup Options " link "Startup Options"}.

@{b}[Ctrl]-[Alt]-W@{ub} 
Opens a new TurboText window ready for editing.

@endnode


@node "Mouse Sequences"

TurboText supports three button mice. The standard Amiga mouse only has
two buttons, the left and right ones, the middle button is only available
on third party mice.

Holding down the left button and pushing the mouse off the bottom or top
edges of the window scrolls the display. While the left button is still
down, clicking the right button brings the cursor back to its original
cursor position and stops scrolling.

The speed at which vertical scrolling occurs is directly related to the
horizontal position of the mouse pointer during scrolling. The fastest
scrolling speed can be attained by positioning the mouse at the extreme
left edge of the window, while progressively slower speeds are possible by
moving the mouse towards the right edge.

Double-clicking the left button marks the start of a @{" selection block " link "Selection Blocks"}.
This is identical to selecting the @{" Edit/Mark " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command.

Double-clicking the middle button marks the start of a
@{" vertical selection block " link "Vertical Selection Blocks"}. This is identical to selecting the
@{" Edit/Mark Vertical " link "The Edit Menu"} menu command.

Holding down the left button and clicking the middle button creates a
@{" fold " link "Folds"}. This is identical to selecting the @{" Folds/Make Fold " link "The Folds Menu"} menu
command.

Holding down the middle button and clicking the right button toggles the
@{" fold " link "Folds"} under the cursor from shown to hidden and back. That is, if the
fold under the cursor is currently shown, this sequence has the same effect
as the @{" Folds/Hide/Single " link "The Folds Menu"} menu command, while if the fold is currently
hidden, this sequence has the same effect as the @{" Folds/Show/Single " link "The Folds Menu"} menu
command.

@endnode







