@node "Definition Files"

Definition files are special text files read by TurboText which afford a
great deal of flexibility to the program. Using definition files, you can
completely change TurboText's menus, its keyboard commands, define word
dictionaries, and more.

If you followed the installation procedures outlined in
@{" Installing TurboText " link "Installing TurboText"}, there should be many definition files in the
@{b}TurboText:Support@{ub} drawer. The names of definition files always end with
@{b}.dfn@{ub} to clearly indicate they are definition files.

When TurboText is started, it configures itself using a built-in default.
Once the default configuration is installed, it searches for a file called
@{b}TTX_Startup.dfn@{ub}. This file is a definition file, and all definitions it
contains override the internal defaults of the editor.

Once the editor is running, a different definition file may be loaded by
choosing the @{" Prefs/Open Definitions... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu command and picking the
definition file to load from the file requester that appears. For example,
choose the menu command, and pick the @{b}TTX_Emul_CED.dfn@{ub} definition file.
After this file is loaded, you'll notice all TurboText menus are now
completely different! To restore the menus to normal, choose the
@{" Prefs/Open Definitions... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu command, and pick the @{b}TTX_BuiltIn.dfn@{ub}
file.

By changing the contents of the @{b}TTX_Startup.dfn@{ub} file, you can make
TurboText automatically look and act quite differently. This is an
extremely useful feature if you wish to emulate other text editors, or add
capabilities through @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros.

	@{" Overview                           " link "Definition File Overview"}
	@{" Using Definition Files             " link "Using Definition Files"}
	@{" Changing The Menus                 " link "Changing The Menus"}
	@{" Changing The Keyboard Commands     " link "Changing The Keyboard Commands"}
	@{" Changing The Hot Key Commands      " link "Changing The Hot Key Commands"}
	@{" Changing The Mouse Button Commands " link "Changing The Mouse Button Commands"}
	@{" Creating Dictionaries              " link "Creating Dictionaries"}
	@{" Creating Templates                 " link "Creating Templates"}
	@{" Linking Multiple Definition Files  " link "Linking Multiple Definition Files"}
	@{" Provided Definition Files          " link "Provided Definition Files"}

@endnode


@node "Definition File Overview"

Definition files control many of TurboText's features. The files are
divided into various sections. A section starts with the section name,
followed by definitions for that section, and terminated by a single @{b}#@{ub}
symbol. For example:

	KEYBOARD:  		-- section name
	  CTRL-X  DeleteSOL 	-- section definitions
	  CTRL-Q  CloseDoc
	# 			-- end of section marker

The following sections are currently supported:

	· @{" DICTIONARY:    " link "Creating Dictionaries"}

	· @{" HOT_KEYS:      " link "Changing The Hot Key Commands"}

	· @{" KEYBOARD:      " link "Changing The Keyboard Commands"}

	· @{" LINKS:         " link "Linking Multiple Definition Files"}

	· @{" MENUS:         " link "Changing The Menus"}

	· @{" MOUSE_BUTTONS: " link "Changing The Mouse Button Commands"}

	· @{" TEMPLATES:     " link "Creating Templates"}

Any number of sections can appear in a definition file.

Definition files can also contain comments. Comments are sections of the
files meant for humans to read, not for TurboText. Comments use the
standard C language commenting technique. Any part of the file enclosed
between /* and */ is ignored by the editor. For example:

	KEYBOARD:

	  /* delete to the start of the line */
	  CTRL-X  DeleteSOL

	  /* quit the program */
	  CTRL-Q  CloseDoc
	#

In the above, the text "delete to the start of the line" as well as "quit
the program" is meant to make what is happening clearer to a human reader,
and is ignored by the editor when the file is read in. Note that comments
can be nested. That is, there can be comments within comments. Comments
can also span any number of lines.

If an error occurs while reading a definition file, a requester is opened
displaying an error message, and the line on which the error occurred. The
option is then given to continue reading the rest of the file or to simply
abort the operation. Errors are mostly due to incorrectly formed definition
lines. Consult @{" Error Codes And Messages " link "Error Codes And Messages"} for more information on the
various errors possible.

@endnode


@node "Using Definition Files"

The TurboText disk includes many different definition files. There are
some which emulate different text editors, others provide non-English text
for TurboText's menus, and still others offer dictionaries and template
lists for different uses.

The trick with definition files is to pick and choose the features you want
and need, and to combine the various files into one file and copy this file
to @{b}TurboText:Support/TTX_Startup.dfn@{ub}. That way, all the features you need
are loaded automatically by TurboText when it is started. The
@{" Provided Definition Files " link "Provided Definition Files"} section explores the definition files included
with TurboText in detail and shows exactly how to make use of them.

The @{b}TTX_BuiltIn.dfn@{ub} definition file contains definitions that match
TurboText's internal default definitions. This file is very useful to
understand how definition files work. We recommend you load this file into
the editor to observe how it is put together. To do this:

	1 - Choose the @{" Project/Open... " link "The Project Menu"} menu command.

	2 - Enter @{b}TurboText:Support@{ub} in the @{b}Drawer@{ub} text gadget.

	3 - Select the file @{b}TTX_BuiltIn.dfn@{ub} from the list area using
	    the left mouse button.

	4 - Click the @{b}Open@{ub} gadget.

The following sections discuss how to change the various definitions in a
definition file. We suggest you compare the explanations given to the
contents of the @{b}TTX_BuiltIn.dfn@{ub} file. This will help you clearly understand
how definition files work.

@endnode


@node "Changing The Menus"

The @{b}MENUS@{ub} section describes the menus presented by TurboText along with the
commands associated with them.

Every action that can be performed in TurboText is defined by a specific
command. These are the same commands that can be used from @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros.
Consult the @{" TurboText Command Reference " link "TurboText Command Reference"} for a complete list of available
commands.

A menu strip consists of four major components:

	· Menu

	· Items

	· Sub-items

	· Separation bars

There are several menus in a menu strip. The names of these menus is what
appears in the menu bar when holding down the right mouse button. An item
is a single entry within a menu, this is what you choose. A sub-item is an
item contained in a sub-menu. Finally, a separation bar is used to
separate sections within a menu or sub-menu.

You can define all four menu components within a definition file. To
define a component, you must specify a component type and, when
appropriate, its name, keyboard shortcut, and associated editor command.
The component types are:

	· MENU	for menu names

	· ITEM	for items

	· SUB	for sub-items

	· BAR	for separation bars in menus

	· SBAR	for separation bars in sub-menus

When specifying a new menu, you give its name, and an optional AmigaGuide
help document to load in when the user asks for help on a menu. For example

	MENU "Project" "TurboText:TurboText_Manual/The Project Menu"

defines a new menu called @{b}Project@{ub}. If the user presses the help key while
this menu is pulled-down, the @{b}TurboText_Manual@{ub} AmigaGuide document will be
loaded and displayed on top of the current document window. When new menus
are added, they appear to the right of existing menus.

When specifying an item, you must give its name, a keyboard shortcut, and
a command to execute when the item is chosen. For example

	ITEM "Open..." "O" OpenFile

defines an item called @{b}Open...@{ub} which has @{b}O@{ub} as keyboard shortcut, and
executes the @{" OpenFile " link "OpenFile"} command when it is chosen. When new items are
added, they appear at the bottom of the last menu defined.

Sub-items are defined exactly like items, except that the keyword @{b}SUB@{ub} is
used to identify them. For example

	SUB "Save As..." "" SaveFileAs

defines a sub-item called @{b}Save As...@{ub}, which has no keyboard shortcut, and
executes the @{" SaveFileAs " link "SaveFileAs"} command when it is chosen. When a sub-item is
defined, it is added at the bottom of the current sub-menu. If there is
currently no sub-menu, one is created and attached to the last item
defined.

If you are running release 3.0 or later of the Amiga Kickstart, then it is
possible to specify multiple character keyboard sequences for items and
sub-items. Doing so causes TurboText to put the given sequence in the
right part of the menu, without an Amiga key symbol next to it. For example

	ITEM "Send Mail" "F1" ExecARexxMacro "TurboText:Rexx/SendMail.ttx"

defines a menu item that would look like

	Send Mail      F1

Pressing F1 for such as item will NOT invoke the associated command. You
still have to define @{b}[F1]@{ub} as a keyboard sequence in a KEYBOARD: section.

To insert a separation bar within a menu, simply put the @{b}BAR@{ub} keyword by
itself on a line such as

	BAR

Finally, to insert a separation bar within a sub-menu, simply put the @{b}SBAR@{ub}
keyword by itself on a line such as

	SBAR

Following is a complete menu strip definition to create a strip with only
one menu in it. This menu is identical to the first standard TurboText
menu.

	MENUS:
	  MENU "Project" "TurboText:TurboText_Manual/The Project Menu"
	    ITEM "Open..."             "O" OpenFile
	    ITEM "Open New..."         "Y" OpenDoc FileReq
	    ITEM "Insert..."           ""  InsertFile
	    BAR
	    ITEM "Save"                "S" SaveFile
	    ITEM "Save As..."          "A" SaveFileAs
	    BAR
	    ITEM "Clear"               "K" ClearFile
	    ITEM "Print..."            "P" PrintFile
	    ITEM "Info..."             "?" OpenRequester Info
	    BAR
	    ITEM "Read-Only"    "[Ctrl]-R" SetReadOnly Toggle
	    BAR
            ITEM "Close Window"        "Q" CloseDoc
	#


@endnode


@node "Changing The Keyboard Commands"

The @{b}KEYBOARD@{ub} section describes which commands are associated with which key
sequences.

Every action that can be performed in TurboText is defined by a specific
command. These are the same commands that can be used from @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros.
Consult the @{" TurboText Command Reference " link "TurboText Command Reference"} for a complete list of available
commands.

A key sequence is a series of keys entered at the keyboard. A sequence
consists of a single character accompanied by an arbitrary number of key
qualifiers. Key qualifiers are keys like @{b}[Shift]@{ub} or @{b}[Alt]@{ub} that alter the
meaning of other keys. The possible key qualifiers are:

	· @{b}SHIFT@{ub} stands for either @{b}[Shift]@{ub} key

	· @{b}LEFT_SHIFT@{ub} stands for the left @{b}[Shift]@{ub} key

	· @{b}RIGHT_SHIFT@{ub} stands for the right @{b}[Shift]@{ub} key

	· @{b}ALT@{ub} stands for either @{b}[Alt]@{ub} key

	· @{b}LEFT_ALT@{ub} stands for the left @{b}[Alt]@{ub} key

	· @{b}RIGHT_ALT@{ub} stands for the right @{b}[Alt]@{ub} key

	· @{b}CTRL@{ub} stands for the @{b}[Ctrl]@{ub} key

	· @{b}AMIGA@{ub} stands for either @{b}[Amiga]@{ub} key

	· @{b}LEFT_AMIGA@{ub} stands for the left @{b}[Amiga]@{ub} key

	· @{b}RIGHT_AMIGA@{ub} stands for the right @{b}[Amiga]@{ub} key

	· @{b}META@{ub} is one of the special emulation qualifiers

	· @{b}META2@{ub} is one of the special emulation qualifiers

	· @{b}MODE@{ub} is one of the special emulation qualifiers

	· @{b}MODE2@{ub} is one of the special emulation qualifiers

	· @{b}ANYMODE@{ub} is one of the special emulation qualifiers

	· @{b}NUM_PAD@{ub} stands for a key on the numeric keypad

	· @{b}NOREPEAT@{ub} specifies that a sequence is not to auto-repeat

These qualifiers alter the meaning of other keys. For example, pressing the
@{b}A@{ub} key by itself yields the letter @{b}a@{ub}, while pressing the @{b}A@{ub} key when at the
same time holding down @{b}[Shift]@{ub} yields the letter @{b}A@{ub}.

Key sequences also need to describe keys which do not have simple
characters attached to them. For those keys, special names are used:

	· BACKSPACE

	· CURSOR_DOWN

	· CURSOR_LEFT

	· CURSOR_RIGHT

	· CURSOR_UP

	· DEL

	· ENTER

	· ESC

	· F1 through F10

	· HELP

	· NP_DEL (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_DOWN (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_END (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_HOME (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_INS (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_LEFT (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_NUML (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_PGDN (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_PGUP (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_PRTSC (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_RIGHT (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_SCRL (numeric keypad key)

	· NP_UP (numeric keypad key)

	· RETURN

	· SPACEBAR

	· TAB

All keys listed above with the @{b}NP_@{ub} prefix are shorthand forms to indicate
the keys on the numeric keypad without having to specify the NUM_PAD
qualifier.

Here are some examples of keyboard sequences:

	CTRL-A

means hold down @{b}[Ctrl]@{ub} and press the @{b}A@{ub} key.

	SHIFT-DEL

means hold down either @{b}[Shift]@{ub} key and press the @{b}[Del]@{ub} key.

	SHIFT-ALT-F1

means hold down either @{b}[Shift]@{ub} key, either @{b}[Alt]@{ub} key, and press the @{b}[F1]@{ub}
key.

To define a keyboard command, you must list the key sequence followed by
the command to execute when the sequence is entered by the user. For
example

	CTRL-F1 ClearFile

means that the @{" ClearFile " link "ClearFile"} command is executed whenever the @{b}[F1]@{ub} key is
struck while the @{b}[Ctrl]@{ub} key is being held down.

More information on defining keyboard sequences can be found in:

	@{" Emulation Qualifiers     " link "Emulation Qualifiers"}
	@{" Controlling Key Repeat   " link "Controlling Key Repeat"}
	@{" Using Extended Keyboards " link "Using Extended Keyboards"}

