@node "Emulation Qualifiers"

There exist five special qualifiers that are meant to help create effective
emulations of other text editors. These are @{b}META@{ub}, @{b}META2@{ub}, @{b}MODE@{ub}, @{b}MODE2@{ub},
@{b}ANYMODE@{ub}.

Many editors use linked keyboard sequences in order to execute a command.
For example, to save a file in the EMACS editor, @{b}[Ctrl]-X@{ub} must be entered,
followed by @{b}[Ctrl]-S@{ub}. The two @{b}META@{ub} and the two @{b}MODE@{ub} qualifiers enable the
mapping of such keyboard sequences, and are controlled by four editor
commands:

	· @{" SetMeta " link "SetMeta"} causes the @{b}META@{ub} qualifier to be set the next
	  time a key sequence is entered.

	· @{" SetMeta2 " link "SetMeta2"} causes the @{b}META2@{ub} qualifier to be set the next
	  time a key sequence is entered.

	· @{" SetMode " link "SetMode"} causes the @{b}MODE@{ub} qualifier to be set for all
	  future key sequences entered.

	· @{" SetMode2 " link "SetMode2"} causes the @{b}MODE2@{ub} qualifier to be set for all
	  future key sequences entered.

A keyboard command definition emulating the EMACS file saving command
looks like:

	KEYBOARD:
          CTRL-X       SetMeta
          META-CTRL-S  SaveFile
        #

When @{b}[Ctrl]-X@{ub} is entered, it causes the next key sequence to have the @{b}META@{ub}
qualifier set. When @{b}[Ctrl]-S@{ub} is then entered, the @{" SaveFile " link "SaveFile"} command is
executed. The same technique is used for @{b}META2@{ub}. @{b}MODE@{ub}, and @{b}MODE2@{ub} work
similarly except they are permanent. That is, once the @{" SetMode " link "SetMode"} command
has been executed, all further keyboard sequences have the @{b}MODE@{ub} qualifier
set. Executing a @{" SetMode OFF " link "SetMode"} command turns this off.

The @{b}ANYMODE@{ub} qualifier defines a key sequence which is executed if a
sequence is entered that has either of @{b}META@{ub}, @{b}META2@{ub}, @{b}MODE@{ub}, or @{b}MODE2@{ub} set and
doesn't match any defined sequence. That is, if a previous key sequence
caused any of the special qualifiers to be set and a keyboard sequence is
entered that doesn't match any of the currently defined sequences, the
special qualifiers are removed and replaced by the @{b}ANYMODE@{ub} qualifier and
another attempt is made to find a matching sequence. Defining a sequence
with the @{b}ANYMODE@{ub} qualifier serves as a fall-back sequence for keys using
the four special qualifiers.

In addition to the @{b}ANYMODE@{ub} qualifier, another feature provides a fall-back
for unknown commands. Specifying a key sequence of @{b}OTHERWISE@{ub} defines a
command to execute whenever a key sequence with the @{b}ANYMODE@{ub} qualifier
cannot be found.

To clarify the use of @{b}ANYMODE@{ub} and @{b}OTHERWISE@{ub}, consider the following:

	KEYBOARD:
	  CTRL-X          SetMeta
	  META-Q          Insert "bonjour"
	  ANYMODE-CTRL-P  Insert "hello"
	  OTHERWISE       Insert "goodbye"
	#

With the above @{b}KEYBOARD@{ub} section in effect, entering @{b}[Ctrl]-X@{ub} causes the
@{b}META@{ub} qualifier to be set for the next key sequence entered. So if the next
sequence entered is simply @{b}Q@{ub}, the editor looks for a key sequence of
@{b}META-Q@{ub}, finds it and executes its associated command, namely @{b}Insert
"bonjour"@{ub}.

Now if the second sequence entered is instead @{b}[Ctrl]-P@{ub}, the editor looks
for a key sequence of @{b}META-CTRL-P@{ub}. Since it doesn't find it, the @{b}META@{ub}
qualifier is then removed and replaced by the @{b}ANYMODE@{ub} qualifier, and a
search is made for @{b}ANYMODE-CTRL-P@{ub}. The sequence is then found and the
@{b}Insert "hello"@{ub} command is executed.

If the sequence entered after @{b}[Ctrl]-X@{ub} is instead @{b}[Ctrl]-W@{ub}, the editor
looks for @{b}META-CTRL-W@{ub} and doesn't find it. The @{b}META@{ub} qualifier is then
removed and replaced by the @{b}ANYMODE@{ub} qualifier and another unsuccessful
search is performed. At this point, TurboText gives up and executes the
command associated with the @{b}OTHERWISE@{ub} sequence, which in this case is
@{b}Insert "goodbye"@{ub}. If the @{b}OTHERWISE@{ub} sequence is not defined, then all
special qualifiers are stripped off and the command is treated as a normal
key sequence.

@endnode


@node "Controlling Key Repeat"

By default, all key sequences defined in a definition file are
auto-repeating. That is if you enter the key sequence and hold the keys
down, they start to repeat at a rate which is defined in the system
preferences. It is in some cases desirable to prevent keys from
auto-repeating. This is done by specifying the @{b}NOREPEAT@{ub} qualifier. For
example

	NOREPEAT-RETURN InsertLine

defines that pressing @{b}[Return]@{ub} inserts a new line, while keeping the key
pressed does not cause the sequence to be automatically repeated. Without
the @{b}NOREPEAT@{ub} qualifier, holding the key down causes new lines to be
inserted until the key is released.

@endnode


@node "Using Extended Keyboards"

A special facility exists to support extended keyboards sold by third party
vendors, or any future extended keyboards sold by Commodore. These
keyboards may well provide certain extra keys which are not available on
the standard Amiga keyboard. That means TurboText will not be capable of
understanding these keys directly. To circumvent this potential problem, it
is possible to specify a keyboard key by its @{i}raw key code.@{ui}

The raw key code is the value transmitted by the keyboard to the main
computer whenever a given key is struck. Every key on the keyboard has a
different raw key code associated with it. Any keys added on future
keyboards will also have unique raw key codes associated with them. The
raw key codes should be supplied in the documentation accompanying any
keyboard you purchase separately.

To specify a raw key code, you use the @{b}@@{ub} symbol, followed by the raw
key code value. For example, the raw key code associated with the spacebar
on the standard Amiga keyboard is 64. To define a keyboard sequence using
this raw key code would look like:

	SHIFT-@64  Insert "hello"

The above definition means that whenever the key with raw code 64 is struck
while the @{b}[Shift]@{ub} key is down, the @{b}Insert "hello"@{ub} command is executed.
Using this technique, you can define key sequences for any possible
keyboard configuration.

@endnode


@node "Changing The Hot Key Commands"

The @{b}HOT_KEYS@{ub} section describes which @{" hot key sequences " link "Hot Key Sequences"} TurboText should
look for and which commands are executed when these sequences are
encountered.

Unlike normal key sequences, hot key sequences are available from anywhere
within your system. This means that regardless of which window is
currently active, hot key sequences find their way to TurboText, and
TurboText acts on them.

The @{b}HOT_KEYS@{ub} definitions are virtually identical to the @{b}KEYBOARD@{ub}
definitions described in the previous section. There are two differences:

	· Hot key sequences cannot make use of the @{b}META@{ub}, @{b}META2@{ub}, @{b}MODE@{ub}, @{b}MODE2@{ub},
	  @{b}ANYMODE@{ub}, and @{b}NOREPEAT@{ub} qualifiers.

	· Only global TurboText commands are available to be bound to hot key
	  sequences.

While normal key sequences can make use of almost all commands defined in
the @{" TurboText Command Reference " link "TurboText Command Reference"}, hot key sequences are limited to the
TurboText @{" global commands " link "Global Commands"}.

Following is a complete hot key definition which is identical to the
standard TurboText hot key definition:

	HOT_KEYS:
	  CTRL-ALT-A  ActivateLastDoc
	  CTRL-ALT-O  OpenDoc FileReq
	  CTRL-ALT-S  Screen2Front
	  CTRL-ALT-U  SetBackground OFF
	  CTRL-ALT-W  OpenDoc
	#

The @{b}HOT_KEYS@{ub} section can also make use of the @{" raw key code " link "Using Extended Keyboards"} specification
used with extended keyboards.

@endnode


@node "Changing The Mouse Button Commands"

The @{b}MOUSE_BUTTONS@{ub} section describes which commands get executed whenever
special sequences of mouse clicks are performed. The mouse click sequences
understood by TurboText are:

	· @{b}LEFTMIDDLE@{ub} - depress left button and click middle button

	· @{b}LEFTRIGHT@{ub} - depress left button and click right button

	· @{b}MIDDLELEFT@{ub} - depress middle button and click left button

	· @{b}MIDDLERIGHT@{ub} - depress middle button and click right button

	· @{b}DOUBLELEFT@{ub} - double-click the left button

	· @{b}DOUBLEMIDDLE@{ub} - double-click the middle button

Note that the standard Amiga mouse does not have a middle button, which
means the @{b}LEFTMIDDLE@{ub}, @{b}DOUBLEMIDDLE@{ub}, @{b}MIDDLELEFT@{ub} and @{b}MIDDLERIGHT@{ub} sequences
are only available when a special three button mouse is being used.

To define a mouse sequence, you list the sequence, followed by the editor
command to execute whenever the mouse sequence is entered. Like menus and
key sequences, any command can be associated with a mouse click sequence.

Following is a complete mouse button definition which is identical to the
standard TurboText mouse button definition:

	MOUSE_BUTTONS:
	  DOUBLELEFT    MarkBlk
	  DOUBLEMIDDLE  MarkBlk Vertical
	  LEFTRIGHT     MoveBookmark
	  LEFTMIDDLE    MakeFold
	  MIDDLERIGHT   ToggleFold
	#

@endnode


@node "Creating Dictionaries"

The @{b}DICTIONARY@{ub} section is a simple list of words used by TurboText's
advanced @{" Case Correction " link "Word Correction"} and @{" Word Correction " link "Word Correction"} features. You must
enumerate the words you wish to have these features know about, one per
line. For example:

	DICTIONARY:
	  PROCEDURE
	  MODULE
	  IMPLEMENTATION
	#

Whenever a definition file containing a DICTIONARY section is loaded in
the editor, the words in the section become the current dictionary. From
that point on, all Case Correction and Word Correction operations use
these words.

Typically, the dictionary contains words and tokens that refer to a
programming language. You can also enter Amiga-specific terms such as
@{b}SwapBitsRastPortClipRect@{ub} or @{b}BltMaskBitMapRastPort@{ub}, so that when you type
these words in, the editor is able to correct their spelling or letter
case.

The case of the words you define in a @{b}DICTIONARY@{ub} section is important. It
is used for Case Correction. You can enter words in either upper, lower, or
mixed case, and Case Correction transforms the case of the words you type
in the editor to match what is in the dictionary.

@endnode


@node "Creating Templates"

The @{b}TEMPLATES@{ub} section is necessary to support TurboText's special
@{" Template Completion " link "Templates"} feature.

The @{b}TEMPLATES@{ub} section contains a series of lines describing the expressions
that TurboText can accept in its Template Completion function. Every line
contains a single expression which the editor uses when trying to complete
a template.

To explain the format of this section, it is best to use an example:

	1 - Choose the @{" Prefs/Open Definitions... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu command.

	2 - From the file requester that appears, select the
	    @{b}TTX_M2.dfn@{ub} definition file.

	3 - Move the text cursor to an empty line, type @{b}PROCE@{ub},
	    and press @{b}[F2]@{ub}. You will obtain the following:

		PROCEDURE ();
		VAR

		BEGIN

		END ;

	    and the cursor will be positioned on the open parenthesis after
	    the word PROCEDURE.

The template definition used to store the above template is:

	PROCEDURE @();*nVAR*n*nBEGIN*n*nEND ;*n

The relation between this line and the resulting on-screen template is
simple.

First, there are the @{b}*n@{ub} combinations. These indicate that there is a line
break at that position in the template. So basically, when inserting the
text in the editor, a @{b}*n@{ub} combination yields the same result as pressing
@{b}[Return]@{ub}. This is why the words VAR and BEGIN, for instance, end up on two
separate lines in our example.

Second, the @{b}@@{ub} symbol indicates where the cursor should be positioned
after the template has been completed. The cursor is positioned on the
character following the @{b}@@{ub} sign. In our example, the cursor gets
positioned on the open parenthesis.

To further explain this format, we can take a template and turn it into
the necessary sequence of characters to create a definition. Assume the
following template:

	WHILE () DO

	END;

Every line of this template needs to be specified. Anywhere where you would
press @{b}[Return]@{ub} when typing the template, use the @{b}*n@{ub} combination instead:

	"WHILE () DO*n*nEND;*n"

Note that to specify the empty line in the middle, an extra @{b}*n@{ub} was added
after the word DO.

Now given the template, the most logical choice for where to position the
cursor is within the two parenthesis. (The template represents a Modula-2
programming construct and there needs to be something inserted in between
the parenthesis.) This means that the cursor must be positioned on the
closing parenthesis. To specify this, you include the @{b}@@{ub} sign just
before the parenthesis. This turns the definition into:

	"WHILE (@) DO*n*nEND;*n"

Every line of a @{b}TEMPLATES@{ub} section contains such a definition. Templates can
be very useful when using various programming languages, or even to create
standard headings that are used often.

@endnode


@node "Linking Multiple Definition Files"

The TurboText distribution disk includes many different definition files
that offer various features. As mentioned above, the most straightforward
approach to use many of the definition files at the same time is to combine
them into a single larger definition file and call it @{b}TTX_Startup.dfn@{ub}.
There is however a more elegant way of accomplishing the same thing.

The @{b}LINKS@{ub} section in a definition file is used to cause other definition
files to be read in automatically. For example, if a definition file
contains

	LINKS:
	  "TurboText:Support/MyDefs.dfn"
	#

the definition file @{b}TurboText:Support/MyDefs.dfn@{ub} is read in automatically.
The underlying concept for LINKS is identical to the C programming
language's #include directive.

Whenever TurboText encounters a section in a definition file, it replaces
its current definitions with the ones found in the definition file. That
is, when TurboText encounters a @{b}KEYBOARD@{ub} section in a definition file, all
currently defined key sequences are replaced by the new definitions. The
same is true for menu strips; when a @{b}MENUS@{ub} section is encountered, the
current menu strip is completely replaced by the new one.

The special @{b}APPEND@{ub} directive is extremely useful when combined with use of
the @{b}LINKS@{ub} section. When a definition file section is annotated with the
@{b}APPEND@{ub} directive, it tells TurboText you wish the definitions it contains
to be @{i}added @{ui}to the existing definitions instead of @{i}replacing @{ui}them.

For example, you can have a main definition file called @{b}TTX_Startup.dfn@{ub}
which looks like:

	KEYBOARD:
	  CTRL-A Insert "hello"
	  CTRL-B Insert "there"
	#

	LINKS:
	  TurboText:Support/TTX_Emul_PCNumPad.dfn
	#

When reading this definition file, TurboText replaces all of its keyboard
sequences with the two definitions included. After encountering the @{b}LINKS@{ub}
section, TurboText starts to read the @{b}TTX_Emul_PCNumPad.dfn@{ub} definition
file. This definition file looks like:

	KEYBOARD: APPEND
	  SHIFT-NP_NUML  SetMode Toggle

	  MODE-NP_INS    SetPrefs Overstrike Toggle
	  MODE-NP_END    MoveEOF
	  MODE-NP_DOWN   MoveDown
	  MODE-NP_PGDN   MoveDownScr
	  MODE-NP_LEFT   MoveLeft
	  MODE-NUM_PAD-5 NOP
	  MODE-NP_RIGHT  MoveRight
	  MODE-NP_HOME   MoveSOF
	  MODE-NP_UP     MoveUp
	  MODE-NP_PGUP   MoveUpScr
	  MODE-NP_NUML   SetMode OFF
	  MODE-NP_DEL    Delete
	#

Note the @{b}APPEND@{ub} directive next to the @{b}KEYBOARD@{ub} section header. This tells
TurboText to add the new definitions to the existing ones, instead of
replacing the existing ones. That means, the two keyboard definitions made
in the original definition file @{b}TTX_Startup.dfn@{ub} remain valid, the new
definitions are just grafted on.

@endnode


@node "Provided Definition Files"

As mentioned previously, the TurboText distribution disk includes many
different definition files in the @{b}TurboText:Support@{ub} drawer. There are some
which emulate different text editors, others provide non-English text for
