@node "TurboText And ARexx"

ARexx is an easy-to-use programming language in common use on the Amiga
that acts mostly as a scripting language for applications. ARexx comes
standard with most Amigas. Although TurboText can make good use of ARexx's
capabilities, ARexx is not required for correct operation - TurboText
works perfectly well without it.

Through ARexx, additional capabilities can be added to TurboText. You can
use TurboText's substantial set of commands as building blocks and
construct new, more complex commands out of them.

ARexx can also be used to link multiple applications together. From one
macro running in one application, you can easily control other
applications in the system.

This documentation does not attempt to explain the fundamental concepts
behind ARexx, nor how to write ARexx programs. We assume you have read the
ARexx documentation and understand it adequately. The TurboText
installation procedure copied a number of ARexx macros to the
@{b}TurboText:Rexx@{ub} directory - we recommend you browse through these macros,
which serve as good examples of what can be done using ARexx and TurboText
together.

	@{" ARexx In TurboText         " link "ARexx In TurboText"}
	@{" The Command Shell          " link "The Command Shell"}
	@{" Recorded Macros From ARexx " link "Recorded Macros From ARexx"}
	@{" The ARexx Macro Cache      " link "The ARexx Macro Cache"}
@remark !!!	@{" Escaping In ARexx Macros " link "Escaping In ARexx Macros"}
	@{" Return Values And Errors   " link "Return Values And Errors"}
	@{" Provided Macros            " link "Provided Macros"}

@endnode


@node "ARexx In TurboText"

ARexx macros communicate with running applications through standard Amiga
message ports. In addition to a single global message port, TurboText
provides a message port for every document window. The message ports
associated with the document windows are referred to as document ports.

The global message port, called @{b}TURBOTEXT@{ub}, is used to control the editor as
a whole, while the document ports are used to control the individual
document and their contents. Document ports are named @{i}TURBOTEXTnnn @{ui}where
@{i}nnn @{ui}is a number, such as @{b}TURBOTEXT0@{ub} or @{b}TURBOTEXT41@{ub}. The document port name
associated with a given document window can be found in the @{" Info " link "The Info Requester"}
requester.

Every time a new document is created, a new document port is created along
with it. When that document is closed, the port is also closed. During the
time a document remains open, it always has the same document port
associated with it.

TurboText provides well over 150 commands that can be used from ARexx to
interact with the editor. A subset of these commands can be used with the
global port, while all of them can be used with the document ports. The
@{" TurboText Command Reference " link "TurboText Command Reference"} provides a complete description of all the
commands supported by TurboText.

ARexx macros can be run easily from TurboText by choosing the
@{" Macros/Execute ARexx... " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command. Choosing this command causes the
@{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} to be opened, allowing you to choose a macro to execute.
TurboText macros usually have the special @{b}.ttx@{ub} file extension appended at
the end of their names to distinguish them from other macros.

When starting a macro from within TurboText, its default host address will
be set to the port associated with the current document. When starting a
macro from an external source, it is necessary to locate the correct
document port by inquiring of its name at the global port using the
@{" GetPort " link "GetPort"} command.

@endnode


@node "The Command Shell"

The TurboText command shell is a window where TurboText commands can be
typed in directly. Normally, commands are bound to menus and keyboard
sequences, but using the command shell it is possible to execute commands
directly by typing them in. In addition, the command shell lets you invoke
ARexx macros and other applications directly.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}The command shell is implemented itself as an ARexx macro.
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}This means that the shell is not available without ARexx.

To open the command shell, choose the @{" Windows/Open TTX Shell... " link "The Windows Menu"} menu
command. This command opens a window on top of the current document window.
You can then type TurboText commands directly in this window. For example,
you can open a new file by using the editor's @{" OpenFile " link "OpenFile"} command.

@{fg highlight}To open file using the command shell:@{fg text}

	1 - Open the command shell by choosing the
	    @{" Windows/Open TTX Shell... " link "The Windows Menu"} menu command.

	2 - Type

		OpenFile @{i}<filename>@{ui}

	    where @{i}<filename> @{ui}is the name of the file to open.

	3 - Press @{b}[Return]@{ub}.

Any of the TurboText commands listed in the @{" Command Reference " link "TurboText Command Reference"} can be
executed in this manner. If an error occurs during execution of the
command, the error is reported in the shell window.

If you type a command that TurboText does not understand, the shell
attempts to run the command as an ARexx macro.

@{fg highlight}To run an ARexx macro from the command shell:@{fg text}

	1 - Open the command shell.

	2 - Type the macro name:

		CountWords

	3 - Press @{b}[Return]@{ub}.

The @{b}CountWords@{ub} macro is then loaded and executed by ARexx. Just as when you
run macros from elsewhere in TurboText, it is assumed that the macro names
have a file extension of @{b}.ttx@{ub}.

If the command shell is not capable of running the command as an ARexx
macro, it then tries to run it as an AmigaDOS application.

@{fg highlight}To run an application from the command shell:@{fg text}

	1 - Open the command shell.

	2 - Type the name of the application:

		DIR

	3 - Press @{b}[Return]@{ub}.

The @{b}DIR@{ub} command is then loaded from disk and executed. Note that when
searching for an application, the command shell scans your current command
path to try to locate the application.

You can ask for help within the command shell by typing

	@{b}Help@{ub}

will show you the table of contents of the TurboText on-line
documentation. You can also enter

	@{b}Help @{i}<command name>@{ui}@{ub}

such as

	@{b}Help OpenFile@{ub}

in order to get a complete description of any given TurboText command.

To close the command shell you can click the close gadget of the window, or
you can type in @{b}Quit@{ub} and press @{b}[Return]@{ub}.

@endnode


@node "Recorded Macros From ARexx"

TurboText's @{" recorded macros " link "Recorded Macros"} provide a very convenient way to perform a
simple operation repeatedly. Recorded macros execute very fast. In fact,
they are many times faster than executing the same series of commands as an
ARexx macro.

A very useful technique to use when creating an ARexx macro is to use
recorded macros as much as possible within the ARexx macro. This can
increase the execution speed considerably.

Macro recording records anything you do with menus and keyboard commands,
and it also records any ARexx commands sent to the document port. So to
record a series of ARexx commands, you can do:

	RecordMacro
	MoveLeft
	MoveDown
	MoveEOL
	EndMacro

The above series of commands will cause a recorded macro to be created
which contains three commands: @{b}MoveLeft@{ub}, @{b}MoveDown@{ub}, and @{b}MoveEOL@{ub}. You can
then play back the recorded macro by using the @{" PlayMacro " link "PlayMacro"} command.

It is important to understand that only TurboText commands are recorded.
If you perform any ARexx function calls, or ARexx loops, or IF statements,
these will not be recorded, and playback of your macro will likely not
perform the action you want.

The @{" RecordMacro " link "RecordMacro"} command provides the @{b}QUIET@{ub} option. When this option is
specified, it tells TurboText to record the series of ARexx commands, but
to not execute them while recording. Once done recording, the sequence of
commands can be executed normally using the @{" PlayMacro " link "PlayMacro"} command.

For an example of using recorded macros from ARexx, we recommend you take a
look at the @{b}AddChars@{ub} ARexx macro supplied with TurboText.

@endnode


@node "The ARexx Macro Cache"

TurboText 2.0 features an ARexx macro cache which lets your ARexx macros
start much more quickly.

The first time you execute a macro, it is loaded in memory by TurboText.
ARexx is then invoked to execute the macro. The cache causes TurboText to
keep the macro loaded in memory even when the macro is done executing.
That way, the next time the macro is executed it does not need to be
loaded from disk. The cache can considerably speed up often used macros.

The cache has two limitations. First is that macro invocations where
arguments are passed to the macro cannot be cached. Only invocations with
no arguments can be cached. Second, the name of the macro used to launch
the macro should match exactly the name of the macro on disk, including the
@{b}.ttx@{ub} or @{b}.rexx@{ub} extension. Otherwise, TurboText may not find the macro file
and will not be able to add it to the cache.

The cache can pose a problem when developing and testing new macros. If
you write a macro and save it to disk, then run it, TurboText will load it
in memory the first time you run it, and will never load it from disk
again. If you are trying to make changes to the macro and must have it
reloaded from disk to pick up the changes, the cache can get in the way.
TurboText provides multiple services to help with this problem.

The @{" FlushARexxCache " link "FlushARexxCache"} command is provided to let you totally empty the
macro cache. After this command is executed, any macro executed will need
to be loaded from disk.

The @{" SetARexxCache " link "SetARexxCache"} command lets you control whether the macro cache is
active. Turning it off prevents TurboText from using macros in the cache,
and prevent new macros from being added to the cache. The @{" GetARexxCache " link "GetARexxCache"}
command can be used to determine the current state of the cache.

Finally, the @{b}NOCACHE@{ub} option of the @{" ExecARexxMacro " link "ExecARexxMacro"} command lets you
specifically instruct TurboText to not look in its cache for the macro
being run, and always get the macro from disk.

@endnode


@remark !!! @node "Escaping In ARexx Macros"
@remark !!!
@remark !!! Strings being passed to TurboText by ARexx must be either terminated by a
@remark !!! 0 byte or a linefeed. That is, if a string is being passed to TurboText
@remark !!! and that string contains a linefeed, TurboText treats the linefeed
@remark !!! character as the end of the string and does NOT process further characters
@remark !!! in the string.
@remark !!!
@remark !!! Since linefeed characters indicate the end of a string, then how can you
@remark !!! actually pass a linefeed character to TurboText? This is where escape
@remark !!! sequences come into play. Every string passed from ARexx to TurboText gets
@remark !!! escaped. Escaping is a feature that allows non-printing characters to be
@remark !!! represented within a string. The escaping mechanism used by TurboText is
@remark !!! identical to that used by AmigaDOS. That is, TurboText supports two escape
@remark !!! sequences: *N and *E. Whenever TurboText sees *N in a string, it replaces
@remark !!! it by a linefeed character (CTRL-J, ASCII code 10). *E is replaced by the
@remark !!! Escape character (ASCII code 27).
@remark !!!
@remark !!! The asterisk ("*") is thus used as an escape sequence introducer. To
@remark !!! actually include an asterisk in a string, the asterisk needs to be
@remark !!! doubled. An asterisk followed by a non-escaping character results in just
@remark !!! the character being processed (*a is like entering simply "a").
@remark !!!
@remark !!! The above is applicable in the regular case in TurboText, but there is an
@remark !!! exception which often can simplify things. Several TurboText commands have
@remark !!! a template specification containing /F arguments. For example, the TEXT
@remark !!! command has a template of "TEXT/F". For these arguments, specifying the
@remark !!! keyword name when calling the command causes the string to be interpreted
@remark !!! 'as is' without performing any escaping on it. For example:
@remark !!!
@remark !!!   Text "this is a test*n"
@remark !!!
@remark !!! would cause the string "this is a test" followed by a linefeed character
@remark !!! to be inserted into TurboText. On the other hand:
@remark !!!
@remark !!!   Text TEXT "this is a test*n"
@remark !!!
@remark !!! would cause the string "this is a test*n" to be inserted into TurboText.
@remark !!! Note that even while specifying the template argument name for a /F
@remark !!! argument, linefeeds are still interpreted as a string terminator.
@remark !!!
@remark !!! @endnode


@node "Return Values And Errors"

Many of TurboText's commands return values to the calling macro. Returned
values are always put in the ARexx @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable. As is normal in ARexx,
you need to enable results explicitly if you wish to get them. This is done
by including a line at the top of your ARexx macros:

	OPTIONS RESULTS

which tells ARexx you wish to receive results from commands.

Some commands return values relating to cursor positions within the
current document. These commands always return their results in a format
such as "line column" and not "column line". This is more convenient for
many applications. Note that line and column numbers start at 1, not 0.

Whenever a TurboText command is executed from an ARexx macro, it is
possible for the command to fail and return an error code. TurboText uses
the standard means of returning errors to ARexx macros, through the ARexx
@{b}RC@{ub} variable.

When a command is done executing, the special @{b}RC@{ub} variable can be examined
to determine whether the command was successful, or had a problem and
failed. When @{b}RC@{ub} is zero, it means the command worked correctly. Any other
value indicates an error - in fact, the greater @{b}RC@{ub}'s value, the more severe
the error.

The @{b}RC@{ub} variable provides what is known as an error-severity level. There
are 4 possible severity levels; the greater the value, the more severe the
error:

	0	Normal, there was no error

	5	Slight error, not fatal

	10	Serious error

	20	Fatal error

When a command failure is detected by looking at the @{b}RC@{ub} variable, two other
variables can be examined to learn more about the cause of the failure. The
@{b}TURBOTEXT.LASTERROR@{ub} variable contains the specific TurboText error code
describing the reason why the command failed. These errors are described in
detail in @{" Error Codes And Messages " link "Error Codes And Messages"}.

Depending on the value returned in @{b}TURBOTEXT.LASTERROR@{ub}, a specialized error
code may be contained in @{b}TurboText.SPECIALERROR@{ub}. Specifically, if the
previous command failed due to an AmigaDOS error, the exact AmigaDOS error
code is stored in this variable. The same is true for ARexx errors.
Descriptions of the possible AmigaDOS and ARexx errors are contained
in @{" Error Codes And Messages " link "Error Codes And Messages"}.

@endnode


@node "Provided Macros"

Following is a description of what several of the ARexx macros provided
with TurboText do. These macros can be bound to any menu or key sequence.
Any macro can also be invoked by choosing the @{" Macros/Execute ARexx... " link "The Macros Menu"}
menu command and selecting the macro name from the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} that
appears. Finally, macros can be invoked directly from the @{" command shell " link "The Command Shell"}
by simply entering the name of the macro.

@{b}AddChars@{ub} 
Lets you add characters at the start of every line within the current
document. If a @{" selection block " link "Selection Blocks"} is currently defined, only the block is
affected. You can provide the characters to insert as parameters when
running this macro from the command shell. If no parameter is provided, a
small window is opened asking you to enter the characters to add.

@{b}CmdShell@{ub} 
This is the macro that implements the command shell, and it is usually
invoked through the @{" Windows/Open TTX Shell... " link "The Windows Menu"} menu command.

@{b}CommentBlk@{ub} 
Tranforms the currently @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} into an ARexx comment block. This
macro can be easily modified to create C, Modula-2 or Ada comments. Written
by Chris Bailey.

@{b}CountWords@{ub} 
Counts the number of words in the current document and reports it in the
document window's @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}.

@{b}Documentize@{ub} 
Removes linefeed characters from a TurboText document in order to create
documents suitable to be loaded in most word processors. This effectively
causes all paragraphs of the current document to appear as one long line.
Written by Denny Atkin.

@{b}ExecBlk@{ub} 
Executes the lines of the currently selected block as an AmigaDOS script
file. If no block is selected, executes the whole document.

@{b}GetKin@{ub} 
Loads a @{i}kin @{ui}file to the current document in another document window. Kin
files are files like @{b}test.c@{ub} and @{b}test.h@{ub}, basically files with the same names
but with different file extensions. The macro considers the following as
kin file extensions:

	.h and .c
	.h and .cpp
	.h and .cc
	.h and .cxx
	.i and .a
	.i and .asm
	.def and .mod

Additional kin file extensions can easily be added. Written by
Chris Bailey.

@{b}GetRef@{ub} 
Finds a reference to the word currently under the cursor, or to the word
passed in as an argument. If a reference is found, a new document window
is opened and the file containing the reference is loaded into the new
window. You use the @{b}MarkRef@{ub} macro to add words to the reference file.

@{b}Hanoi@{ub} 
This macro solves the Towers Of Hanoi problem using TurboText to provide
an animated solution.

@{b}InsertVersion@{ub} 
Creates and inserts an AmigaDOS version string at the current cursor
position. The version string is made up of the current document name, and
of the current date. Once a version string is in a file, the AmigaDOS
@{b}Version@{ub} command can be used to obtain the version of the file. Written by
Chris Bailey.

@{b}MarkAutoDocRef@{ub} 
Enters all the functions from the currently loaded autodoc file in the
reference file, so they can later be used by @{b}GetRef@{ub}. Autodoc files are
special documentation files distributed by Commodore to programmers.

@{b}MarkRef@{ub} 
Enters the word currently under the cursor as a reference in the reference
file, so it can later be used by @{b}GetRef@{ub}.

@{b}NextParagraph@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the next paragraph within the current document.

@{b}NumberLines@{ub} 
Adds line numbers before every line in the current document.

@{b}OrganizeWindows@{ub} 
Organizes all opened document windows on the current screen into one of
four layouts. The layouts are specified by passing an argument to the
macro. You can request one of CASCADE, ICONIFY, STACK, and TILE.

@{b}PrevParagraph@{ub} 
Moves the cursor to the previous paragraph within the current document.

@{b}PrintBlk@{ub} 
Prints the currently selected block to the system printer.

@{b}RemoveBlankLines@{ub} 
Removes all empty lines from the current document.

@{b}SaveBlk@{ub} 
Saves the currently selected block to a file on disk. The filename can be
provided as a parameter. If it is not, then the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} is opened
letting you enter a filename.

@{b}SaveChangedDocs@{ub} 
Saves all currently loaded document that have been modified since their
last save.

@{b}SaveLayout@{ub} 
Creates an ARexx macro that when run, will reset the editor to the same
state it is in when SaveLayout was run. This lets you shut down TurboText
using a single command, come back later and run a simple macro which will
reload all the documents that were previously loaded, put the cursor back
in the same position, etc. You can provide as parameters the name of the
macro to create, as well as a SHUTDOWN option. Written by Michael Sinz.

@{b}SelectDoc@{ub} 
Displays a list of all currently loaded documents and lets you pick one by
number. After picking one, the document is then activated and brought to
the front. Written by Neil Lucking.

@{b}SetDfn@{ub} 
Checks the extension of a file as it is being loaded, and loads an
appropriate @{" definition file " link "Definition Files"} to configure TurboText to deal with a file
of that type. You can easily add new extensions to this script to make it
smarter. This script is mostly useful when installed as a replacement for
the usual @{" Project/Open... " link "The Project Menu"} and @{" Project/Open New... " link "The Project Menu"} menu commands.

@{b}ShowAG@{ub} 
Displays the current section of text as an AmigaGuide document. If a block
is selected, then the block is displayed. If no block is selected, then if
the cursor is in the middle of an AmigaGuide node, that node is displayed.
If the cursor is not in the middle of a node, the whole document is
displayed.

@{b}SortBlk@{ub} 
Alphabetically sorts all the lines of the currently selected block. If no
block is selected, sorts the whole document. This macro requires that the
AmigaDOS @{b}Sort@{ub} command be in your system's C: directory. Written by
Gerald R. Duprey Jr.

@{b}StripANSI@{ub} 
Removes all ANSI escape sequences from the currently loaded document.

@{b}StripMan@{ub} 
Removes any UNIX @{i}man@{ui} formatting commands found in the current document.
Written by Bill Barton.

@{b}UnsetLocks@{ub} 
This macro is very useful when developing and testing ARexx macros. It
goes through all documents currently loaded in TurboText and unlocks any
set input or display locks that are found.

@endnode







