@node "The Calculator"

TTXCalc is a calculator providing basic math operations as well as many
additional features often needed by programmers. Conversion between
various number bases, control of bit size of operations, and full keyboard
control are features making TTXCalc a very useful addition to a
programmer's set of tools.

	@{" Data Entry Model    " link "Data Entry Model"}
	@{" Starting TTXCalc    " link "Starting TTXCalc"}
	@{" Supported Functions " link "Supported Functions"}

@endnode


@node "Data Entry Model"

TTXCalc uses a data entry model similar to the traditional TI calculators,
which is:

	{(number) (operation) (number)} (=)

For example, the operation @{b}Add 2 and 5@{ub} requires the following keys be
entered:

	2
	+
	5
	=

The operation @{b}Multiply 4 by 3 and subtract 2@{ub} is accomplished with:

	4
	x
	3
	-
	2
 	=

Operations supported by TTXCalc fall into one of three classes:

	· Immediate operations

	· High-priority binary operations

	· Low-priority binary operations

Immediate operations affect the currently displayed value only. For
example, hitting the @{b}+/-@{ub} gadget inverts the sign of the currently displayed
value only and does not affect the rest of the current sequence of
operations. @{b}NOT@{ub}, @{b}«SH@{ub} and @{b}RO»@{ub} are other examples of Immediate operations.

High-priority binary operations involve two numbers and are evaluated
immediately. For example, the multiplication operation gets evaluated as
soon as the second number involved in the operation is entered. This is as
opposed to the behavior of the low-priority operations such as addition
which are delayed. This follows the normal conventions adopted in
mathematics. For example:

	2+3*6=

gives 20, and not 30. The multiplication gets evaluated before the
addition since it is a high-priority operation. A few more examples:

	2+3*6+7= (gives 27)

	2+3*6/2= (gives 11 because / is a high-priority operator)

As seen in the above example, when there are several operators of the same
priority in a given expression, they are evaluated from left to right.
This is consistent with the way TI calculators operate.

TTXCalc also supports parenthesis in the normal way, which means that
expressions enclosed in parenthesis are evaluated before other expressions
regardless of the priority of the involved operators.

@endnode


@node "Starting TTXCalc"

TTXCalc can be run from within TurboText by choosing the
@{" Windows/Open Calculator... " link "The Windows Menu"} menu command. It can also be run as a
stand-alone application from Shell or Workbench.

To start TTXCalc from Workbench, simply double-click its icon. You can
specify a single tool type in TTXCalc's icon. The @{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} tool type let's
you specify the name of the public screen the calculator should open on. If
there is no @{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} tool type or if the named screen is not found, the
calculator opens on the Workbench screen.

When starting TTXCalc from Shell, you can specify the screen name as a
command-line argument. You must surround the name with quotes if it
contains any spaces.

Once the calculator is started, it can be quit by clicking its close gadget
or by pressing @{b}[Esc]@{ub}.

@endnode


@node "Supported Functions"

All functions supported by TTXCalc are listed in the table below. The first
column shows the text used on the calculator's gadgets, the second shows
the keyboard equivalents for the gadgets. For example, pressing @{b}s@{ub} or @{b}S@{ub} on
the keyboard is the same as clicking on the @{b}STO@{ub} gadget. The third column in
the table shows the priority of the operation attached to the gadget: @{b}H@{ub} is
High, @{b}L@{ub} is Low, and @{b}I@{ub} is Immediate. The final column gives a brief
description of the operation attached to the gadget.

	CA		@{b}[Del]@{ub}		I	Clear All, reset to
						initial state

	CE		@{b}[SpaceBar]@{ub}	I	Clear Entry, reset the
						current entry back to 0

	+		+		L	Arithmetic addition

	-		-		L	Arithmetic subtraction

	x		* or x		H	Arithmetic multiplication

	÷		/ or ÷		H	Arithmetic division

	MOD		M or %		H	Arithmetic modulo

	AND		&		H	Logical AND operation

	OR		O or |		H	Logical OR operation

	XOR		X or ^		H	Logical exclusive OR operation

	NOT		~ or !		I	Logical negation

	«RO		,		I	Binary rotate left

	RO»		.		I	Binary rotate right

	«SH				I	Logical shift left

	SH»				I	Logical shift right

	STO		S		I	Store the currently displayed
 						value in backup memory

	RCL		R		I	Recall the value stored in the
						backup memory

	+/-		T or ± 		I	Toggle the sign of the
						currently displayed value.
						This only works when
						operating in signed mode.

	=		= or @{b}[Return]@{ub}	H	Performs all pending
						operations and yields a
						result. This closes any
						opened parenthesis for you
 						before performing the
						calculations.

The calculator offers 3 cycle gadgets which allow you to choose number
base, bit size, and whether the calculations should be signed or unsigned.

	Number Base		N	I	Change the number base.
						There are 4 possible number
						bases:

 							@{b}BIN@{ub} (base 2)
 							@{b}OCT@{ub} (base 8)
 							@{b}DEC@{ub} (base 10)
 							@{b}HEX@{ub} (base 16)

	Bit Width		W	I	Change the number of bits
 						used to perform operation.
						There are 3 possible bit
						sizes:

 							@{b}Byte@{ub} (8 bits)
 							@{b}Word@{ub} (16 bits)
 							@{b}LWord@{ub} (32 bits).

	Signed Mode		U	I	Toggle between @{b}Sgnd@{ub} (signed)
						and @{b}Usgnd@{ub} (unsigned)
						arithmetic.

Additional keyboard support includes use of @{b}0@{ub}-@{b}9@{ub} and @{b}A@{ub}-@{b}F@{ub} to enter numbers, @{b}(@{ub}
and @{b})@{ub} to isolate expressions, @{b}[Backspace]@{ub} to delete the right-most digit on
the display, and finally @{b}[Esc]@{ub} or @{b}Q@{ub} to quit the program.

