@node "Emulations"

Emulations are used to make TurboText behave like other popular text
editors. Several such emulations are included on the distribution disk to
help you in the transition from an older editor up to TurboText. We highly
recommend you use TurboText in its standard configuration as you can
access all of the program's features under a simple and consistent
framework.

The provided emulations are not perfect. They reproduce most of the
interface of the other editors within reasonable limits. Some editors have
a totally different underlying operating model from TurboText, making them
difficult to emulate faithfully. Still, we hope the emulations will make
you feel more comfortable when starting to use TurboText by reducing the
"culture shock".

This section presents, in broad terms, the emulations included with
TurboText. No attempt is made to explain every detail, as we assume that
if you wish to emulate another editor, it is because you already know how
to operate this other editor. More attention is given to operational
differences rather than describing all the features.

	@{" Overview            " link "Emulations Overview"}
	@{" Supplied Emulations " link "Supplied Emulations"}
	@{" Keyboard Extensions " link "Keyboard Extensions"}

@endnode


@node "Emulations Overview"

Emulations are implemented by using TurboText's @{" definition files " link "Definition Files"} in
combination with @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros. As such, they are totally
user-configurable and you can adapt them to your liking. All the emulations
require ARexx for them to be fully functionality.

To select an emulation, choose the @{" Prefs/Open Definitions... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu
command and select the desired emulation from the file requester that
appears. If you plan on using an emulation permanently, you should modify
your @{b}TTX_Startup.dfn@{ub} to include a @{" LINKS " link "Linking Multiple Definition Files"} section such as:

	LINKS:
  	  "TurboText:Support/@{i}<emulation name>@{ui}"
	#

where @{i}<emulation name> @{ui}is the name of the emulation you wish to use. For
example:

	LINKS:
	  "TurboText:Support/TTX_Emul_MEMACS.dfn"
	#

would load in the MEMACS emulation every time the editor is started.

Some features found in the original text editors cannot easily be emulated
in TurboText, or simply do not make any sense. In these cases, TurboText
simply ignores any attempt to use such functions.

@endnode


@node "Supplied Emulations"

@{b}TTX_Emul_BRIEF.dfn@{ub} 
Provides a fairly complete emulation of the MS-DOS BRIEF editor. Functions
specific to the PC-compatible world are not implemented, and in many cases
not needed. Written by Jamie Clark.

@{b}TTX_Emul_CED.dfn@{ub} 
Provides menu and keyboard definitions to emulate the CygnusEd 3.5 editor.
The emulation is fairly complete, although many menu functions bring up
requesters instead of performing the action directly. The non-standard CED
Environment menu is instead split into 3 separate menus.

@{b}TTX_Emul_Ed.dfn@{ub} 
Contains menu and keyboard definitions to emulate the AmigaDOS 2.0 Ed
editor. The menus are virtually identical to the standard Ed menus.
Extended commands are also supported, but repeating extended commands is
not.

@{b}TTX_Emul_MEMACS.dfn@{ub} 
Contains menu and keyboard definitions to emulate the AmigaDOS 2.0 MEMACS
editor.

@{b}TTX_Emul_QEdit.dfn@{ub} 
Contains menu and keyboard definitions to roughly emulate the MS-DOS QEdit
editor. The emulation is not exact because there are various things that
QEdit and TurboText do differently, the most obvious of which are block
commands, window operations, and macros. Written by Chris Bailey.

@{b}TTX_Emul_TxEd.dfn@{ub} 
Provides a relatively faithful emulation of TxEd+ 2.0. Almost all
operations are identical, except for printing the clipboard which
automatically sends the output to the current @{b}Print Device@{ub} (as defined in
the @{" Miscellaneous " link "Preferences - Miscellaneous"} section of the preferences requester) instead of
opening up the file requester to let you pick a print device.

@{b}TTX_Emul_WordStar.dfn@{ub} 
Offers a rather complete emulation of the standard WordStar keyboard
command set. The only significant difference is in the way selection
blocks are handled. TurboText always attaches the end of the selection
block to the current cursor position, while WordStar doesn't. This means
commands to move the cursor to the start of the block, or hide the block
do not work.

@endnode


@node "Keyboard Extensions"

The following definition files modify the standard TurboText keyboard
layout to make it work like other systems.

@{b}TTX_Emul_PCNumPad.dfn@{ub} 
Offers definitions to use the numeric keypad as a PC-compatible keypad.
After loading this file the keypad will operate normally until you enter
@{b}[NumericPad]-[Shift]-(@{ub} which causes the keypad to execute the functions
indicated in front of the keys as on a PC-compatible keyboard when the
NumLock key is off.

@{b}TTX_Emul_VTNumPad.dfn@{ub} 
And its associated ARexx macros provide keyboard definitions to use the
numeric keypad as if it were a keypad on DEC's line of VT terminals. This
keypad emulation requires several ARexx macros to operate. These macros
should be present in a directory called TTX_VT located in the normal REXX:
directory.

The Delete and Undelete keys are incompatible with the "standard" key
definitions for those functions. For instance, you cannot use Gold-Minus to
undelete what was deleted using @{b}[Shift]-[Del]@{ub}.

Because of ARexx quoting conventions, undeleting text strings containing
quotes and/or asterisks will likely not correctly undelete the deleted
text.

These are interpreted macros and they require time to execute. While not
excessively slow, processing of some keys may not be able to keep up with
rapid keystrokes.

Written by Marc A. Criley.

@{b}TTX_Emul_Northgate.dfn@{ub} 
Contains keyboard definitions to support the Northgate OmniKey ULTRA
keyboard. All "dead" keys are activated. Keys perform their labelled
functions whenever appropriate. The following keys are defined:

	· Rate Select          Open New

	· Print Screen         Delete

	· [Ctrl]-Print Screen  Print current file

	· Scroll Lock          Current window to front

	· Pause                Current window to back

	· Num Lock             Keypad (

	· [Shift]-Num Lock     Keypad )

	· [F11]                Save current file

	· [F12]                Open new file

Written by Denny Atkin.

@endnode







