@node "Reference Conventions"

The commands are listed here under the standard headings Format, Template,
Release, Purpose, Specifications, and See Also. The letter case of
TurboText commands and options is not important. Options are listed here
in capital letters simply to distinguish them from the rest of the text.

The @{" Format " link "Reference Format"} and @{" Template " link "Reference Templates"} listings are two alternate ways of indicating
the proper usage of TurboText commands. These both show the type and
function of any parameters (extra input items given with a command) that a
command might accept, whether they are required or optional, their order,
punctuation, etc...

The Release section indicates in which version of TurboText the command was
introduced. Most commands were present in the initial release of the
product, while new ones were added in every release.

The Purpose section gives a brief one line description of the role of the
command.

The Specifications section is the main command description. All the
command's parameters are discussed, along with the various aspects of its
possible usage.

Finally, the See Also section refers you to other commands or sections of
this documentation which are related to the current command.

@endnode


@node "Reference Format"

In Format listings, parameters are enclosed in various kinds of brackets
or braces to indicate the type of parameter, and separated by spaces. The
brackets and braces are not to be typed as part of the command.

	< >	Angle brackets enclose parameters whose content, such as a
		filename or numerical value, must be supplied. For instance,
		<filename> means that you must enter the appropriate filename
		in that position when you give the command. These brackets
		are @{b}not@{ub} to be typed as part of the command.

	[ ]	Square brackets enclose optional parameters; options are
		accepted by the command but are not required. The brackets
		are @{b}not@{ub} to be typed as part of the command.

	{ }	Braces enclose items that can be repeated any number of
		times. The braces are @{b}not@{ub} to be typed as part of
		the command.

	|	Vertical bars mean @{b}or@{ub} and are used to separate
		options of which you can choose one. For instance,
		[ON | OFF | TOGGLE] means that you can choose the ON option,
		the OFF option, or the TOGGLE option. The vertical bar is
		@{b}not@{ub} to be typed as part of the command.

@endnode


@node "Reference Templates"

In Template listings, parameters are followed by a slash (/) and a capital
letter to indicate the type of parameter, and are separated by commas. The
slash/letter combinations and commas are not to be typed as part of the
command.

The template specifications described in this section are identical to the
standard AmigaDOS template specifications used in AmigaDOS commands.

	<parameter>/A	The parameter must @{b}A@{ub}lways be included in order
			for the command to be accepted.

	<option>/K	The option's @{b}K@{ub}eyword must be given. For
			example, TurboText's command-line allows the
			specification of a public screen on which the editor
			is to open its windows. The option is specified as
			PUBSCREEN/K in the template. This means the PUBSCREEN
			keyword must be included in front of the name of the
			screen. For example @{b}PUBSCREEN=screenname@{ub}.

	<option>/S	The option simply works as a @{b}S@{ub}witch. If the
			switch option keyword is included, the option is @{b}on@{ub},
			if it is not included, the option is @{b}off@{ub}. You
			must therefore type the name of the option in order
			to specify the option.

	<value>/N 	Indicates that a @{b}N@{ub}umeric parameter (rather
			than text) is expected. By preceding a number with
			a @{b}$@{ub} symbol or with the @{b}0x@{ub} sequence, you can
			provide the number in hexadecimal (base 16) form.

	<parameter>/M	@{b}M@{ub}ultiple parameters accepted - the template
			equivalent of the braces @{b}{}@{ub}.

	<string>/F	The string must be the @{b}F@{ub}inal parameter on
			the command-line. The entire remainder of the
			command-line is taken as the desired string,
			double quotes are not necessary even if the
			string contains spaces.

	, (comma)	Indicates the command takes no parameters.

@endnode


