@node "ExecARexxMacro"

Format:		ExecARexxMacro [CONSOLE] [LOCKINPUT] [LOCKDISPLAY] [NOCACHE]
				[macro name]

Template:	CONSOLE/S,LOCKINPUT/S,LOCKDISPLAY/S,NOCACHE/S,NAME/F

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Execute an ARexx macro.

Specifications: 
ExecARexxMacro executes an @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macro. This command is mostly useful as
a keyboard or menu assignment.

The CONSOLE option causes a console window to be opened when the macro is
run. The console window provides a default input and output environment to
the macro. If the CONSOLE option is not specified, the macro's IO is sent
to the NIL: device, which means all output is ignored, and any input
attempts fail.

Starting with TurboText 2.0, the LOCKINPUT and LOCKDISPLAY options let you
automatically turn on the input and display locks before starting the
macro. The locks are automatically turned off again once the macro ends.

Starting with TurboText 2.0, the NOCACHE option lets you specifically
instruct TurboText to not look in its @{" ARexx macro cache " link "The ARexx Macro Cache"} for this macro.
This is useful when developing new macros.

The optional NAME parameter specifies the name of the macro file to
execute. If the macro name is not present, then the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} is
opened allowing the user to select a file. Note that when a macro name is
specified, it may be fully qualified (i.e. have a complete directory path),
in order to override ARexx's default macro search path.

The default extension for ARexx macros in TurboText is @{b}.ttx@{ub}. You may omit
this extension in the macro name, although macros will execute slightly
faster if the extension is supplied. Macros are searched for according to
the normal rules imposed by ARexx.

This command requires that ARexx be correctly installed in your system.

See Also: @{" ExecARexxString " link "ExecARexxString"}
	  @{" SaveMacro       " link "SaveMacro"}

	  @{" Macros/Execute ARexx... " link "The Macros Menu"}

@endnode


@node "ExecARexxString"

Format:		ExecARexxString [CONSOLE] [LOCKINPUT] [LOCKDISPLAY] <macro>

Template:	CONSOLE/S,LOCKINPUT/S,LOCKDISPLAY/S,MACRO/F

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Execute an ARexx string macro.

Specifications: 
ExecARexxString executes an @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} string macro. This command is mostly
useful as a keyboard or menu assignment.

The CONSOLE option causes a console window to be opened when the macro is
run. The console window provides a default input and output environment to
the macro. If the CONSOLE option is not specified, the macro's IO is sent
to the NIL: device, which means all output is ignored, and any input
attempts fail.

Starting with TurboText 2.0, the LOCKINPUT and LOCKDISPLAY options let you
automatically turn on the input and display locks before starting the
macro. The locks are automatically turned off again once the macro ends.

The MACRO parameter contains the macro to execute. That is, unlike
@{" ExecARexxMacro " link "ExecARexxMacro"}, this command does not load the macro from a disk file,
but instead treats the argument itself as the macro. Refer to the ARexx
documentation for more information on string file macros.

This command requires that ARexx be correctly installed in your system.

See Also: @{" EndMacro       " link "EndMacro"}
	  @{" ExecARexxMacro " link "ExecARexxMacro"}
	  @{" SaveMacro      " link "SaveMacro"}

@endnode


@node "ExecTool"

Format:		ExecTool [PORT] [SCREEN] [ASYNC] [tool name]

Template:	PORT/S,SCREEN/S,ASYNC/S,NAME/F

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Execute an external tool.

Specifications: 
ExecTool is used to start a program from within the editor.

The optional NAME parameter specifies the disk name of the tool to execute,
which may include a complete path specification. If the tool name is not
present, then the @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} is opened allowing the user to select a
file.

If the PORT option is specified, the editor passes the current @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"}
port name as a command-line argument to the tool, which is useful if the
tool wishes to communicate with the editor. If the SCREEN option is
specified, the editor passes the @{" public screen " link "Public Screens"} name where the current
@{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"} is opened, which is useful in order to open a tool on
the same screen as the editor.

After the tool is started, the editor waits until the tool completes before
continuing with normal editing. To avoid this, you can specify the ASYNC
option.

@endnode


@node "Find"

Format:		Find [find string]

Template:	FIND/F

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Find a string within the current document.

Specifications: 
This command searches the current document for the specified text string.
The search operation can proceed forward or backward in the document, can
ignore letter case, can ignore diacritical marks, and can restrict its
search to complete words. These options are controlled through the @{" Find " link "The Find Requester"}
requester or by the @{" SetPrefs " link "SetPrefs"} command.

The optional parameter specifies the string to search for. If the
parameter is not specified, the current default search string is used.
When the string is provided, it is used for the search, and becomes the
default search string.

The find string parameter can contain simple @{i}wildcards. @{ui}The question mark
(?) can be used to mean "match any character". For example, entering @{b}h?llo@{ub}
as a search string causes strings such as @{b}hallo@{ub}, @{b}h4llo@{ub} or @{b}h-llo@{ub} to be
considered matches.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Executing a Find operation with no find string parameter can be
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}substantially faster than when a find string is provided. This is
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}due to the fact a complicated search pattern has to be generated
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}every time a new find string is provided. When no find string is
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}provided, the previous search pattern is used directly.

See Also: @{" FindChange    " link "FindChange"}
	  @{" OpenRequester " link "OpenRequester"}

	  @{" Search/Find...   " link "The Search Menu"}
	  @{" Search/Find Next " link "The Search Menu"}

@endnode


@node "FindChange"

Format:		FindChange [ALL] [FIND <find string>] [change string]

Template:	ALL/S,FIND/K,CHANGE/F

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Find and change a string within the current document.

Specifications: 
FindChange searches the current document for the FIND parameter and
replaces it with the CHANGE parameter. The search operation can proceed
forward or backward in the document, can ignore letter case, can ignore
diacritical marks, and can restrict its search to complete words. These
options are controlled through the @{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"} requester or by the
@{" SetPrefs " link "SetPrefs"} command.

The optional parameters specify the string to search for, and the string
to replace it with. If either parameter is not specified, the default
strings are used. When the parameters are provided, they are used for the
search, and become the default strings. The ALL option causes the
operation to be performed for all strings found until the end of the
document is reached.

After this command executes, the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable contains the
number of strings that were changed.

The find string parameter can contain simple @{i}wildcards. @{ui}The question mark
(?) can be used to mean "match any character". For example, entering @{b}h?llo@{ub}
as a search string causes strings such as @{b}hallo@{ub}, @{b}h4llo@{ub} or @{b}h-llo@{ub} to be
considered matches.

 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}Executing a Find operation with no find string parameter can be
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}substantially faster than when a find string is provided. This is
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}due to the fact a complicated search pattern has to be generated
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}every time a new find string is provided. When no find string is
 @{fg highlight} »»»  @{fg text}provided, the previous search pattern is used directly.

The change string parameter can also contain wildcard characters, as long
as the number of wildcards in it does not exceed the number in the find
string.

To demonstrate how wildcards may be used, consider the following:

	Find	@{b}?all ?an@{ub}
	Change	@{b}?ame ?en@{ub}

If the FindChange command is executed using the above strings, the
following are possible matches and replacements:

	Matched Text	Replaced Text

	Tall Pan	Tame Pen
	Fall Man	Fame Men
	Tall Man	Tame Men
	Tall Dan	Tame Den
	Mall Tan	Mame Ten

See Also: @{" Find          " link "Find"}
	  @{" OpenRequester " link "OpenRequester"}

	  @{" Search/Find & Change... " link "The Search Menu"}

@endnode


@node "FormatParagraph"

Format:		FormatParagraph

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Format the current paragraph using the right margin.

Specifications: 
FormatParagraph modifies lines in a paragraph so they contain as many words
as the current @{" right margin " link "Preferences - Editing"} allows. Linefeeds are inserted in lines
longer than the right margin, and linefeeds are removed in lines shorter
than the right margin. A blank line, or a line starting with a space
indicates the end of the paragraph. The right margin can be adjusted in the
@{" Editing " link "Preferences - Editing"} section of the preferences requester or by using the @{" SetPrefs " link "SetPrefs"}
command.

See Also: @{" Center  " link "Center"}
	  @{" Justify " link "Justify"}

	  @{" Extras/Format Paragraph " link "The Extras Menu"}

@endnode


@node "FlushARexxCache"

Format:		FlushARexxCache

Template:	,

Release:	Version 2.0

Purpose: 
Empty the ARexx macro cache.

Specifications: 
FlushARexxCache removes all macros from the editor's @{" ARexx macro cache " link "The ARexx Macro Cache"}.
This means that ARexx macros executed after this command will be loaded
from disk instead of being taken from the cache.

This command is useful when developing and testing ARexx macros, to remove
them from the cache to force them to be loaded from disk.

See Also: @{" GetARexxCache " link "GetARexxCache"}
	  @{" SetARexxCache " link "SetARexxCache"}

@endnode


@node "GetARexxCache"

Format:		GetARexxCache

Template:	,

Release:	Version 2.0

Purpose: 
Return the current whether the ARexx macro cache is currently on.

Specifications: 
GetARexxCache returns whether the editor's @{" ARexx macro cache " link "The ARexx Macro Cache"} is
currently enabled. When enabled, macros that are run are automatically kept
in memory by TurboText. The next time the macros are run, the version in
memory is automatically used instead of having to reload it from disk
again.

The information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists
of either ON or OFF, depending if the editor is in background mode or not.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" FlushARexxCache " link "FlushARexxCache"}
	  @{" SetARexxCache   " link "SetARexxCache"}

@endnode


@node "GetBackground"

Format:		GetBackground

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return the current setting of the background mode option.

Specifications: 
GetBackground returns whether the editor is currently running in
@{" background " link "Startup Options"} mode. When running in background mode, the editor will remain
in memory even when all documents are closed, awaiting for a
@{" hot key sequence " link "Hot Key Sequences"} to activate it.

The information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists
of either ON or OFF, depending if the editor is in background mode or not.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" SetBackground " link "SetBackground"}

@endnode


@node "GetBlk"

Format:		GetBlk <stem variable name>

Template:	STEM/A

Release:	Version 2.0

Purpose: 
Return the contents of the currently selected block to an ARexx macro.

Specifications: 
GetBlk returns the text from the currently @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} to an ARexx
macro, in the form of a stem variable. The single required parameter is the
name of the stem variable which should receive the lines of the selected
block.

If this command is called with

  GetBlk lines.

TurboText will fill in the stem variable with the following:

  lines.0  contains the number of lines that were in the selected block
  lines.1  contains the text for the first line in the selected block
  lines.2  contains the text for the second line in the selected block
  ...
  lines.n  contains the text for the last line in the selected block.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" GetBlkInfo " link "GetBlkInfo"}
	  @{" MarkBlk    " link "MarkBlk"}

@endnode


@node "GetBlkInfo"

Format:		GetBlkInfo

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return information about the currently selected block.

Specifications: 
GetBlkInfo returns information about the currently @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"}. The
information specifies whether there is a selected block, whether it is a
@{" vertical " link "Vertical Selection Blocks"} or horizontal block, and the coordinates of the start of the
selected area.

The information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists
of two on/off values and a pair of coordinates. The first on/off value
indicates whether there is currently a selected block, the second value
indicates whether the block is vertical, and the pair of coordinates
indicate the line and column where the selection block starts. For example,
if there is currently a normal selection block defined starting at line 23
and column 19, the RESULT variable will hold @{b}ON OFF 23 19@{ub} (ON says that
there is indeed a selected block, and OFF says that the block is not
vertical).

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" GetBlk  " link "GetBlk"}
	  @{" MarkBlk " link "MarkBlk"}

@endnode


@node "GetChar"

Format:		GetChar

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return the character currently under the cursor.

Specifications: 
GetChar returns the character currently under the cursor. The character is
returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable. If the cursor is currently at the
end of the document, ASCII value 0 is returned.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" GetLine " link "GetLine"}
	  @{" GetWord " link "GetWord"}
	  @{" SetChar " link "SetChar"}

@endnode


@node "GetCurrentDir"

Format:		GetCurrentDir

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return the current directory associated with the current document.

Specifications: 
GetCurrentDir returns the full name of the current directory associated
with the current document. Every document has a distinct current directory
associated with it, just like every process on the Amiga has its own
current directory.

The information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists
of a complete directory path describing the current directory.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" GetFileInfo   " link "GetFileInfo"}
	  @{" GetFilePath   " link "GetFilePath"}
	  @{" SetCurrentDir " link "SetCurrentDir"}
	  @{" SetFilePath   " link "SetFilePath"}

@endnode


@node "GetCursor"

Format:		GetCursor

Template:	,

Release:	Version 2.0

Purpose: 
Return whether the text cursor is currently displayed.

Specifications: 
GetCursor returns whether the text cursor is currently displayed. The
information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists of
either ON or OFF, depending whether the cursor is being displayed or not.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" SetCursor " link "SetCursor"}

@endnode


@node "GetCursorPos"

Format:		GetCursorPos [FOLDS]

Template:	FOLDS/S

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return information about the current cursor position.

Specifications: 
GetCursorPos returns the current cursor position, and whether there is a
@{" fold " link "Folds"} on the current line.

The information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists
of two numbers indicating respectively the line and column where the cursor
is located, followed by a yes/no value indicating whether the line on which
the cursor is has a fold attached to it, followed by a number indicating
how many characters there are from the start of the line to the current
column, and finally followed by the number of characters from the start of
the document to the current cursor position. The format of the returned
value is @{b}line column fold characterFromSOL characterFromSOF@{ub} such as
@{b}10 32 NO 25 238@{ub} to indicate the cursor is on line 10, column 32,
the current line doesn't have a fold attached, there are 25 characters
from the start of the line to the current position, and there are 238
characters from the start of the document to the current position.

The value indicating the number of characters from the beginning of the
line is useful for dealing with lines containing tab characters. If the
editor's @{" tab width " link "Preferences - Tabs"} setting is currently 8, and you enter @{b}[Tab]@{ub} while the
cursor is sitting in the first column in the editor, the cursor will move
to column 8. Entering @{b}[Tab]@{ub} again will move the cursor to column 16. In
this position, the character count returned by GetCursorPos would be 2,
since there are only two characters between the start of the line and the
current position.

When the FOLDS option is provided, the returned line number and count of
characters from the beginning of the document both include in their
calculations any currently hidden @{" folds " link "Folds"} above the current line. This is
useful in order to determine the actual line or character number within the
document.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" Move     " link "Move"}
	  @{" MoveChar " link "MoveChar"}

@endnode


@node "GetDocuments"

Format:		GetDocuments

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return a list of the currently loaded documents.

Specifications: 
GetDocuments returns a list of all the documents currently loaded in the
editor, and their associated ARexx port names.

The list is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists of the
name of a loaded document enclosed in double quotes, followed by the port
name to access this document, then another document name, and a port name,
and so on. The document names match the titles of the document windows. So
if TurboText currently has three documents loaded called @{b}Test.doc@{ub}, @{b}Book.doc@{ub}
and @{b}Manual.doc@{ub}, the returned value for this command might look like:

	@{b}"Test.doc" TURBOTEXT0 "Book.doc" TURBOTEXT1 "Manual.doc" TURBOTEXT2@{ub}

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" GetPort " link "GetPort"}

@endnode


@node "GetErrorInfo"

Format:		GetErrorInfo <error number>

Template:	AMIGADOS/S,ERROR/N/A

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return a text string describing a specific editor or AmigaDOS error.

Specifications: 
GetErrorInfo returns a string describing an editor error number. This
command is similar to the AmigaDOS @{b}Fault@{ub} command. The ERROR parameter
corresponds to one of the possible @{" editor error numbers " link "TurboText Errors"}.

The resulting error string is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable and
consists of the same text that would be displayed in the editor's status
area when encountering the error associated with the given error number.

After a command fails, the TURBOTEXT.LASTERROR ARexx variable holds the
error number describing the cause of the error. This error number is what
this command expects.

Starting with TurboText 2.0, the AMIGADOS option can be specified, and
indicates that the error number supplied is an AmigaDOS error number.
TurboText then queries the system to obtain an error string for the error
number.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" BeepScreen   " link "BeepScreen"}
	  @{" Screen2Front " link "Screen2Front"}
	  @{" SetStatusBar " link "SetStatusBar"}
	  @{" Window2Front " link "Window2Front"}

@endnode


@node "GetFileInfo"

Format:		GetFileInfo

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return information about the current document.

Specifications: 
GetFileInfo returns information about the current document, including the
number of lines in the document, whether the document has been modified
since it was last saved, and the current document name.

The information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists
of three entries indicating respectively the number of lines in the
document, whether the document has been modified or not, and the current
document name enclosed in double quotes. For example, @{b}231 YES "Test.doc"@{ub}
indicates the document has 231 lines, it has been modified since the last
save, and its name is @{b}Test.doc@{ub}.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" GetCurrentDir " link "GetCurrentDir"}
	  @{" GetFilePath   " link "GetFilePath"}
	  @{" GetPort       " link "GetPort"}

@endnode


@node "GetFilePath"

Format:		GetFilePath

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return the complete file path and name leading to the current document on
disk.

Specifications: 
GetFilePath returns the complete file path for the current document. The
last component in the path is the actual name of the document. The path is
returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" GetCurrentDir " link "GetCurrentDir"}
	  @{" GetFileInfo   " link "GetFileInfo"}
	  @{" SetFilePath   " link "SetFilePath"}

@endnode


@node "GetLine"

Format:		GetLine [start column] [end column]

Template:	STARTCOL/N,ENDCOL/N

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return the text of the current line.

Specifications: 
GetLine returns the text of the line currently under the cursor. The
information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable.

The optional parameters specify which part of the line to return. If these
are not provided, the entire line is returned. If the end column exceeds
the maximum character on this line, the returned value is correctly
truncated. If only the starting column parameter is provided, all
characters from that position to the end of the line are returned,
excluding any linefeed (LF) character that may be terminating the line. As
such, executing a @{b}GetLine 1@{ub} command has the same effect as a @{b}GetLine@{ub}
command, but it never returns the linefeed character at the end of the
line.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" GetChar " link "GetChar"}
	  @{" GetWord " link "GetWord"}

@endnode


@node "GetLockInfo"

Format:		GetLockInfo

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return information about the state of the available editor locks.

Specifications: 
GetLockInfo returns the on/off state of the editor's display and input
locks.

The information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists
of two on/off values indicating respectively whether the display lock is
on, and whether the input lock is on.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" SetDisplayLock " link "SetDisplayLock"}
	  @{" SetInputLock   " link "SetInputLock"}

@endnode


@node "GetMacroInfo"

Format:		GetMacroInfo

Template:	,

Release:	Version 2.0

Purpose: 
Return information about the state of the command recorder.

Specifications: 
GetMacroInfo returns whether the editor has a recorded macro available,
whether recording is in progress, and whether commands are being recorded
quietly.

The information is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable, and consists
of three on/off values indicating respectively whether there is currently
a macro available to be played, whether the editor is currently recording,
and whether the editor is currently recording in quiet mode. If the editor
is currently recording, this command will itself not be recorded.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" EndMacro       " link "EndMacro"}
	  @{" ExecARexxMacro " link "ExecARexxMacro"}
	  @{" OpenMacro      " link "OpenMacro"}
	  @{" PlayMacro      " link "PlayMacro"}
	  @{" RecordMacro    " link "RecordMacro"}
	  @{" SaveMacro      " link "SaveMacro"}

@endnode


@node "GetPort"

Format:		GetPort [document name]

Template:	NAME/F

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return the ARexx port name associated with a loaded document.

Specifications: 
GetPort returns the name of the ARexx port associated with a given document
name. The port name is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable. NAME
specifies the name of the document, and is the same thing that appears in
the title bar of document windows. The port name returned can be used by a
subsequent ARexx @{b}ADDRESS@{ub} command.

If no document name is given, the name of the port associated with the
current document is returned. When sending GetPort to the
@{" global TurboText port " link "Global Commands"}, you have to specify a document name.

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

@endnode


@node "GetPrefs"

Format:		GetPrefs [ARexxConsoleName | AutoDeiconify |
			AutoDetectBinFiles | AutoEraseBlocks |
			AutoIndent | AutoSave | AutoSaveConfirm |
			AutoSaveDelay | AutoTrackCursor | AutoWindow2Front |
			BackupTemplate | BackgroundColor |
			BufferedWindow | CantBackupConfirm
			ChangeString | ChunkyMode | ConversionOnLoad |
			ConversionOnPrint | ConversionOnSave |
			CorrectCase | DoubleLoadConfirm | DynamicMargin |
			FilePattern | FindBackward | FindDoPatterns |
			FindIgnoreAccents | FindIgnoreCase | FindString |
			FindWholeWords | FoldIndent | FontName |
			FontNameGadgets | FontSize | FontSizeGadgets |
			FreeForm | IconTool | LineWrap | MakeBackups |
			MaxBackupVersion |
			MouseBlanker | Overstrike | OverwriteConfirm |
			PrintDevice | RightMargin | SaveEOLAs |
			SaveIcons | ScreenMode | ScreenName | ScreenSize |
			ScrollGadget | SelectWhenDragging | ShowEOF |
			ShowEOLS | ShowSpaces | ShowTabs | StripEOLBlanks |
			TabsGiveSpaces | TabWidth | TabWidthDisk | TextColor |
			TranslateCRs | WordWrap | ZoomGadget]

Template:	PREFS/A

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Return the current value of a preferences setting.

Specifications: 
GetPrefs returns the current value of any preferences option. The single
parameter expected by this command specifies which preference option to
return. The value is returned in the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} RESULT variable.

The format of the return value varies depending on which option is being
queried. The following options return either ON or OFF:

	AutoIndent			AutoDeiconify
	AutoDetectBinFiles		AutoEraseBlocks
	AutoSave			AutoSaveConfirm
	AutoTrackCursor			AutoWindow2Front
	BufferedWindow			CantBackupConfirm
	ChunkyMode			CorrectCase
	DoubleLoadConfirm		DynamicMargin
	FindBackward			FindDoPatterns
	FindIgnoreAccents		FindIgnoreCase
	FindWholeWords			FreeForm
	LineWrap			MakeBackups
	MouseBlanker			Overstrike
	OverwriteConfirm		SaveIcons
	SelectWhenDragging		ShowEOF
	ShowEOLS			ShowSpaces
	ShowTabs			StripEOLBlanks
	TabsGiveSpaces			TranslateCRs
	WordWrap			ZoomGadget

The remaining options are:

	ARexxConsoleName	returns the name of the ARexx console

	AutoSaveDelay		returns the current auto save delay in
				minutes

	BackgroundColor		returns the current pen number used to
				render the background of text

	BackupTemplate		returns the current backup template

	ChangeString		returns the current Change string

	ConversionOnLoad	return the tab conversion type applied
				when loading. 0 is none, 1 is tabs to spaces,
				and 2 is spaces to tabs

	ConversionOnPrint	return the tab conversion type applied
				when printing. 0 is none, 1 is tabs to spaces,
				and 2 is spaces to tabs

	ConversionOnSave	return the tab conversion type applied
				when saving. 0 is none, 1 is tabs to spaces,
				and 2 is spaces to tabs

	FilePattern		returns the default pattern for the file
				requester

	FindString		returns the current Find string

	FoldIndent		returns the current fold indent level

	FontName		returns the current font name

	FontNameGadgets		returns the current font name used for
				gadgets

	FontSize		returns the current font size

	FontSizeGadgets		returns the current font size used for
				gadgets

	IconTool		returns the current icon tool

	MaxBackupVersion	returns the current maximum backup version

	PrintDevice		returns the device name used when printing

	RightMargin		returns the current right margin

	SaveEOLAs		returns a number indicating how TurboText
				indicates the end of a line in files that it
				creates. 0 means that the LF character is
				used, 1 means that the CR character is used,
				2 means that both CR and LF are used, and
				3 means that the same end-of-line character
				that was in the file when it was loaded will
				be used when saving the file.

        ScreenMode		returns the current preferred screen mode
        			for the current document. This is a
        			graphics database mode id, and requires
        			Amiga programming knowledge to interpret.

	ScreenName		returns the current preferred public screen
				name for the current document.

	ScreenSize		returns the current screen width,height in
				pixels

	ScrollGadget		returns the current state of the scroll
				gadget. 0 means the gadget is on the right,
				1 means it is on the left, and 2 means there
				is no scroll gadget in the current document
				window

	TabWidth		returns the current tab size

	TabWidthDisk		returns the current tab size for external
				files

	TextColor		returns the current pen number used to
				render the foreground of text

This command can only be used through the ARexx interface.

See Also: @{" OpenDefinitions " link "OpenDefinitions"}
