@node "SplitView"

Format:		SplitView [ON | OFF | TOGGLE]

Template:	ON/S,OFF/S,TOGGLE/S

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Split or unify the current document.

Specifications: 
SplitView controls whether the current @{" document window " link "The TurboText Document Window"} shows the two
document @{" views " link "Multi-View Editing"} simultaneously. The ON option forces the document window
to show both views, the OFF option forces the document window to show only
one view, and the TOGGLE option toggles the current setting.

See Also: @{" CenterView  " link "CenterView"}
	  @{" GetViewInfo " link "GetViewInfo"}
	  @{" ScrollView  " link "ScrollView"}
	  @{" SizeView    " link "SizeView"}
	  @{" SwapViews   " link "SwapViews"}
	  @{" SwitchView  " link "SwitchView"}
	  @{" UpdateView  " link "UpdateView"}

	  @{" Windows/Views/Split " link "The Windows Menu"}

@endnode


@node "SwapChars"

Format:		SwapChars

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Exchange the character currently under the cursor with the previous
character.

Specifications: 
SwapChars exchanges the character under the cursor with the previous
character within the current document. If the cursor is currently on the
first or last character of a line, this command does nothing.

See Also: @{" GetChar    " link "GetChar"}
	  @{" Insert     " link "Insert"}
	  @{" InsertLine " link "InsertLine"}
	  @{" SetChar    " link "SetChar"}

@endnode


@node "SwapViews"

Format:		SwapViews

Template:	,

Release:	Version 2.0

Purpose: 
Swap the contents of the two views.

Specifications: 
SwapViews swaps the contents of the two views. The top view will contain
what the bottom view used to contain, and vice-versa.

See Also: @{" CenterView  " link "CenterView"}
	  @{" GetViewInfo " link "GetViewInfo"}
	  @{" ScrollView  " link "ScrollView"}
	  @{" SizeView    " link "SizeView"}
	  @{" SplitView   " link "SplitView"}
	  @{" SwitchView  " link "SwitchView"}
	  @{" UpdateView  " link "UpdateView"}

	  @{" Windows/Views/Swap " link "The Windows Menu"}

@endnode


@node "SwitchView"

Format:		SwitchView

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Change the active view.

Specifications: 
SwitchView switches the display and input to the other @{" view " link "Multi-View Editing"}, making it
the active view.

The editor allows both views to be on screen at once, or views can take
over the entire display. This command does the necessary work to make any
hidden view visible.

See Also: @{" CenterView  " link "CenterView"}
	  @{" GetViewInfo " link "GetViewInfo"}
	  @{" ScrollView  " link "ScrollView"}
	  @{" SizeView    " link "SizeView"}
	  @{" SplitView   " link "SplitView"}
	  @{" SwapViews   " link "SwapViews"}
	  @{" UpdateView  " link "UpdateView"}

	  @{" Windows/Views/Toggle " link "The Windows Menu"}

@endnode


@node "Text"

Format:		Text <text>

Template:	TEXT/F

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Insert text in the current document, bypassing formatting and case
correction.

Specifications: 
This command inserts characters in the current document, bypassing any
text altering option currently active. Characters are guaranteed to be
inserted as is. The single parameter specifies the characters to insert.

See Also: @{" Insert     " link "Insert"}
	  @{" InsertLine " link "InsertLine"}
	  @{" SetChar    " link "SetChar"}

@endnode


@node "ToggleCharCase"

Format:		ToggleCharCase [FORCEUPPER | FORCELOWER]

Template:	FORCEUPPER/S,FORCELOWER/S

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Modify the letter case of the character currently under the cursor.

Specifications: 
ToggleCharCase inverts the letter case of the character currently under
the cursor, and moves the cursor right by one character. Only alphabetical
characters are affected by this command, all other characters are ignored.

Starting with TurboText 2.0, the FORCEUPPER and FORCELOWER options cause
ToggleCharCase to convert the character under the cursor to a specific
letter case, instead of just toggling the current letter case.

See Also: @{" GetChar " link "GetChar"}
	  @{" Insert  " link "Insert"}
	  @{" SetChar " link "SetChar"}
	  @{" Text    " link "Text"}

@endnode


@node "ToggleFold"

Format:		ToggleFold

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Toggles the hidden state of a fold.

Specifications: 
If the cursor is currently on a hidden @{" fold " link "Folds"}, ToggleFold acts like
@{" ShowFold " link "ShowFold"} and displays the contents of the fold. If the cursor if
currently on an exposed fold, ToggleFold acts like @{" HideFold " link "HideFold"} and hides
the fold.

See Also: @{" HideFold   " link "HideFold"}
	  @{" MakeFold   " link "MakeFold"}
	  @{" ShowFold   " link "ShowFold"}
	  @{" UnmakeFold " link "UnmakeFold"}

@endnode


@node "UndeleteLine"

Format:		UndeleteLine

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Insert the last line that was deleted using DeleteLine.

Specifications: 
UndeleteLine inserts the text of the last line that was deleted using the
DeleteLine command. If no line has previously been deleted, this command
has no effect.

See Also: @{" UndoLine " link "UndoLine"}

	  @{" Extras/Undelete Line " link "The Extras Menu"}

@endnode


@node "UndoLine"

Format:		UndoLine

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Undo all the modifications made to the current line.

Specifications: 
UndoLine undoes any modifications made to the current line since the
cursor was moved to it. If no changes have been made, this command has no
effect.

See Also: @{" UndeleteLine " link "UndeleteLine"}

	  @{" Extras/Undo Line " link "The Extras Menu"}

@endnode


@node "UnmakeFold"

Format:		UnmakeFold [NESTED | ALL]

Template:	NESTED/S,ALL/S

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Expand folds.

Specifications: 
UnmakeFold expands and removes @{" folds " link "Folds"}. Invoked by itself, this command
unmakes the fold currently under the cursor only. When provided the NESTED
option all folds within the current fold are also unmade. When passed the
ALL option, all folds within the current document are unmade.

See Also: @{" HideFold   " link "HideFold"}
	  @{" MakeFold   " link "MakeFold"}
	  @{" ShowFold   " link "ShowFold"}
	  @{" ToggleFold " link "ToggleFold"}

	  @{" Folds/Unmake/Single " link "The Folds Menu"}
	  @{" Folds/Unmake/Nested " link "The Folds Menu"}
	  @{" Folds/Unmake/All    " link "The Folds Menu"}

@endnode


@node "UpdateView"

Format:		UpdateView [ALL]

Template:	ALL/S

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Force an update of the display.

Specifications: 
UpdateView forces the editor to update the contents of the current document
@{" view " link "Multi-View Editing"}. This is done by first erasing all characters and redisplaying
them. This command is mostly useful from within an @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macro which has
locked the display using @{" SetDisplayLock " link "SetDisplayLock"}.

The ALL option can be provided to cause all currently visible document
views to be updated. This includes the @{" hex window " link "Editing Binary Files"}, if opened, and the
second view when operating in split view mode.

See Also: @{" CenterView  " link "CenterView"}
	  @{" GetViewInfo " link "GetViewInfo"}
	  @{" ScrollView  " link "ScrollView"}
	  @{" SizeView    " link "SizeView"}
	  @{" SplitView   " link "SplitView"}
	  @{" SwitchView  " link "SwitchView"}
	  @{" SwapViews   " link "SwapViews"}

@endnode


@node "UsurpWindow"

Format:		UsurpWindow <port name>

Template:	PORT/A

Release:	Version 2.0

Purpose: 
Steal a document window from another document.

Specifications: 
The purpose of this command is to allow one document to steal the window
from another document.

The PORT parameter specifies the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} port name associated with the
document to steal the window from. The document you send this command to
will appear on-screen in what used to be the window associated with the
document indicated by the PORT parameter.

If the document you send the command to already has its own window opened,
it is first closed. If the target document doesn't have a window opened,
no error is reported.

Here's an example to clarify the use of this command. Assume the following:

	Document Name     Port Name    Window Number

	test.c            TURBOTEXT1   1
	hello.c           TURBOTEXT2   2

If you send an @{b}UsurpWindow TURBOTEXT2@{ub} command to the @{b}TURBOTEXT1@{ub} port, the
result will be:

	Document Name     Port Name    Window Number

	test.c            TURBOTEXT1   2
	hello.c           TURBOTEXT2   <none>

The command told the document holding @{b}test.c@{ub} to steal the window of the
document holding @{b}hello.c@{ub}.

See Also: @{" ControlWindow " link "ControlWindow"}
	  @{" GetDocuments  " link "GetDocuments"}
	  @{" IconifyWindow " link "IconifyWindow"}

@endnode


@node "Window2Back"

Format:		Window2Back

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Send the current document window behind all other windows.

Specifications: 
Window2Back sends the current document window to the back of all windows
in the screen on which the editor is running.

See Also: @{" BeepScreen   " link "BeepScreen"}
	  @{" GetErrorInfo " link "GetErrorInfo"}
	  @{" Screen2Back  " link "Screen2Back"}
	  @{" Screen2Front " link "Screen2Front"}
	  @{" SetStatusBar " link "SetStatusBar"}
	  @{" Window2Front " link "Window2Front"}

@endnode


@node "Window2Front"

Format:		Window2Front

Template:	,

Release:	Version 1.0

Purpose: 
Bring the current editor window in front of all windows.

Specifications: 
Window2Front brings the current document window to the front of all
windows in the screen on which the editor is running.

See Also: @{" BeepScreen   " link "BeepScreen"}
	  @{" GetErrorInfo " link "GetErrorInfo"}
	  @{" Screen2Back  " link "Screen2Back"}
	  @{" Screen2Front " link "Screen2Front"}
	  @{" SetStatusBar " link "SetStatusBar"}
	  @{" Window2Back  " link "Window2Back"}

@endnode







@remark **********************************************************************
@remark **********************************************************************







@node "Error Codes And Messages"

The errors that can occur when TurboText fails to complete an operation
can be divided into four main categories:

	@{" TurboText Errors       " link "TurboText Errors"}
	@{" Definition File Errors " link "Definition File Errors"}
	@{" AmigaDOS Errors        " link "AmigaDOS Errors"}
	@{" ARexx Errors           " link "ARexx Errors"}

This section lists the various errors that can be encountered when using
TurboText, their severity level, their probable cause, and suggestions for
recovery.

@endnode


@node "TurboText Errors"

The general errors which can occur while using TurboText are listed here in
numerical order according to their error codes. Following the error code is
the error message which is displayed in the document window's
@{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"} when the error occurs.

The error code is useful for @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros only. This is the value
returned in the ARexx @{b}TURBOTEXT.LASTERROR@{ub} variable when an error occurs.
Passing this error code back to the @{b}GetErrorInfo@{ub} command returns the error
message to the ARexx macro.

The severity level is another value which is only useful for ARexx macros.
This value is returned in the ARexx @{b}RC@{ub} variable. When @{b}RC@{ub} equals 0, the
previous operation succeeded, while any other value indicates there was an
error. The higher this value, the more severe the error.

Finally, certain errors return specialized error codes in the ARexx
@{b}TURBOTEXT.SPECIALERROR@{ub} variable.

	Error	Description
	Code

	7       @{" Hit document boundary                 " link "Hit document boundary"}
	8       @{" Not on {, [, (, }, ] or )             " link "Not on {, [, (, }, ] or )"}
	9       @{" Not allowed in read-only mode         " link "Not allowed in read-only mode"}
	10      @{" User requested abort                  " link "User requested abort"}
	11      @{" Bookmark not set                      " link "Bookmark not set"}
	12      @{" No block marked                       " link "No block marked"}
	13      @{" More '?' in 'Change' than in 'Find'   " link "More '?' in 'Change' than in 'Find'"}
	14      @{" No fold on current line               " link "No fold on current line"}
	15      @{" Already a fold on current line        " link "Already a fold on current line"}
	16      @{" Not currently recording               " link "Not currently recording"}
	17      @{" Not found                             " link "Not found"}
	18      @{" Clipboard is empty                    " link "Clipboard is empty"}
	19      @{" Clipboard does not contain text       " link "Clipboard does not contain text"}
	20      @{" Clipboard device not found            " link "Clipboard device not found"}
	21      @{" ARexx process or library not found    " link "ARexx process or library not found"}
	22      @{" Command only allowed in ARexx macros  " link "Command only allowed in ARexx macros"}
	23      @{" Bookmark not found                    " link "Bookmark not found"}
	24      @{" No macro to play                      " link "No macro to play"}
	25      @{" Template or word not found            " link "Template or word not found"}
	26      @{" Not enough characters for Comp.Temp.  " link "Not enough characters for Comp.Temp."}
	27      @{" Too many characters                   " link "Too many characters"}
	28      @{" Illegal while recording               " link "Illegal while recording"}
	29      @{" Illegal command or arguments          " link "Illegal command or arguments"}
	30      @{" Not enough memory                     " link "Not enough memory"}
	31      @{" Load error                            " link "Load error"}
	32      @{" Save error                            " link "Save error"}
	33      @{" Backup error - not saved              " link "Backup error - not saved"}
	34      @{" Print error                           " link "Print error"}
	35      @{" Clipboard I/O error                   " link "Clipboard IO error"}
	36      @{" ARexx error                           " link "ARexx error"}
	37      @{" Couldn't execute tool                 " link "Couldn't execute tool"}
	38      @{" AmigaGuide error                      " link "AmigaGuide error"}
	39	@{" Couldn't open ARexx console           " link "Couldn't open ARexx console"}
	40      @{" Command requires a window             " link "Command requires a window"}
	41	@{" AmigaGuide library not found          " link "AmigaGuide library not found"}
@endnode


@node "Hit document boundary"

Severity level: 5

Probable Cause: 
The cursor cannot be moved beyond the bounds of the document. For example,
it cannot be moved to lines beyond the current maximum line.

Recovery: 
Restrict cursor positioning operations to within the document boundaries.

@endnode


@node "Not on {, [, (, }, ] or )"

Severity level: 5

Probable Cause: 
The cursor must be positioned on a bracket in order to try to match a
bracket.

Recovery: 
Position the cursor on a bracket and retry the operation. Supported
brackets consist of the following characters:

	[  ]  {  }  (  )  <  >  «  »

@endnode


@node "Not allowed in read-only mode"

Severity level: 5

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to modify the contents of the document while it was in
@{" read-only mode " link "Read-Only Mode"}.

Recovery: 
Turn off read-only mode and retry the operation.

@endnode


@node "User requested abort"

Severity level: 5

Probable Cause: 
The last operation was aborted by the user. There are a few common cases
where this can happen:

  - Clicking 'Cancel' in a confirmation requester. For example, if the
    editor opens a requester asking: @{b}Clear without saving changes?@{ub},
    clicking on Cancel aborts the ClearFile operation.

  - Pressing @{b}[Esc]@{ub} during a Find or Find & Change operation.

  - Closing a @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} without selecting a file.

This error will mostly be encountered by ARexx macros.

Recovery: 
To avoid encountering this error during the execution of an ARexx macro,
you can lock out user input using the @{" SetInputLock " link "SetInputLock"} command, as well as
making use of the QUIET option available with many commands. Note that it
is much better to allow the user to abort operations, rather than locking
the input.

@endnode


@node "Bookmark not set"

Severity Level: 5

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to move to the position indicated by a @{" bookmark " link "Bookmarks"}
which was never set.

Recovery: 
Always set bookmarks prior to attempting to jump to them.

@endnode


@node "No block marked"

Severity level: 5

Probable Cause: 
An operation requiring a @{" selected block " link "Selection Blocks"} of text was attempted without
having a block selected.

Recovery: 
Select a block and retry the operation.

@endnode


@node "More '?' in 'Change' than in 'Find'"

Severity level: 5

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to perform a Find & Change operation while the number
of wildcard characters (question marks) was greater in the Change string
than in the Find string.

Recovery: 
Refer to the discussion of the @{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"} requester for more
information on how wildcarding works.

@endnode


@node "No fold on current line"

Severity level: 5

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to hide, show or unmake a @{" fold " link "Folds"} on a line which
doesn't have a fold.

Recovery: 
Make sure the cursor is positioned on a fold and retry the operation. The
fold can either be currently hidden or not.

@endnode


@node "Already a fold on current line"

Severity level: 5

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to create a @{" fold " link "Folds"} on a line which already has a fold.
It is not possible to have two folds starting at the same line.

Recovery: 
Move the cursor to a line without a fold, and retry the operation.

@endnode


@node "Not currently recording"

Severity level: 5

Probable Cause: 
This error is generated if you ask the editor to stop @{" recording a macro " link "Recorded Macros"}
while it wasn't recording a macro in the first place.

@endnode


@node "Not found"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
This error is generated whenever the editor cannot locate something it was
searching for. This happens during Find operations or Match Bracket
operations.

@endnode


@node "Clipboard is empty"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to read from the clipboard while it contained nothing.
There must already be something in the clipboard in order to read from it.

Recovery: 
Copy data to the clipboard and retry the operation. Copying data to the
clipboard can be done using the @{" Edit/Cut " link "The Edit Menu"} or @{" Edit/Copy " link "The Edit Menu"} menu commands.

@endnode


@node "Clipboard does not contain text"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to read from the @{" clipboard " link "Using The Clipboard"} while it contained
non-ASCII data such as graphics or sound.

Recovery: 
Copy text data to the clipboard and retry the operation. Copying data to
the clipboard can be done using the @{" Edit/Cut " link "The Edit Menu"} or @{" Edit/Copy " link "The Edit Menu"} menu
commands.

@endnode


@node "Clipboard device not found"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
The system file @{b}DEVS:clipboard.device@{ub} could not be loaded from disk. It was
either not found, or there was not enough memory to load it in memory.

Recovery: 
Insure that the file @{b}clipboard.device@{ub} is present in your system's DEVS:
directory and there is sufficient memory to load it in memory. The
@{b}clipboard.device@{ub} file comes standard with every Amiga and is always
available unless explicitly deleted.

@endnode


@node "ARexx process or library not found"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
When attempting to execute an ARexx macro, the RexxMast program was not
running in your system or the file @{b}rexxsyslib.library@{ub} could not be loaded
from disk.

Recovery: 
Verify the ARexx documentation to insure ARexx is properly installed in
your system and make sure there is sufficient memory to invoke ARexx
macros.

@endnode


@node "Command only allowed in ARexx macros"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
Certain commands can only be executed from within ARexx macros and are not
allowed in keyboard or menu mappings.

Recovery: 
Consult the @{" TurboText Command Reference " link "TurboText Command Reference"}, for more information on the
command which caused this error.

@endnode


@node "Bookmark not found"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to move to the position indicated by a @{" bookmark " link "Bookmarks"}, but
the position no longer existed. This happens if the line pointed to by a
bookmark has been deleted for example.

Recovery: 
Do not delete lines on which bookmarks are set.

@endnode


@node "No macro to play"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to play a macro while no macro was currently in memory.

Recovery: 
Record a macro using the @{" Macros/Record Macro " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command, or load a
macro from disk using the @{" Macros/Open Macro... " link "The Macros Menu"} menu command, and retry
the operation.

@endnode


@node "Template or word not found"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
The @{" template completion " link "Templates"} algorithm, the @{" word correction " link "Word Correction"} algorithm or
the word @{" case correction " link "Word Correction"} algorithm could not locate the current word in
their respective dictionaries.

Recovery: 
Load in the correct dictionary using the @{" Prefs/Open Definitions... " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu
command, or add the unknown word to the current definition file, so it will
be known.

@endnode


@node "Not enough characters for Comp.Temp."

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
The @{" template completion " link "Templates"} algorithm failed due to multiple entries in the
template list which could match the current template.

Recovery: 
Additional characters should be entered to allow the algorithm to
distinguish between templates.

@endnode


@node "Too many characters"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
The @{" template completion " link "Templates"} algorithm, the @{" word correction " link "Word Correction"} algorithm and
the @{" case correction " link "Word Correction"} algorithm can handle up to 80 characters at a time,
no more.

Recovery: 
Do not try to apply the algorithms to words of more than 80 characters of
length.

@endnode


@node "Illegal while recording"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
Certain operations cannot be performed while the editor is
@{" recording a macro " link "Recorded Macros"}.

Recovery: 
Turn off recording mode by selecting the @{" Macros/Stop Recording " link "The Macros Menu"} menu
command, and retry the operation.

@endnode


@node "Illegal command or arguments"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
An illegal command, or a command with illegal parameters has been
encountered while processing an ARexx macro.

From @{" ARexx " link "Return Values And Errors"} macros, the @{b}TURBOTEXT.SPECIALERROR@{ub} variable holds the
AmigaDOS error code describing the error.

Recovery: 
Verify that all commands being passed to the editor are valid editor
commands, and make sure their parameters are also correct. You can consult
the @{" TurboText Command Reference " link "TurboText Command Reference"}, for a complete description of all
commands and their supported parameters.

From ARexx macros, the variable @{b}TURBOTEXT.SPECIALERROR@{ub} holds the AmigaDOS
error code describing why the command was rejected.

@endnode


@node "Not enough memory"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
There was not enough memory to perform the last operation.

Recovery: 
Free up some memory in the system by closing unused documents or
applications and retry the operation.

@endnode


@node "Load error"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
There was an AmigaDOS error while loading from a file on disk. The most
likely cause of this error is a media defect.

When this error is encountered, the specific AmigaDOS error is displayed in
the status area of the editor. See the @{" AmigaDOS Errors " link "AmigaDOS Errors"} section below for
a complete list of possible DOS errors.

From @{" ARexx " link "Return Values And Errors"} macros, the @{b}TURBOTEXT.SPECIALERROR@{ub} variable holds the
AmigaDOS error code describing the error.

Recovery: 
Correct any media defect and retry the operation.

@endnode


@node "Save error"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
There was an AmigaDOS error while saving to a file on disk. The save
operation did not complete and a possibly-incomplete file remains on disk.
The most likely causes of this error are a full disk, or a media defect.

When this error is encountered, the specific AmigaDOS error is displayed in
the status area of the editor. See the @{" AmigaDOS Errors " link "AmigaDOS Errors"} section below for
a complete list of possible DOS errors.

From @{" ARexx " link "Return Values And Errors"} macros, the @{b}TURBOTEXT.SPECIALERROR@{ub} variable holds the
AmigaDOS error code describing the error.

Recovery: 
Insure that there is enough room on the disk you wish to save to. Also
correct any media defects. This will possibly require saving to a
different disk. Then retry the operation.

@endnode


@node "Backup error - not saved"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
There was an AmigaDOS error while creating a file backup during a save
operation. The save operation which caused a backup to be created was not
executed.

When this error is encountered, the specific AmigaDOS error is displayed in
the status area of the editor. See the @{" AmigaDOS Errors " link "AmigaDOS Errors"} section below for
a complete list of possible DOS errors.

From @{" ARexx " link "Return Values And Errors"} macros, the @{b}TURBOTEXT.SPECIALERROR@{ub} variable holds the
AmigaDOS error code describing the error.

Recovery: 
Verify the current @{b}Backup Template@{ub} as specified in the @{" Backup Creation " link "Preferences - Backup Creation"}
section of the preferences requester. Alternatively turn off backup
creation.

@endnode


@node "Print error"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
There was an AmigaDOS error while writing to the printer.

When this error is encountered, the specific AmigaDOS error is displayed in
the status area of the editor. See the @{" AmigaDOS Errors " link "AmigaDOS Errors"} section below for
a complete list of possible DOS errors.

From @{" ARexx " link "Return Values And Errors"} macros, the @{b}TURBOTEXT.SPECIALERROR@{ub} variable holds the
AmigaDOS error code describing the error.

Recovery: 
Make sure the printer is properly connected and operational and that the
correct printer driver has been selected in Preferences.

@endnode


@node "Clipboard IO error"
@title "Clipboard I/O error"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
There was an error during transfer to or from the @{" clipboard " link "Using The Clipboard"}. This is
most likely due to a lack of memory.

Recovery: 
Make sure there is enough memory for proper clipboard operation.

@endnode


@node "ARexx error"

Severity level: (depends on ARexx macro)

Probable Cause: 
This error is returned when an @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macro started by the editor fails.
The severity level is determined by the ARexx macro.

When this error is encountered, the specific ARexx error is displayed in
the document window's @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}. See the @{" ARexx Errors " link "ARexx Errors"} section below
for more information.

From @{" ARexx " link "Return Values And Errors"} macros, the @{b}TURBOTEXT.SPECIALERROR@{ub} variable holds the ARexx
error code describing the error.

@endnode


@node "Couldn't execute tool"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
There was an AmigaDOS error when attempting to run an external tool. Most
likely the external tool was not found, or there was not enough memory to
run it.

Recovery: 
Insure the @{" ExecTool " link "ExecTool"} command is being passed the correct parameters and
that there is enough memory to run the tool.

@endnode


@node "AmigaGuide error"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
This error is returned when an @{b}AmigaGuide@{ub} document launched by TurboText
reports an error.

When this error is encountered, the specific AmigaGuide error is displayed
in the document window's @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"}.

@endnode


@node "Couldn't open ARexx console"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
There was an AmigaDOS error when attempting to open the @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} console
window. The likely reason for this failure is that the @{b}ARexx Console@{ub} gadget
in the @{" Miscellaneous " link "Preferences - Miscellaneous"} section of the preferences requester contains an
invalid console specification.

Recovery: 
Insure the @{b}ARexx Console@{ub} gadget contains a valid specification.

@endnode


@node "Command requires a window"

Severity level: 10

Probable Cause: 
An attempt was made to execute a command requiring a document window,
while the document window was closed.

Recovery: 
Open the document window using the @{" ControlWindow " link "ControlWindow"}
command, and retry the command.

@endnode


@node "AmigaGuide library not found"

Severity level: 20

Probable Cause: 
The file @{b}LIBS:amigaguide.library@{ub} could not be loaded from disk. It was
either not found, or there was not enough memory to load it in memory.

Recovery: 
Insure that the file @{b}amigaguide.library@{ub} is present in your system's LIBS:
directory and there is sufficient memory to load it in memory. The
TurboText installation process normally puts it there for you. Also make
sure there is sufficient memory to launch an AmigaGuide document.

@endnode


@node "Definition File Errors"

Following is a list of the errors that can occur when the editor reads in a
definition file. These error messages are normally fairly self-explanatory
and typically occur following a typo when creating the definition file.
When the cause of an error is not clear, refer to @{" Definition Files " link "Definition Files"}, for
information.

	@{" Invalid command specification      " link "Invalid command specification"}
	@{" Invalid keyboard sequence          " link "Invalid keyboard sequence"}
	@{" Invalid mouse sequence             " link "Invalid mouse sequence"}
	@{" Unknown MENUS directive            " link "Unknown MENUS directive"}
	@{" Incorrect MENU specification       " link "Incorrect MENU specification"}
	@{" Incorrect ITEM specification       " link "Incorrect ITEM specification"}
	@{" Incorrect SUB specification        " link "Incorrect SUB specification"}
	@{" Invalid Hot Key command            " link "Invalid Hot Key command"}
	@{" Templates must start with a letter " link "Templates must start with a letter"}
@endnode


@node "Invalid command specification"

This error occurs when a command associated with a @{" menu " link "Changing The Menus"} or @{" keyboard " link "Changing The Keyboard Commands"}
definition is incorrectly formed, or is not a valid command. Make sure the
command has correct parameters by consulting the
@{" TurboText Command Reference " link "TurboText Command Reference"}.

@endnode


@node "Invalid keyboard sequence"

A @{" keyboard sequence " link "Changing The Keyboard Commands"} was incorrectly formed in a @{b}KEYBOARD@{ub} or a @{b}HOT_KEYS@{ub}
section.

@endnode


@node "Invalid mouse sequence"

A non-existent @{" mouse sequence " link "Changing The Mouse Button Commands"} was given in a @{b}MOUSE_BUTTONS@{ub} section.
There are only six supported mouse sequences: DoubleLeft, DoubleMiddle,
LeftMiddle, LeftRight, MiddleLeft, and MiddleRight.

@endnode


@node "Unknown MENUS directive"

A non-existent menu directive was given in a @{" MENUS " link "Changing The Menus"} section. There are
only five supported menu commands: @{b}MENU@{ub}, @{b}ITEM@{ub}, @{b}SUB@{ub}, @{b}BAR@{ub}, and @{b}SBAR@{ub}.

@endnode


@node "Incorrect MENU specification"

A @{" MENU " link "Changing The Menus"} specification must be followed by the menu's name and nothing
else. For example:

	MENU " Project "

@endnode


@node "Incorrect ITEM specification"

An @{" ITEM " link "Changing The Menus"} specification must be followed by the item's name, followed by a
keyboard shortcut for the item, and the command associated with the item.
For example:

	ITEM "Open..." "O" OpenFile

@endnode


@node "Incorrect SUB specification"

A @{" SUB " link "Changing The Menus"} specification must be followed by the sub-item's name, followed by
a keyboard shortcut for the sub-item, and the command associated with the
sub-item. For example:

	SUB "Open..." "O" OpenFile

@endnode


@node "Invalid Hot Key command"

A command was specified for a hot key which is not one of TurboText's
@{" global commands " link "Global Commands"}.

@endnode


@node "Templates must start with a letter"

@{" Templates " link "Templates"} specified in the @{b}TEMPLATES@{ub} section must start with a letter,
and not with other characters.

@endnode


