@node "AmigaDOS Pattern Matching"

Pattern matching is a technique to specify a series of files as a group
rather than individually. So with a single command you can call up
numerous files without having to enter all their names. The pattern
matching technique described here is compatible with the standard AmigaDOS
pattern matching used in AmigaDOS commands.

Pattern matching capabilities come through the use of several special
characters to make a search pattern:

	?  #  |  %  (  )  [  ]  '  ~

(The third character is the vertical bar located to the left of the
@{b}[Backspace]@{ub} key on American keyboards.)

	?		Matches any single character

	#		Matches the following expression 0 or more times

	(ab|cd)		Matches any one of the expressions separated by "|"

	~		Negates the following expression

	[abc]		Character class, matches any of the characters in
			the class

	a-z		Character range (only within character classes)

	%		Matches 0 characters always (useful in expression
			such as @{b}(ab|cd|%)@{ub})

In the above table, @{i}expression @{ui}means either a single character such as @{b}?@{ub},
an alternation such as @{b}(ab|cd|ef)@{ub}, or a character class such as @{b}[abc]@{ub}. For
example: @{b}#?@{ub}, @{b}#(ab|cd|ef)@{ub} and @{b}~[abc]@{ub} are all expressions.

To remove the special effect of a pattern character, it must be preceded
by an apostrophe.

The best way to understand pattern matching is by studying a few examples:

	a?b		Matches anything 3 characters long starting with an
			@{i}a @{ui}and ending with a @{i}b. @{ui}Example matches include:
			aab, abb, azb, axb

	a#bc		Matches anything starting with an @{i}a@{ui}, ending with
			@{i}c @{ui}and with any number of @{i}b@{ui}s in the middle. Example
			matches include:  ac, abc, abbc, abbbc

	a(b|c)d		Matches anything starting with an @{i}a@{ui}, ending with a
			@{i}d @{ui}and with either a @{i}b @{ui}or a @{i}c @{ui}in the middle. Example
			matches include:  abd, acd

	abc#?		Matches anything starting with @{i}abc. @{ui}The pound or
			number sign @{b}#@{ub} followed by a character means "match
			any number of the following character". The question
			mark @{b}?@{ub} matches any single character. Combining @{b}#@{ub} and
			@{b}?@{ub} effectively means "match any sequence of
			characters". Example matches include: abc, abcxyz,
			abcabcjk

	#?xyz		Matches anything ending in @{i}xyz. @{ui}Example matches
			include:  xyz, abcxyz, xyzxyz

	#(ab)		Matches any number of repetitions of @{i}ab. @{ui}Example
			matches include:  ab, abab, ababab

	a(b|d|%)#c	Matches anything starting with the character @{i}a @{ui}which
			is also followed by either @{i}b@{ui}, @{i}d@{ui}, or nothing,
			followed by any number of @{i}c@{ui}s. Example matches
			include:  ad, ac, abc, adcc

	a[bcd]		Matches anything starting with @{i}a @{ui}which is followed
			by @{i}b@{ui}, @{i}c @{ui}or @{i}d. @{ui}Example matches include:  ab, ac, ad

	a~[bcd]		Matches anything starting with @{i}a @{ui}and @{b}not@{ub} followed
			by @{i}b@{ui}, @{i}c @{ui}or @{i}d. @{ui}Example matches include:  ae, az, aa

	~(#?c)		Matches anything not ending with @{i}c. @{ui}Example matches
			include:  a, abcdef, cccx

@endnode







