@node "Product History"

This section outlines the changes made to TurboText in its various
versions.

	@{" Changes In Version 1.03 (08-Jun-91) " link "Version 1.03"}
	@{" Changes In Version 2.0  (05-Sep-94) " link "Version 2.0"}

@endnode


@node "Version 1.03"

Screen updates and scrolling are now faster.

Moving through a document using the scroll gadget is now much faster.

The @{" ScrollView " link "ScrollView"} and @{" CenterView " link "CenterView"} commands now sometimes operate an order
of magnitude faster.

Clicking to the right of the scroll gadget within a document window
(basically on the right border of the window) no longer causes the display
to scroll to the right.

Paragraph formatting is now smarter. Spaces, tabs and blank lines at the
front of a paragraph are now skipped. This lets you invoke paragraph
formatting several times in a row to format a series of paragraphs.

The @{" Hex editing window " link "Editing Binary Files"} now has its internal font setting adjusted to
match that of the main document window. This lets utilities like SNAP be
able to read characters from the window.

Menu shortcut keys are no longer lost when entered in quick succession.

The end-of-line character (¶) is now correctly displayed when the
@{" Show End Of Lines " link "Preferences - Special Marks"} option is on and the @{" Tab Width " link "Preferences - Tabs"} setting is different
than 8.

There is no more "ghost" cursors left on the screen when either the
@{" OpenFile " link "OpenFile"} or @{" ClearFile " link "ClearFile"} commands are executed while the display lock is
turned on (@{" SetDisplayLock ON " link "SetDisplayLock"}).

Memory is no longer lost when the @{" GetDocuments " link "GetDocuments"} command is executed.

The screen is now updated after executing the @{" Conv2Tabs " link "Conv2Tabs"} command or the
@{" Conv2Spaces " link "Conv2Spaces"} command, which eliminates the chance of getting a stale
display when either the @{" Show Tabs As ° " link "Preferences - Special Marks"} or @{" Show Spaces As · " link "Preferences - Special Marks"} options
are on.

Memory is no longer lost when invoking the TTX program and passing it a
drawer as parameter.

Hiding a fold that contains shown folds now preserves the embedded shown
folds instead of unfolding them.

The @{" MACRO " link "Workbench Options"} and @{" SCREEN " link "Workbench Options"} icon Tool Types now work as documented.

Tool Types of icons dropped on the editor's @{" AppWindow " link "Loading An Existing File By Dropping Icons"} are now processed.

Backups now always have the @{b}D@{ub} (Delete) protection bit cleared when they are
created. If the file being backed up had the Delete bit set, then the
backup would also have it set, which would prevent future backup operations
from working.

Scrolling to the right when the display width is an exact multiple of the
current font's width is now possible.

Executing the @{" SaveMacro " link "SaveMacro"} command while the macro contains any of the
@{" SetPrefs " link "SetPrefs"}, @{" OpenRequester " link "OpenRequester"} or @{" CloseRequester " link "CloseRequester"} commands now creates a
correct output file.

Loading a @{" definition file " link "Definition Files"} containing a @{" MENUS " link "Changing The Menus"} section no longer
results in a system crash if there is insufficient memory to load and build
the menu strip.

Changing the @{" Display Type " link "Preferences - Window And Screen"} setting no longer sometimes results in a
system crash if there is insufficient memory to create a custom screen.

Attempting to load a document with lines longer than 32K no longer causes
a system crash. An out of memory error is generated instead.

Find operations no longer run the risk of entering infinite loops in
certain rare conditions.

The @{" MoveLeft " link "MoveLeft"} and @{" MoveRight " link "MoveRight"} commands now consistently produce an error
when attempting to move beyond the bounds of a document. There used to be
rare cases in which no error would be produced.

The @{" OpenPrefs " link "OpenPrefs"} command now correctly returns an error if the preferences
file cannot be loaded.

Opening a preferences file while in @{" split view mode " link "Multi-View Editing"} no longer runs the
risk of causing a confused display to be produced.

Clicking and releasing the left mouse button will now always cause the
text cursor to appear where the mouse was clicked. Previously, clicking
the mouse button too fast would cause the cursor to move in the direction
of the mouse click, but not quite make it.

Switching views by clicking the left mouse button in the desired view now
always switches the views.

The @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} display subtask now runs at the same priority as the
main editor task instead of always running at priority 0. This avoids
apparent slugishness when the editor's priority is greater than 0.

When automatically saving a file, the @{" Strip EOL Blanks " link "Preferences - End Of Lines"} option is now
turned off to prevent disrupting a document while it is being typed in.

The entry for main() in the TTX_C.dfn definition file has been corrected.

An extraneous @{" ClearFile " link "ClearFile"} command was removed from the GetRef ARexx macro.

The SortBlk, SaveBlk and PrintBlk @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros no longer cause the
cursor to be centered in the screen after they execute.

The Hanoi macro works a tad faster and looks better.

@endnode


@node "Version 2.0"

TurboText 2.0 offers many useful enhancements. This section lets users of
previous versions of the program quickly get familiar with the many new
features of version 2.0.

	@{" General Enhancements         " link "General Enhancements"}
	@{" Menus                        " link "Menus"}
	@{" AmigaDOS Release 3 Support   " link "AmigaDOS Release 3 Support"}
	@{" Startup Options              " link "Version 2.0 Startup Options"}
	@{" Performance                  " link "Performance"}
	@{" Commands                     " link "Commands"}
	@{" Macros And Definition FIles  " link "Macros And Definition Files"}
	@{" Bug Fixes                    " link "Bug Fixes"}

@endnode


@node "General Enhancements"

TurboText now requires Kickstart and Workbench release 2.04 or later for
correct operation.

TurboText now uses the standard system @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} instead of a
built-in proprietary file requester.

TurboText now uses the standard system screen mode requester to allow
selection of screen modes, or public screens. This enables the editor to
open screens of any mode instead of the previous 6 built-in modes, and to
easily pop an existing window to a different @{" public screen " link "Public Screens"}.

Each TurboText window can now be opened on separate public screens, in
addition to a single TurboText-created screen.

Each TurboText window can now have its own font, separate from what other
TurboText windows use.

Each TurboText window can now have its own menu, keyboard, and other
definitions.

TurboText now supports lines of up to 2 billion characters, instead of the
previous limit of 32000 characters.

TurboText windows now use an improved method for memory management. This
lets many more TurboText windows be opened simultaneously, and overlap one
another.

TurboText now sports context-sensitive on-line AmigaGuide help.

TurboText now features an ARexx macro cache, which enhances the performance
of ARexx macros considerably.

There is now a built-in mouse blanker. This feature can optionally be
enabled and automatically turns off the mouse pointer when you type.

The color of text within a document window can now be controlled.

Confirmation requesters now use system requesters instead of custom ones.
The text of the gadgets is now clearer as well, saying @{b}Open@{ub} or @{b}Save@{ub} instead
of simply @{b}OK@{ub}. In addition, many of the requesters have a third gadget
letting you save the current document before proceeding with the operation.
Finally, the name of the current document is now displayed in the title bar
of the requester.

Selecting a print operation from the menus now brings up a confirmation
requester before proceeding with printing. This lets you cancel incorrect
menu selections more easily.

TurboText can now be used for cross-platform editing, as it can load
Macintosh-style ASCII files, and it is able to save IBM-PC style ASCII
files and Macintosh ASCII files.

TurboText now has extensive support for variable tab sizes in files. This
is implemented by a series of conversion options that make it easy to
import and export files with different tab sizes.

It is now possible to click on a fold marker to expand the fold, and to
click on a fold line to hide the fold again.

Whenever TurboText is running, it adds a @{b}TurboText@{ub} item to the Workbench
@{b}Tools@{ub} menu. This lets you quickly and easily start a TurboText document
from Workbench.

Preferences options are now controlled by a unified @{" Preferences " link "The Preferences Requester"}
requester. Many new options exist to customize TurboText to a high degree.

The @{b}Do Patterns@{ub} gadget was added to the @{" Find " link "The Find Requester"} and @{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"}
requesters. Disabling this prevents wildcards from being used.

The text gadgets in the @{" Find " link "The Find Requester"} and @{" Find & Change" link "The Find & Change Requester"} now maintain a list of
the last several text strings used. When one of these text gadgets is
active, the @{b}[CursorUp]@{ub} and @{b}[CursorDown]@{ub} keys may be used to cycle through
the history of text strings.

Doing find and change operations from the @{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"} requester now
brings up a busy pointer in the main document window, and in the requester
window as well.

Status messages that appear as a result of selections in the
@{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"} requester are now displayed in the title bar of the Find &
Change requester in addition to the @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"} of the document window.

The @{b}Show End Of Document As @{ub} option is improved. The special
end-of-document character is now displayed on every line past the end of
the document instead of only on the first line passed the end.

The @{" Info " link "The Info Requester"} requester now shows the current date and time.

The default @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} console specification no longer has /AUTO in it. This
makes the command shell's close gadget work better. With /AUTO, the close
gadget would cause the console window to close, reopen, and close again.
Now it just closes, and doesn't make another peep.

Not specifying a /SCREEN setting in the @{b}ARexx Console Name@{ub} text gadget of
the @{" Miscellaneous " link "Preferences - Miscellaneous"} section of the preferences requester results in the
console opening on the same screen as the TurboText document that invoked
it.

@{" Read-only mode " link "Read-Only Mode"} is smarter than before. When you load a file which is
write-protected, the editor switches to read-only mode. If you then load a
file which is not write-protected, the editor switches back to read/write
mode. This behavior is overridden if you explicitly enter read-only mode.
In that case, the editor will stay in that mode until you explicitly turn
it off.

TurboText no longer uses a custom four-way pointer when in selection mode,
and instead changes the appearance of the text cursor.

The @{" status area " link "The TurboText Document Window"} is now rendered using the same font as the window title.

The date and comment of a file are now preserved when doing a backup. That
is, when a file is renamed or copied to its backup location, its
attributes now go with it.

Files can no longer be saved if the target file on disk is write-protected
or delete-protected. Previously, if backup creation was enabled, then it
was possible to save on top of such files.

When a document window is resized, the document is now scrolled towards
the left as much as possible. Previously, if the cursor was at the end of
a long line, and the document window was shrinked horizontally and
expanded again, you'd often see only the last few characters of the line.
The document is now scrolled to reveal as much of the current line as
possible to the left of the cursor position.

It is now possible to operate TurboText without having a window opened.
This is very useful to execute ARexx macros in the background.

TurboText can now automatically detect binary files when it loads a new
document, and adjust its preferences options in order to handle the file
correctly.

The case correction algorithm has been improved and is smarter about when
to perform, and to not perform, automatic case correction.

TurboText now preserves Tool Types it doesn't know about when it saves
icons.

@endnode


@node "Menus"

There is now a @{" Project/Insert... " link "The Project Menu"} menu command which lets you insert a
file from disk at the current cursor position.

There is now a @{" Project/Read Only " link "The Project Menu"} menu command which lets
@{" read-only mode " link "Read-Only Mode"} be turned on and off.

The @{" Windows " link "The Windows Menu"} menu was reorganized. It now contains additional items to
let you resize windows to their minimum and maximum sizes, to organize all
document windows on the current screen, to bring up an AmigaDOS Shell
window, and to bring up the TurboText on-line manual.

There is now a @{" Search/Go To Char #... " link "The Search Menu"} menu command which lets you move
the cursor to an absolute number of characters counting from the beginning
of the current document.

The @{" Search/Match Bracket " link "The Search Menu"} menu command now also matches the @{b}<@{ub} and @{b}>@{ub}
characters as well as the @{b}«@{ub} and @{b}»@{ub} characters.

There are now @{" Search/Set Bookmark " link "The Search Menu"} and @{" Search/Go To Bookmark " link "The Search Menu"} menu
commands. These contain sub-items to let you set and go to the first ten
TurboText @{" bookmarks " link "Bookmarks"}.

The layout of the @{" Folds " link "The Folds Menu"} menu was changed to reduce its size.

The @{" Prefs " link "The Prefs Menu"} menu no longer has the @{b}Display...@{ub}, @{b}Edit...@{ub}, and @{b}File...@{ub}
options, and instead has a single @{" Change... " link "The Prefs Menu"} option.

The main menu strip is now present even when the document window is
iconified.

Very tall menus defined in definition files are now automatically
columnized instead of being clipped to the bottom of the display.

@endnode


@node "AmigaDOS release 3 Support"

When running with AmigaDOS release 3 or greater, the system's busy pointer
is used instead of a custom one. This makes TurboText pick up changes made
to the busy pointer in Pointer preferences.

TurboText uses new look menus when possible. This makes the menus look
nicer.

You can now specify multi-character sequences as keyboard shortcuts for
menu selections. For example:

    ITEM "Send Mail" "F1" ExecARexxMacro "TurboText:Rexx/SendMail.ttx"

When a multi-character sequence is detected, no Amiga key glyph is put in
the menu, and the sequence is inserted in the menu strip and correctly
aligned to the right side.

TurboText now uses system pen definitions throughout. This makes TurboText
respect the release 3 Palette preferences pen settings.

@endnode


@node "Version 2.0 Startup Options"

Some changes and additions were made to the startup options understood
by TurboText on a shell command-line, or as an icon Tool Type.

The @{b}FILE/M@{ub} option was renamed to @{b}FILES/M@{ub}.

@{b}STARTUP@{ub} is now a synonym for the @{b}MACRO@{ub} option.

@{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} is now a synonym for the @{b}SCREEN@{ub} option.

The following startup options were added:

	WINDOW		- specify the window to use for the documents
	SETTINGS	- specify the preferences to use for the documents
	DEFINITIONS	- specify the definition file to use for the documents

The default preferences file was renamed from @{b}TTX_Startup.prf@{ub} to
@{b}TTX_Startup.prefs@{ub}. This is to match a bit more closely the system naming
convention for preferences files.

@endnode


@node "Performance"

TurboText 2.0 is generally much faster than previous versions at most
tasks. In particular:

Loading and saving documents is between 2 to 3 times faster.

Closing large documents is an order of magnitude faster.

Screen rendering and scrolling are quite a bit faster and take advantage
of many features of the Amiga Kickstart to improve performance, while
remaining compatible with third party graphics boards.

The @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} interface runs considerably faster due to internal
optimizations and the addition of the @{" ARexx macro cache " link "The ARexx Macro Cache"}.

@endnode


@node "Commands"

The following commands were added to the TurboText command interface:

	@{" ControlWindow   " link "ControlWindow"} - close or open a document window
	@{" FlushARexxCache " link "FlushARexxCache"} - empty the @{" ARexx macro cache " link "The ARexx Macro Cache"}
	@{" GetARexxCache   " link "GetARexxCache"} - get the state of the ARexx macro cache
	@{" GetBlk          " link "GetBlk"} - copy the current block to an ARexx stem variable
	@{" GetCursor       " link "GetCursor"} - get the state of the text cursor
	@{" GetMacroInfo    " link "GetMacroInfo"} - get information about the current macro
	@{" InsertFile      " link "InsertFile"} - insert a file in a document
	@{" MoveChar        " link "MoveChar"} - move to an absolute character in the document
	@{" MoveSizeWindow  " link "MoveSizeWindow"} - move and size a document window
	@{" RequestChoice   " link "RequestChoice"} - ask the user for a choice
	@{" SetARexxCache   " link "SetARexxCache"} - set the state of the ARexx macro cache
	@{" SetCursor       " link "SetCursor"} - turn the text cursor on or off
	@{" SwapViews       " link "SwapViews"} - exchange the contents of the top and bottom views
	@{" UsurpWindow     " link "UsurpWindow"} - steal the window of a document

The following commands have new options:

	@{" CloseRequester  " link "CloseRequester"} - PREFS/S
	@{" Conv2Spaces     " link "Conv2Spaces"} - SOL/S
	@{" Conv2Tabs       " link "Conv2Tabs"} - SOL/S
	@{" ExecARexxMacro  " link "ExecARexxMacro"} - LOCKINPUT/S,LOCKDISPLAY/S,NOCACHE/S
	@{" ExecARexxString " link "ExecARexxString"} - LOCKINPUT/S,LOCKDISPLAY/S
	@{" ExecTool        " link "ExecTool"} - ASYNC/S
	@{" GetErrorInfo    " link "GetErrorInfo"} - AMIGADOS/S
	@{" Help            " link "HelpNode"} - FILE/K,TOPIC
	@{" MarkBlk         " link "MarkBlk"} - WORD/S
	@{" MoveEOL         " link "MoveEOL"} - NONBLANK/S
	@{" MoveSOL         " link "MoveSOL"} - NONBLANK/S
	@{" OpenDefinitions " link "OpenDefinitions"} - USEDEFAULT/S,MAKEDEFAULT/S
	@{" OpenDoc         " link "OpenDoc"} - WINDOW/K,SETTINGS/K,DEFINITIONS/K,PUBSCREEN/K,WAIT/S
	@{" OpenPrefs       " link "OpenPrefs"} - USEDEFAULT/S,MAKEDEFAULT/S
	@{" OpenRequester   " link "OpenRequester"} - PREFS/S
	@{" PrintClip       " link "PrintClip"} - QUIET/S
	@{" PrintFile       " link "PrintFile"} - QUIET/S
	@{" RequestFile     " link "RequestFile"} - SAVEMODE/S,DRAWERSONLY/S
	@{" RequestNum      " link "RequestNum"} - POSITIVE/S,DEFAULT/N/K
	@{" SaveClip        " link "SaveClip"} - QUIET/S,APPEND/S
	@{" SaveFile        " link "SaveFile"} - QUIET/S,APPEND/S
	@{" SaveFileAs      " link "SaveFileAs"} - QUIET/S,APPEND/S
	@{" SaveMacro       " link "SaveMacro"} - QUIET/S
	@{" SavePrefs       " link "SavePrefs"} - QUIET/S
	@{" ShiftLeft       " link "ShiftLeft"} - COUNT/N,TABS/S
	@{" ShiftRight      " link "ShiftRight"} - COUNT/N,TABS/S
	@{" ToggleCharCase  " link "ToggleCharCase"} - FORCEUPPER/S,FORCELOWER/S

Many options were added to the @{" GetPrefs " link "GetPrefs"} and @{" SetPrefs " link "SetPrefs"} commands:

	AutoDeiconify		AutoDetectBinFiles	AutoEraseBlocks
	AutoTrackCursor		AutoWindow2Front	BackgroundColor
	BufferedWindow		CantBackupConfirm	ChunkyMode
	ConversionOnLoad	ConversionOnPrint	ConversionOnSave
	DoPatterns		DoubleLoadConfirm	DynamicMargin
	FontNameGadgets		FontSizeGadgets		LineWrap
	MouseBlanker		OverwriteConfirm	SaveEOLAs
	ScreenMode		ScreenName		ScrollGadget
	SelectWhenDragging	TabWidthDisk		TextColor
	ZoomGadget

The @{" ExecTool " link "ExecTool"} command now automatically locks the document input while it
is executing an external program. Starting @{" ExecTool " link "ExecTool"} with no tool
parameter will now bring up a @{" file requester " link "The File Requester"} instead of aborting with an
error. @{" ExecTool " link "ExecTool"} now understands special commands. If you specify %s in
the filename, it is replaced with the public screen name of the current
screen, and %p is replaced by the port name of the current document. That
is:

    ExecTool TTXCalc PUBSCREEN %s

will replace %s with the public screen name.

The @{" GetCursorPos " link "GetCursorPos"} command has an extra return value which specifies the
absolute number of characters from the beginning of the current document to
the current cursor position.

Any command argument expecting a number (/N keywords) can now accept hex
numbers as well. Just precede the numeric argument by @{b}$@{ub} or @{b}0x@{ub}. For example:

    Move $2b

would move the cursor to line 43

@endnode


@node "Macros And Definition Files"

All macros and definition files were updated to use as many new editor
features as possible.

It is now possible to distinguish between left and right qualifier keys
within a key sequence definition. LEFT_SHIFT, RIGHT_SHIFT, LEFT_ALT,
RIGHT_ALT, AMIGA, and RIGHT_AMIGA can now be used.

Definitions of menus can now include the name of an AmigaGuide document to
display when the user presses the @{b}[Help]@{ub} key while the menu is displayed.

It is now possible to bind any @{" global TurboText commands " link "Global Commands"} (commands that
can be sent to the TURBOTEXT port) to a @{" hot key " link "Hot Key Sequences"} sequence. You're no
longer limited to the five commands previously supported.

The following @{" definition files " link "Definition Files"} were added to the distribution:

	TTX_Interface_SASC.dfn
	TTX_Lang_Ada9X.dfn
	TTX_Lang_ARexx.dfn
	TTX_Lang_BASIC.dfn

The following @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macros were added to the distribution:

	ExecBlk
	InsertVersion
	OrganizeWindows
	SetDfn
	ShowAG
	StripMan
	UnsetLocks

The following macros were removed from the distribution:

	ChangeWindow
	CleanUp
	MoveByte
	OpenLayout
	PickFont
	SpeakLines
	WindowOrg

The @{b}TTX_Standard.dfn@{ub} definition file was renamed to @{b}TTX_BuiltIn.dfn@{ub} to
avoid confusion between @{b}TTX_Standard.dfn@{ub} and @{b}TTX_Startup.dfn@{ub}.

The SaveLayout macro is now much improved. It generates an ARexx
macro file that you run to recreate the same environment you had when
things were saved. As a result, the OpenLayout macro is no longer
included.

The Hanoi macro is now substantially faster.

More relationships were added to the GetKin macro, including C++ ones.

@endnode


@node "Bug Fixes"

All known bugs in previous versions of TurboText have been fixed in
TurboText 2.0. The main bugs fixed are listed below.

Ghost cursors were being left behind after opening a file while the display
lock was active in a document. Ghost cursors could also appear when
changing the fold spacing of a document through an @{" ARexx " link "TurboText And ARexx"} macro.

Menu items with "SetPrefs AutoIndent" attached to them would not correctly
display a checkmark next to them when the option was on.

Os with accents were incorrectly being treated like the letter P when doing
Find operations with the @{b}Ignore Letter Case@{ub} option turned on.

Initiating many editing operations while the cursor was beyond the end of
a line in free form mode would often result in the cursor being misplaced
within the document, which could cause all sorts of other problems.

Errors encountered while opening a document would often not be reported,
or would put some garbage characters in the status area instead of a real
error message.

Errors encountered when opening preferences, saving preferences, or
opening definition files would not always be reported correctly, and would
sometimes go unnoticed.

Errors encountered when executing the @{" GetFilePath " link "GetFilePath"}, @{" GetCurrentDir " link "GetCurrentDir"}, and
@{" SetCurrentDir " link "SetCurrentDir"} commands would not set the correct AmigaDOS error codes
for the errors.

Executing the @{" ToggleFold " link "ToggleFold"} command while there is no fold under the cursor
would not produce an error code.

Executing the @{" CorrectWordCase " link "CorrectWordCase"} command on a word not in the current
dictionary would not produce an error code.

Specifying a keyboard sequence of NP_ScrL in a KEYBOARD: section of a
@{" definition file " link "Definition Files"} would cause the editor to crash.

Changing the fold spacing would cause all TurboText windows to close and
reopen.

Shifting, centering, or justifying text could sometimes do strange things
to the text cursor if there were any tab characters in the line being
manipulated.

Performing find & change operations from the @{" Find & Change " link "The Find & Change Requester"} requester
would not always mark the right spot as the "last changed" location.

Several operations would behave incorrectly or cause crashes if executed
while the document window was iconified.

Showing spaces and tabs would sometimes cause garbage characters to be
displayed after saving documents while the @{b}Remove Trailing Spaces When
Saving@{ub} option was on.

Hiding all folds in a document would always position the text cursor at
the beginning of the current document. The cursor is now left as close as
possible to its original position.

Doing a vertical paste containing more than 256 characters would not
always work correctly, and linefeed characters could sometimes not be
inserted.

Pasting text vertically while the end of the paste operation exceeded the
end of the current document would not function correctly. The characters
would end up along the left edge of the display instead of being in their
proper column.

The @{" MoveNextTabStop " link "MoveNextTabStop"} command did not behave correctly when free form mode
was on, and attempting to move beyond the end of the current line.

Pressing @{b}[Esc]@{ub} could still abort a find operation even when the input lock
was set. As well, icons dropped on top of a document would still load the
file in the document even with the input lock enabled.

Sorting a whole document with the SortBlk ARexx macro would often lose
the first character of the document.

If a document window was just the right size, the font was just the right
size, and just the right sequence of characters were typed, then the text
cursor could end up in the border of the window.

Typing at the end of a document in overstrike mode would not overwrite the
last character and would instead insert text before the character.

The @{" hex window " link "Editing Binary Files"} would not always use the correct font for its rendering.

Modifying a line and quickly moving the cursor to a different line would
often not redraw the modified line on the screen to reflect the change.

Executing the @{" GetLine " link "GetLine"} command with the STARTCOL option would lose some
memory.

If the last line of a document had 6 characters or less, and all these
characters were deleted, without deleting the line itself, then 8 bytes of
memory was lost.

Making menu selections while any of the editor's requesters were up would
lose some memory.

Deleting a line that contained a hidden fold would lose some memory.

Hiding a fold, then marking a block starting on the fold and trying to
fold this block would result in an error message saying there is already a
fold on the current line. The block would remain apparently selected on
the screen, but the editor didn't think there was a block marked.

Having a split view document, and fold spacing greater than 0 would not
work quite right when resizing the views.

The document window's scroll bar would sometimes misrepresent the current
position within the document when deleting lines at the end of the
document.

Paragraph formatting didn't work correctly in all cases with very long
lines containing no spaces.

@endnode







