@node "Action Gadget"

Action Gadget:

Rectangular boxes in windows that allow commands to be issued by clicking
on them using the left mouse button.

@endnode


@node "AmigaDOS"

AmigaDOS:

The Disk Operating System (DOS) used by Amiga computers. AmigaDOS controls
the flow of information between the computer and the outside world.

@endnode


@node "Argument"

Argument:

See Parameter.

@endnode


@node "ARexx"

ARexx:

The Amiga version of the REXX programming language used by TurboText to
implement its macro capability. ARexx comes standard with most Amigas.

@endnode


@node "ASCII"

ASCII:

The American Standard Code for Information Interchange. A way of storing
characters in an electronic format.

@endnode


@node "Backup"

Backup:

A copy of a file or disk maintained in case the original is damaged.

@endnode


@node "Binary"

Binary:

A way of representing numbers using base 2 arithmetic.

@endnode


@node "Block"

Block:

A group of characters that have been selected to allow an operation to be
performed on all of the characters at once.

@endnode


@node "Bug"

Bug:

An error or problem in software or hardware.

@endnode


@node "Byte"

Byte:

The smallest computer storage unit. There are 1024 bytes in one Kilobyte.

@endnode


@node "Carriage Return"

Carriage Return:

An ASCII character indicating the end of a line.

@endnode


@node "Checkbox"

Checkbox:

A type of gadget allowing an option to be turned on or off.

@endnode


@node "Chip Memory"

Chip Memory:

The special region of the Amiga's memory accessible by the Amiga custom
chips to create graphics and sound.

@endnode


@node "CLI"

CLI:

See @{" Shell " link "Shell"}

@endnode


@node "Clicking"

Clicking:

The action of pressing and releasing the left mouse button.

@endnode


@node "Close Gadget"

Close Gadget:

The gadget in the upper left corner of a window. Clicking the mouse on
this gadget closes the window.

@endnode


@node "Command"

Command:

An action statement or order given to the Amiga, which can consist of
English-like statements or of menu selections.

@endnode


@node "Command Line"

Command Line:

A command and its parameters.

@endnode


@node "Current Directory"

Current Directory:

The currently selected directory.

@endnode


@node "Current Window"

Current Window:

The currently selected window. The current window (also referred to as the
active window) has its frame rendered differently from other windows (it
is either in a different color, or is solid while other windows are
ghosted). A window can be made the current window by clicking in it with
the left mouse button.

@endnode


@node "Cursor"

Cursor:

A small colored square indicating the current text insertion point within
an editor window or a text gadget. The next character typed is inserted at
the position occupied by the cursor, and the cursor is then moved to the
next position.

@endnode


@node "Cycle Gadget"

Cycle Gadget:

A gadget that cycles through different options when clicked on. The
currently selected option is always displayed in the gadget.

@endnode


@node "Decimal"

Decimal:

The standard way of representing numbers using base 10 arithmetic.

@endnode


@node "Default"

Default:

A value or action assumed by the editor if you do not specify otherwise.

@endnode


@node "To Delete"

Delete:

To erase characters, blocks or files.

@endnode


@node "Depth Gadget"

Depth Gadget:

Gadgets controlling the position of windows on the screen relative to
other windows.

@endnode


@node "Directory"

Directory:

A subdivision of disk storage. A directory can also be divided into
subdirectories. Synonym for Drawer.

@endnode


@node "Disk Drive"

Disk Drive:

A storage device that holds, spins, reads and writes magnetic or optical
disks.

@endnode


@node "Display Mode"

Display Mode:

The selected size and resolution of your display.

@endnode


@node "Double-Clicking"

Double-Clicking:

Rapidly pressing and releasing the left mouse button twice.

@endnode


@node "Dragging"

Dragging:

Moving the mouse while holding down the left mouse button.

@endnode


@node "Drawer"

Drawer:

A subdivision of disk storage. A drawer can contain other drawers. Synonym
for Directory.

@endnode


@node "Execute"

Execute:

To carry out the instructions in a program or command.

@endnode


@node "Fast Memory"

Fast Memory:

A region of the Amiga's memory not accessible to the chips responsible for
graphics and sound. This memory is generally accessed quicker than Chip
memory by the computer, thus the name.

@endnode


@node "Fatal"

Fatal:

A serious error condition causing termination of the current operation.

@endnode


@node "File"

File:

The way information is maintained on floppy and hard disks. Files have
names and are stored in a specific location on the disk.

@endnode


@node "Filename"

Filename:

The name of a file.

@endnode


@node "File Path"

File Path:

See @{" Path " link "Path"}.

@endnode


@node "Flag"

Flag:

A status indicator in a program. Flags can be either true or false.

@endnode


@node "Font"

Font:

Refers to the design characteristics (size, shape, etc..) of a set of
letters, numbers and symbols.

@endnode


@node "Function Key"

Function Key:

Key consisting of the letter F followed by a number, which can be
programmed to perform specific tasks.

@endnode


@node "Gadget"

Gadget:

A region in a window that can be controlled using the left mouse button,
allowing you to communicate with the computer.

@endnode


@node "Ghosting"

Ghosting:

Displaying a gadget or menu on the screen in a less distinctive way than
usual in order to indicate it cannot currently be selected.

@endnode


@node "Hard Disk"

Hard Disk:

A storage device that provides very large amounts of storage capacity.

@endnode


@node "Hexadecimal"

Hexadecimal:

A way of representing numbers using base 16 arithmetic.

@endnode


@node "Highlighting"

Highlighting:

Changing the color of an object on screen to indicate it is currently
selected.

@endnode


@node "Icon"

Icon:

A small graphical object representing a real-life object or action.

@endnode


@node "K"

K:

See @{" Kilobyte " link "Kilobyte"}.

@endnode


@node "Kilobyte"

Kilobyte:

The standard measurement unit for computer memory. There are 1024 bytes in
a Kilobyte, and there are 1024 Kilobytes in a Megabyte.

@endnode


@node "Linefeed"

Linefeed:

An ASCII character indicating the end of a line.

@endnode


@node "Loading"

Loading:

The fact of copying a file from external storage to main memory.

@endnode


@node "Macro"

Macro:

A way to group many commands into a single macro-command, which can be
executed directly.

@endnode


@node "Megabyte"

1024 @{" Kilobytes " link "Kilobyte"}.

@endnode


@node "Memory"

Memory:

A computer's work area. The size of the memory determines how many
applications can be running simultaneously in the computer, and the amount
of information that can be manipulated by these applications.

@endnode


@node "Menu"

Menu:

A list of the choices that can be selected in a program.

@endnode


@node "Menu Bar"

Menu Bar:

The list of menus that appears at the top of the display when holding down
the right mouse button.

@endnode


@node "Menu Button"

Menu Button:

The right mouse button.

@endnode


@node "Menu Item"

Menu Item:

A choice that appears in a menu.

@endnode


@node "Mouse"

Mouse:

The small palm-sized device used to control the pointer and communicate
with the computer.

@endnode


@node "Mouse Pointer"

Mouse Pointer:

See @{" Pointer " link "Pointer"}.

@endnode


@node "Multitasking"

Multitasking:

The ability of a computer to perform many tasks simultaneously.

@endnode


@node "Number Selection Gadget"

Number Selection Gadget:

A gadget allowing you to select a number within a given range of values.

@endnode


@node "Octal"

Octal:

A way of representing numbers using base 8 arithmetic.

@endnode


@node "Parameter"

Parameter:

Extra information provided to a command when invoking it. Synonym of
@{" Argument " link "Argument"}.

@endnode


@node "Path"

Path:

The route the Amiga must take to find a particular file on disk. The path
of a file usually includes the disk name and all of the directories and
subdirectories that lead to the file.

@endnode


@node "Pattern Matching"

Pattern Matching:

An AmigaDOS function that lets you specify file and directory names by
using patterns rather than specifying them individually.

@endnode


@node "Pixel"

Pixel:

PICture ELement. The dots of light that make up a computer's display.

@endnode


@node "Pointer"

Pointer:

An arrow that appears on the screen and moves as you move the mouse. The
pointer is used to select and control objects on the screen.

@endnode


@node "Preferences Options"

Preferences:

A set of options that allow the editor to be tailored to your taste.

@endnode


@node "Printer Driver"

Printer Driver:

A small program that translates printing requests from an application to a
language that can be understood by a printer. There are different printer
drivers for different printers.

@endnode


@node "Project"

Project:

A file where information created or used by a tool is stored.

@endnode


@node "Prompt"

Prompt:

A message or symbol displayed by an application indicating that it is
waiting for you to enter some information.

@endnode


@node "Protection Bits"

Protection Bits:

Software settings that determine whether a file can be read, written to,
deleted, etc...

@endnode


@node "RAM"

RAM:

Random Access Memory. The technical term for memory.

@endnode


@node "RAM Disk"

RAM Disk:

A simulation of a disk drive within memory.

@endnode


@node "RGB"

RGB:

Red Green Blue. Using varying intensities of these three colors, all other
colors can be produced by a video monitor.

@endnode


@node "ROM"

ROM:

Read-Only Memory. A special kind of memory used by computers to store
permanent information.

@endnode


@node "Requester"

Requester:

A special kind of window where an application asks for information.

@endnode


@node "Root Directory"

Root Directory:

The central, or main, directory on a disk. All directories of a disk are
created within the root directory.

@endnode


@node "Saving"

Saving:

The fact of copying a file from main memory to external storage.

@endnode


@node "Scrolling"

Scrolling:

Moving forwards or backwards through the text displayed in a window.

@endnode


@node "Scroll Bar"

Scroll Bar:

A rectangular box that can be selected with the left mouse button to
scroll through a document.

@endnode


@node "Selecting"

Selecting:

The process of choosing an option by positioning the mouse pointer over it
and clicking the left mouse button.

@endnode


@node "Selection Button"

Selection Button:

The left mouse button.

@endnode


@node "Shell"

Shell:

A simple program that lets you execute AmigaDOS commands using the
keyboard.

@endnode


@node "Shift-Clicking"

Shift-Clicking:

The process of clicking the left mouse button while holding down either
Shift key on the keyboard.

@endnode


@node "Sizing Gadget"

Sizing Gadget:

A gadget in the bottom right corner of certain windows that allows the
size of the window to be changed.

@endnode


@node "Slider Gadget"

Slider Gadget:

Allows you to select a value from a given range. Similar in concept to
number selection gadgets.

@endnode


@node "Startup-Sequence"

Startup-Sequence:

A series of AmigaDOS commands that gets executed automatically when the
computer is turned on.

@endnode


@node "String"

String:

A contiguous set of alphanumeric characters.

@endnode


@node "Subdirectory"

Subdirectory:

A subdivision of a directory.

@endnode


@node "Text Gadget"

Text Gadget:

A gadget in which text can be entered.

@endnode


@node "Title Bar"

Title Bar:

The area stretching across the top of a screen or window.

@endnode


@node "Tool"

Tool:

A software application, this is another name for a program.

@endnode


@node "Volume"

Volume:

Synonym for disk.

@endnode


@node "Wildcard"

Wildcard:

Symbol used to represent any value, typically used in filenames.

@endnode


@node "Workbench"

Workbench:

The Amiga's icon-based user-interface. Also refers to the screen on which
this interface functions.

@endnode


@node "Write Protect"

Write Protect:

Refers to the little tab on floppy disks that can be set to prevent stored
information from being written over.

@endnode
